<HEADLINE>
BACK SPASMS PUT OLSON ON DISABLED LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Embattled reliever  &UR; Gregg Olson was placed on the
disabled list before Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's sore lower back, the result of spasms two days earlier,
and slight lingering pain in his elbow, made the move a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of everything,'' Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter
said of Olson's ailments. ``The big thing was the 10 days we had
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Olson last pitched on June 22, his move was retroactive
10 days. He will be eligible to be activated July 8. However,
because of the three-day break for the All-Star Game July 12-14,
the club may decide to give Olson additional time to heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trainers told me there was a better than average chance
that I could have more spasms,'' Olson said. ``Once I heard that, I
agreed to the move. I thought it was a one-time thing, but they
said it could come back because the spasms were protecting
something else that could be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed reliever  &UR; Bobby Chouinard, recalled from Triple-A
Tucson for the third time this season, replaced Olson on the active
roster. He stepped onto the field during the third inning after
flying in from Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard, whose 4.06 ERA is the ninth-best mark in the Pacific
Coast League, pitched two scoreless innings on Saturday. &QL; 
Not close &QL; 
Right-handed pitcher  &UR; Casey Daigle, the Diamondbacks' second
overall pick in last month's draft, remains unsigned, and prospects
for closing the gap between what he wants as a signing bonus and
what the club is offering remain wide.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, unbeknownst to club officials, Daigle
retained  &UR; Scott Boras as an ``adviser,'' a slick term used by high
school players seeking an agent's help in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen minutes before the draft he decided he needed an
adviser,'' said General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Daigle was 11-2 with a 1.04 ERA and had 97 strikeouts in 69
innings at Sulpher High School in Louisiana. The club is offering
just over $1 million. Daigle, who has a full-scholarship offer to
pitch at Tulane University, is seeking more than $1.5 million, one
major league source said. &QL; 
Etc. &QL; 
For the second consecutive game,  &UR; Travis Lee gave way to  &UR; Greg
Colbrunn as the starting first baseman. With right-handed starters
due to pitch against Arizona the next five games, Lee will return
to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks are now 16-12 against left-handed starters and
28-25 against right-handers. They are 8-9 in day games and 36-28 in
night games.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis second baseman  &UR; Joe McEwing extended his hitting
streak to 24 games, the longest ever by a Cardinals rookie.
 &UR; Lou Brock had a 26-game streak in 1971. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
