<HEADLINE>
LA RUSSA GIVES HINTS HE MAY LEAVE CARDINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the game's most respected managers may be on his way out
in what might be the best baseball city in the country.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Manager  &UR; Tony La Russa, who entered the weekend series
tied for 12th on the all-time wins list with 1,602, is leaving a
trail of clues as to his future with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   La Russa, a three-time Manager of the Year during his time in
the American League, has a standing offer to sign a contract
extension with the club that will keep him as manager for at least
another two years.
</P>
<P>
   He refuses to sign it now, preferring to wait until after the
season to resume such talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I'd let them know after the season,'' said La
Russa, who has guided Oakland, the White Sox and St. Louis to the
postseason. ``The season is about the players, not the manager or
coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa entered the weekend series against the Diamondbacks
with a 282-282 record since taking over the Cardinals. Even though
he guided them to their lone playoff appearance in 1996 in the past
12 seasons, the locals never have taken a great liking to him.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, three locals have spent a good portion of their
time taking shots at La Russa.  &UR; Ozzie Smith, a part-time television
analyst for home Cardinals games, former St. Louis Manager  &UR; Whitey
Herzog and former center fielder  &UR; Andy Van Slyke have been vocal
opponents of La Russa.
</P>
<P>
   All three are held in high esteem in the St. Louis area, and
their words carry a lot of weight. So when La Russa said a few
weeks ago that he has ``powerful enemies'' around St. Louis, he's
not imagining things.
</P>
<P>
   By not signing his extension and putting an end to the talk, it
seems as if La Russa very well might leave after this season. A few
spots have been mentioned as possible destinations for La Russa
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay, La Russa's childhood home, has been mentioned, but it
seems virtually impossible to believe he would go to an
organization that seems nowhere close to competing for a title.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's north side is a possibility, especially if the Cubs
stumble in the second half and fire Manager  &UR; Jim Riggleman. Don't
forget, La Russa managed on the south side with the White Sox and
loves Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is Baltimore, where it seems impossible to
believe  &UR; Ray Miller will be back in 2000. Taking over the Orioles
job has its obstacles, notably an owner,  &UR; Peter Angelos, who loves
to meddle. However, La Russa's wife, Elaine, is from the Baltimore
area, and that might be enough to push the Orioles into serious
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   But deep down, La Russa always has been an American League man.
He staunchly defended it during his tenure in the AL. Either way,
don't be surprised if La Russa bolts from St. Louis. The signs all
point to it. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
Who are the four active major league players who made their debuts
during the 1970s? &QL; 
MVP? He has a strong case &QL; 
Some people wonder just how much  &UR; Manny Ramirez really matters to
Cleveland's high-flying offense. Well, the answer may have been
provided recently when Ramirez was forced to miss six games because
of a bruised left index finger after being hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, already a lock for the playoffs, lost four of the
six games, batting only .232 and scoring 25 runs collectively
without their main man in the middle of the lineup. Ramirez missed
three other games earlier because of a suspension. Cleveland is 3-6
and averages 4.6 runs per game without Ramirez. Their collective
batting average with Ramirez is an extremely healthy .303, and they
average 6.9 runs per game. Now that's an MVP. &QL; 
Numbers game &QL; 
Sometimes, the smallest, seemingly insignificant things in the
world can bother a player. And it's up to a manager to try to
soothe a player, hoping to get the most out of him. Florida Manager
 &UR; John Boles recently came across such a situation.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Marlins shortstop  &UR; Alex Gonzalez, one of the most
talented young players in the game, always has wanted to wear
uniform No. 13, the same number worn by fellow Venezuelans such as
 &UR; Luis Aparicio (later in his career),  &UR; Dave Concepcion,  &UR; Omar
Vizquel and  &UR; Ozzie Guillen (by the way, all shortstops).
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Boles wears No. 13. But Boles had no idea of
Gonzalez's aspirations for the number until a south Florida
reporter mentioned it to him. Boles quickly summoned Gonzalez into
his office and and offered to give him the shirt off his back.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who is wearing No. 11, politely declined and said that
he might take Boles up on the offer next year. Boles is thinking
about swapping numbers with Gonzalez during the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can have it whenever he wants it,'' said Boles, one of the
least assuming managers in the game. ``I'll even do the sewing
myself. Rip the name off it. He can have anything he wants as long
as he keeps playing like that. . . . He just has to wear my name on
(the jersey) for one game. Now batting second and playing shortstop
. . .  &UR; Alex
 &UR; Boles.'' &QL; 
Boo-hoo &QL; 
Texas outfielder  &UR; Juan Gonzalez, who has been American League MVP
two of the past three years, is feeling slighted by the fans in the
voting for the All-Star Game. Gonzalez, who is fifth among AL
outfielders, apparently will not travel to Boston for the game if
he is not a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is not fair,'' Gonza lez said. ``Players with great
seasons don't get to go, and players whose seasons aren't as good
get to go. I'd rather have the three days off to rest and get ready
for the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, truly a good guy, sometimes gets the worst advice from
people who have his ear. This seems to be another example of a
problem that has afflicted him throughout his career. &QL; 
More no-hit facts &QL; 
Before throwing his no-hitter against Arizona 10 days ago, St.
Louis right-hander  &UR; Jose Jimenez allowed five runs on 73 hits in
his previous 57 innings.
</P>
<P>
   He became the first Cardinals rookie to throw a no-hitter since
 &UR; Daffy Dean in 1934. Only two other Dominican-born pitchers had
thrown no-hitters:  &UR; Juan Marichal for San Francisco in 1963 and Los
Angeles'
 &UR; Ramon Martinez in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez's no-hitter was the first complete game thrown by a St.
Louis pitcher all season. In addition, the victory was the 1,600th
in La Russa's managerial career. The last 1-0 complete game
no-hitter occurred in 1977, when Cleveland's  &UR; Dennis Eckersley
accomplished the feat over the California Angels. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
Texas pitcher  &UR; Mike Morgan, who made his debut in 1978, was the
first of the active players to make his big league debut. The
following year,  &UR; Rickey Henderson broke in with Oakland,  &UR; Jesse
Orosco made his debut with the New York Mets and  &UR; Tim Raines played
in 19 games for Montreal. Four-decade players are rare. The last to
accomplish the feat was  &UR; Nolan Ryan. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; It must have been one heck of a ceremony: San Diego General
Manager  &UR; Kevin Towers presented former Padres pitcher  &UR; Kevin Brown,
who bolted town for the Dodgers' $105 million, with his National
League championship ring last week, handing him the box while Brown
was in the bullpen in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; This will probably, almost for sure, we can just
 &UR; about promise, be the last time you hear this tidbit: The Phillies,
in describing shortstop  &UR; Desi Relaford's recent wrist surgery sent
out an announcement that partly read it was ``definitely
potentially season-ending.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Mario Soto.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; News the rest of the NL does not want to hear:  &UR; Tom
 &UR; Glavine and  &UR; Greg Maddux, who have combined for six Cy Young
Awards, were 6-3 with a 3.06 ERA during June, dispelling talk that
the two of them are through. The two were 7-9 with a 4.77 ERA the
first two months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Here's a silver lining all Cubs fans can cling to: Chicago
finished June in a swoon, going 10-17 in the month. The only other
losing month the Cubs have had in the past two seasons was June
last year, when they were 12-15 despite benefiting from  &UR; Sammy
Sosa's 20 home runs. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorado superstar  &UR; Larry Walker, who is batting .386, is
attempting to become the first player since Hall of Famer  &UR; Al
Simmons (1929-31) to hit at least .360 three consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay played its final games of the season in Boston,
meaning Devil Rays third baseman  &UR; Wade Boggs, who collected 2,098
of his 2,971 career hits (entering the weekend series) for the Red
Sox, may have made his final visit to Fenway Park as a player.
Boggs' status for 2000 is very much up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Since Philadelphia right fielder  &UR; Bobby Abreau was moved from
sixth in the lineup to third, he is batting just .222. Abreau, one
of the brightest up-and-coming players in the game, was hitting
.360 before the switch was made.
</P>
<P>
   Former Kansas City All-Star second baseman  &UR; Frank
 &UR; White, who was never ejected in 2,324 career games over 18 seasons,
was finally booted last Monday by umpire  &UR; Darryl Cousins, who
objected after White said, ``( &UR; Mike Sweeney) has busted his butt
running 90 feet. It's not too much to ask for you to bust your butt
to run 10 feet to get in position to make the call.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota can, after all, keep its 1999 payroll at $16.2
million, which ranks 29th of the 30 clubs. Twins owner  &UR; Carl
 &UR; Pohlad gave the go-ahead to GM  &UR; Terry Ryan to splurge and keep the
payroll at its current amount instead of the $11 million figure he
mandated during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, which easily has the best record in the majors, has
only had its everyday eight starters and designated hitter in the
starting lineup nine times this season.
</P>
<P>
   Houston submitted a formal bid to host the 2004 All-Star Game at
its new Enron Field, which will open next spring. The Astros may
have trouble hosting that year since either Arizona or Milwaukee,
whichever doesn't host the 2002 game, will probably get the nod in
2004. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It appears that San Diego's  &UR; Bruce Bochy, who will manage the NL
All-Star team, is leaning toward taking  &UR; John Smoltz as his only
Atlanta pitcher. If Smoltz, who has been bothered by stiffness in
his elbow, cannot make it, then no Braves pitcher will make the
squad.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's  &UR; Dwight Gooden, who has won just two of his past 16
starts, may be on his way out of the Indians' plans altogether.
Cleveland picked up pitcher  &UR; Tom Candiotti last week and may give
him Gooden's spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs third baseman  &UR; Gary Gaetti, who has pretty much
been banished to the bench and limited duty, may be considering
retirement, especially after not starting against a left-handed
starter Wednesday. Gaetti, who is batting .184, started at third
Saturday and got noticed, not for his 1-for-4 day at the plate but
instead for his work on the mound in the eighth inning as the Cubs'
seventh pitcher of the day in a 21-8 loss to the Phillies. He got
three outs but gave up a homer and triple.
</P>
<P>
   For any Dodgers fans out there thinking a trade will fix Los
Angeles' woes, take a look at their roster and there's really only
one player who has much trade value, first baseman  &UR; Eric Karros.
Problem is, he's the only Dodger who seems to care about winning.
The contracts of  &UR; Raul Mondesi,  &UR; Gary Sheffield,  &UR; Eric Young,
 &UR; Devon White,
 &UR; Kevin Brown and  &UR; Carlos Perez make them virtually untradable.
</P>
<P>
   Houston may be in the market to listen to serious offers for
pitcher  &UR; Sean Bergman, whom the Astros believe they can replace
with the heralded  &UR; Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   During off-season meetings, Philadelphia GM  &UR; Ed Wade plans to
bring up the alarming number of hitters who continue to expand the
arsenal of protective gear they wear at the plate. It's a subject
that has come up in many other front offices and should have the
backing from the majority of his peers. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. ClevelandIndians are actually human; they allowed 10 runs in one
inning to KC.  &QL; 
2. NY Yankees &UR; Chuck Knoblauch, meet  &UR; Steve Sax. You two have a lot
in common.  &QL; 
3. BostonLike him or not, GM  &UR; Dan Duquette has delivered a winner
in Beantown.  &QL; 
4. AtlantaTwo blown saves to Montreal? Suddenly, the bullpen is
struggling.  &QL; 
5. CincinnatiBelieve it, SS  &UR; Barry Larkin may be playing better
than ever.  &QL; 
6. San FranciscoThe magic of  &UR; Dusty Baker is unleashed once again.
 &QL; 
7. Houston &UR; Jeff Bagwell passed  &UR; Cesar Cedeno for the club record in
doubles.  &QL; 
8. NY MetsSince the firing of three coaches, the Mets were 18-6
entering weekend.  &QL; 
9. TexasA tough June stretch that included 20 road games, and still
gained. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. FloridaPlayed the 1,000th game in its history Wednesday, a rare
win.  &QL; 
29. MinnesotaPitcher  &UR; Brad Radke's groin is aching. Is there an
All-Star left here?  &QL; 
28. BaltimoreOh, what a difference a week _ and tougher opponents _
makes.  &QL; 
27. Tampa BayInfielders are complaining about the turf and sand
combo at Tropicana.  &QL; 
26. DetroitTigers suffered their major league-leading 10th shutout
last week.  &QL; 
25. Los AngelesThe 8-17 June was the third-worst month since
leaving Brooklyn.  &QL; 
24. MontrealSurprisingly, these Expos are playing spunky lately.  &QL; 
23. ColoradoRockies are trying their hand with a four-man rotation.
 &QL; 
22. AnaheimOF  &UR; Tim Salmon has started the slow climb back to the
lineup. ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; San Diego Padres: The club with the longest winning streak since
1994 is on fire. The Padres had their 14-game winning streak
snapped Saturday and are at the .500 mark. Most amazing, the Padres
trailed in only six innings during the streak. They gained 9{ games
on first place during the push. Incredibly, San Diego had not won
more than two in a row before it ripped off the winning streak.
Just as important to the Padres, they won six in a row over the
hated Dodgers during a nine-day span. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Diamondbacks: After spending more than a month alone in first
place, Arizona fell from the top spot after being swept in
Cincinnati last week. The club's offense has been sputtering in the
worst way, managing only five runs in the sweep, including getting
no-hit and one-hit in a six-day span. The rotation remains solid
but has received little help from the stumbling offense. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Philadelphia Manager  &UR; Terry Francona, after Phillies center fielder
 &UR; Doug Glanville was not given a hit by the official scorer in
Pittsburgh after Glanville hit a sharp bouncer back to the pitcher
that hit off Pirates pitcher  &UR; Kris Benson's foot: ``That's an error
when a 100-pound pig jumps out of my ear.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
Toronto's  &UR; Billy Koch hadn't relieved much before this season, but
once Blue Jays Manager  &UR; Jim Fregosi gave the right-hander a shot at
the end of May, he hasn't looked back, or bad, since. Koch, who
used to possess a 100-mph fastball, has seen it drop to somewhere
in the mid-90s since an arm injury. Koch has emerged as the
Toronto's most reliable reliever, closing out 10 saves in 12
chances. He entered the weekend series with a 1.52 ERA and had
struck out 26 batters in 29 innings. In short, Koch appears to be
here for good. &QL; 
