<HEADLINE>
MERCURY TAKES HEART IN LOSS  
 MILLER EAGER DESPITE RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ In the ashes of a third consecutive loss,
franchise-low 27.4 percent shooting, a 2-5 road trip and a dip to
last in the WNBA Western Conference, the Mercury might have found
an identity Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   As impossible as it seems, a 56-47 loss to the expansion
Minnesota Lynx (5-4) might have been a more complete effort than
that in any of the Phoenix (3-7) victories.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mercury, 6{ games behind West leader Houston and 3{ out
of playoff position, returns to America West Arena for 14 of its
final 22 games still believing it can reach the postseason for a
third straight season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's time to go home and get that home crowd and hopefully
some home calls and everything else,'' Coach Cheryl Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be one thing (to be 3-7) if everybody in the league
had the type of schedule we had early on. But everybody else has to
come the same route we did in the middle and late in the season.
I'd rather take my hits early, right this ship and play our best
basketball down the stretch than to sit up there, play great and
fall apart at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   With even a tad better shooting _ Phoenix was 2-for-19 from
3-point range _ the Mercury would have completed its comeback from
a 34-20 deficit in the final 17:40 to hand the Lynx a fourth
straight home loss.
</P>
<P>
   But the first four times its lead was trimmed to three,
Minnesota had an answer: Andrea Lloyd-Curry driving layup when it
was 36-33; Tonya Edwards layup at 38-35; Edwards 14-footer at
42-39; and Lloyd-Curry layup at 44-41.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Mercury kept coming, and off a Bridget Pettis free
throw at 58.4 seconds was within 50-47. This time there was a
defensive stop _ on a miss by Edwards _ and Jennifer Gillom
rebound. Phoenix raced down court as a nervous 9,560 at the Target
Center saw visions of Thursday's double-overtime loss to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than setting up the offense with 25 seconds left, Edna
Campbell popped a straight-away three-point miss that left her
1-for-14 overall and 0-for-6 on treys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have set something up,'' said Miller,
who had a 20-second and a full timeout remaining. ``But I'd bet
Reggie's house that she'd make that next one. I'd take that shot
any day in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury was without its second-leading scorer, Clarissa
Davis-Wrightsil, due to back spasms, but Gillom did heat up in the
second half to finish with 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just shooting like (expletive),'' Campbell said.
``Shooting is pretty much a confidence thing. I don't think I'm
feeling it right now. I'm hesitating on my shot a lot. I get it and
then shoot, it's like an afterthought. When I catch it and shoot
and I'm confident about it, I can count it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you hope the numbers catch up with you,'' she said
of the crunch-time attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The Lynx were 6-for-6 on free throws after Campbell's miss, with
Michele Timms and 6-foot-8 Maria Stepanova not connecting on an
inbounds lob after the first pair to snuff the final Mercury hope.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mercury Brandy Reed was the scoring (14) and rebounding
(8) leader for Minnesota, which had its own shooting woes (33.3
percent) and was outboarded, 43-35.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it (the win) is real important,'' Lynx Coach Brian
Agler said. ``Later in August, we'll sit back and say it was very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury might say the same if, in another loss, it found the
character to keep fighting. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
