<HEADLINE>
ROAD HAS BEEN LONG FOR U.S. STAR CHASTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ This is where it all began for Brandi
Chastain, on the youth soccer fields in the south San Francisco Bay
area.
</P>
<P>
   On the Quaketts, her first team, at 8 years old. On the
Horizons, coached by her dad, Roger, in the early 1970s. Later, on
the Santa Clara University side, where she met her future husband,
Coach Jerry Smith.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems only fitting that Chastain should achieve a career
milestone in her own back yard.
</P>
<P>
   When the U.S. national team defender takes the field for today's
Women's World Cup semifinal match against Brazil, she will make her
100th international appearance. Only 10 American players have done
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it will be quite a special day,'' Chastain said of
reaching the coveted mark in front of her family and friends just
up Interstate 101 at Stanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the journey to this point was anything but smooth for the
30-year-old San Jose native. After being selected ``Soccer
America's'' Freshman of the Year in 1986, Chastain suffered a torn
anterior cruciate ligament. Two years later, she joined the
national team, only to again undergo reconstructive knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain overcame the injuries, but more heartache was to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain rejoined the national team in time to play in the 1991
World Cup and thought she was on her way to earning a starting
berth. Then one day _ without warning, she says _ Coach Anson
Dorrance decided to drop her from the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough time,'' Chastain said. ``The national team had
been so much a part of my life. Then, without any notice, it
suddenly wasn't there for me anymore. I was devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain played two seasons in Japan but longed to return to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   She kept in contact with new Coach Tony DiCicco. Finally, after
the 1995 World Cup, DiCicco invited Chastain to train for the '96
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one catch _ she wasn't going to play forward, the
position she had handled since her youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't care,'' Chastain said. ``I told them I just wanted to
be a part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been a major part of it ever since. And now, 11
tumultuous years later, she is on the verge of her 100th cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say, it's quite an accomplishment for me,'' Chastain
said, with only a hint of irony in her voice, ``because of my
absence from the team and because it's a different time now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the younger players on this team, and I see them
getting the valuable playing time and experience that I never had
when I was younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm happy. It's been a great run.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain has had an interesting run this summer. She joked with
David Letterman on the ``Late Show'' and posed for a provocative
photo in ``Gear'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, she has assisted on two goals _ including a header
pass to Cindy Parlow. Chastain also notched her first goal of the
Cup in the quarterfinals against Germany, but only after she scored
an own-goal in the fifth minute of the match.
</P>
<P>
   But Chastain's value to the team is on defense, where she has
played left, right and central. She even had a few minutes at
defensive midfield against North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gives us so much versatility,'' DiCicco said. ``She's
playing well, but the truth is her best soccer is still ahead of
her in this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain's biggest test likely will come today, when she and her
teammates take on Brazil's Sissi, the tournament's leading scorer
with seven goals. Assistant coach Lauren Gregg knows Chastain will
be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brandi is one of our most sophisticated players,'' Gregg said.
``She studies games, all games, and watches players intently. She
is very good both technically and tactically on defense, plus her
ability to attack out of the back makes her a dangerous player.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain said she is ``having a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just enjoy being on the field,'' she said. ``It's been
beautiful. I've enjoyed every minute of it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
