<HEADLINE>
REED STARTING TO FIND RHYTHM WITH LYNX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _  &UR; Brandy Reed said she knew through her agent that
she would not be among the Mercury's six protected players for the
WNBA expansion draft three months ago, so she is not surprised to
be with the Minnesota Lynx.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't upset,'' Reed said. ``I was just sort of surprised.
I'm going to Minnesota, a different team, a different organization,
a different setting. It's still basketball, you still have to go
out there and play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out I was (the first expansion pick), that was an
honor, respectful. I just appreciated that.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1 forward, Phoenix's third-round 1998 draft pick, was
the Lynx's leading scorer for the fourth time in a 56-47 win
Saturday. She also had a team-high eight rebounds in an athletic
performance that would have been familiar to Mercury fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just beginning to find my offensive rhythm, and that is
one of my strengths,'' said Reed, averaging 14.8 points and among
the top 15 in league scoring. ``I'm just trying to continue my
offensive game as much as I can and at the same time develop my
defensive skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed is doing enough on defense to satisfy Coach  &UR; Brian Agler,
who otherwise is starting all players from his Columbus Quest
championship ABL team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brandy keeps getting better and better,'' Agler said of the
22-year-old. ``She has a world of potential and has a chance to be
a great player.'' &QL; 
More of Mapp &QL; 
The latest of still rare WNBA trades means that the Mercury will
play seven times against  &UR; Rhonda Mapp this season, including
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-2 Mapp now is with the Houston Comets, who play the first
of four games against Phoenix on Friday. In one of her final games
for Charlotte on June 24, Mapp had nine points in the Sting's 88-72
rout of the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries to  &UR; Monica Lamb (eye surgery) and  &UR; Tammy
 &UR; Jackson (knee) and the absence of  &UR; Natalia Zasulskaya because of
her mother's illness, the Comets needed a backup for center  &UR; Polina
 &UR; Tzekova. They gave up 6-7  &UR; Kara Wolters, on the injured list since
June 21 because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to go out and find an experienced player . . . who
could come in here and help us during this stretch right now,''
Comets Coach/General Manager  &UR; Van Chancellor told the ``Houston
Chronicle''. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
