<SLUG> BC-BOX-CARBAJAL-COMEBACK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARBAJAL'S HEART, FIST HEAVY IN FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Michael Carbajal had more than just himself and the
resumption of his boxing career as motivation for a workmanlike
victory Friday night at the Tucson Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   He had a promise to keep.
</P>
<P>
   A memory to honor.
</P>
<P>
   His father-in-law, Billy Martinez, 61, died of cancer late
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight was dedicated to him,'' Carbajal said of his
fourth-round technical knockout of an overmatched Oscar Calzada.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix fighter (48-4, 32 knockouts) returned to the Valley
late Thursday to be with his wife, Merci, Martinez's daughter. He
returned to Tucson at about 6 a.m. Friday. If the death in his
family was a distraction, it wasn't evident.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the ring as though he were stepping into an office.
He stopped Calzada (14-8-2) in the businesslike, efficient manner
that marked his career through the days when he was among the
world's best, regardless of weight. Those days are gone.
</P>
<P>
   In his comeback, Carbajal is a different fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as fast,'' Carbajal said as he compared himself to the
fighter he was in 1993 when he dominated the junior flyweight
(108-pound) division. ``But I'm as strong as I ever was. My punches
are more precise.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how the Carbajal of today would fare against the
fierce warrior who six years ago became the lightest fighter in
history ever to collect a $1 million purse, he replied, ``It would
be a draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever physical skill has been lost through time seems to have
been offset by an evident sense of maturity and self-assurance in
Carbajal, who turns 32 in September. During the two to three years
before his 18-month retirement, he was embroiled in problems
outside of the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he had said the trouble was not a distraction. But in
retrospect, Carbajal concedes that it was.
</P>
<P>
   It is anybody's guess as to whether relative peace outside of
the ropes will result in a better fighter within them.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a mistake to make too much of the victory against
Calzada, who has lost five of his past six fights. Nine years ago,
Carbajal stopped him within three rounds in the first of many
defenses of the International Boxing Federation's junior flyweight
title.
</P>
<P>
   In the rematch before a Tucson crowd of nearly 5,000, Carbajal
employed withering body shots to knock Calzada to his knees twice,
once in the second round and again in the third. A looping right
uppercut at 2:01 of the fourth finished it as Calzada absorbed the
blow and staggered across the ring like a kid trying to run across
a trampoline.
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal took a few glancing blows from a game Calzada in the
second and again in the third. But he left the ring unmarked and
with a very predictable victory.
</P>
<P>
   The next step in his comeback doesn't figure to be so certain.
He has agreed to challenge Mexican Jorge Arce (20-2-1) for the
World Boxing Organization's 108-pound title on July 31 in Tijuana,
a card that will feature unbeaten super bantamweight Erik Morales.
</P>
<P>
   For Carbajal, the bout is dangerous. He will be fighting in
front of a rabid Mexican crowd. As the Mexican-American, the odds
will be stacked against him.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time he has been in that situation. He lost
two rematches by controversial split and majority decisions to
rival Humberto Gonzalez in front of Mexican-dominated crowds in Los
Angeles and Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   At Tijuana, his brother, trainer and manager, Danny Carbajal, is
expected to demand that at least one and perhaps two of the
ringside judges be from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Without that assurance written into the contract, Carbajal would
be foolish to take the fight. And even then, he would face a
daunting challenge, especially if Arce borrows Gonzalez's elusive
tactics and runs from Carbajal's undiminished power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to knock him out,'' said Carbajal, whose comeback
goal is to win a major title at a heavier weight, 112. ``I will
knock him out.''
</P>
<P>
   For a businessman in an unforgiving profession, there are no
other options. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
