<HEADLINE>
LACK OF RAIN COULD MAKE FOR SPARSE QUAIL HUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Ron Engel-Wilson cringes when he's asked for
predictions on this year's quail season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making any predictions,'' said Engel-Wilson, the
Arizona Game and Fish Department's small game biologist. ``People
hold me to them. I get into too much trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he did it anyway _ conditionally.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this extremely dry year, he said, things don't look
too bright for Gambel and scaled quail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, hunters killed about 750,000 quail,'' he said.
``This coming season, it probably will be more like half a
million.''
</P>
<P>
   That means breeding season wasn't too successful. To make great
things happen, rain needs to fall late in the year, and more should
follow in February and March. That causes green plants to grow,
stimulating egg production in females that eat the plants.
</P>
<P>
   The rain also produces insects that chicks eat for important
protein.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Arizona got moisture in late spring, but it was too
little and too late in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Mearns quail, which hold in tight coveys and are considered to
be trophies among hunters with pointing dogs, are different.
</P>
<P>
   These birds, which dwell only in the southeastern part of the
state, rely on summer monsoon rain to spur their reproduction.
That's why the Mearns season opens much later than that for Gambel
or scaled quail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good monsoon rain in the southeast would really help the
Mearns,'' Engel-Wilson said. ``It also would be of some help to
Gambel and scaled quail.''
</P>
<P>
   He said last year was a great season for Mearns quail. More than
15,000 were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we're going to have a good season, we must have the
summer rain,'' Engel-Wilson said. &QL; 
Ferrets booming &QL; 
The endangered black-footed fer ret, one of the rarest mammals in
the world, was reintroduced to Arizona in 1996. And it appears the
animals have every intention of making it this time.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen of 17 gave birth to 63 kits this year at the
reintroduction site in Aubrey Valley near Seligman, in the
northwestern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Together with the ferret breeding program at the Phoenix Zoo,
100 ferrets were born in Arizona this spring.
</P>
<P>
   That's an amazing number, a success rate of 93 percent compared
with 63 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ferrets will be released into the Aubrey Valley
site. As many as 30 will be held for breeding next year. Arizona
will receive 20 additional kits from the national captive breeding
program later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Adult females have been released from their breeding boxes and
have taken their kits into underground burrows, where temperatures
are much more suitable.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrets prey primarily on prairie dogs at night.
</P>
<P>
   They have been reintroduced in Wyoming, Montana and South
Dakota. There are plans for reintroductions in Colorado and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish still is looking for volunteers for spotlighting
surveys of the ferrets through September. Those interested can call
biologist Richard Winstead at (520) 692-7700. &QL; 
Bears getting worse &QL; 
Dry conditions are causing more contact by wild animals with
humans. Bears are the biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
   Wildfires, most of them small, are increasing the problem by
driving wildlife away from their territory.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish officials are extremely concerned because some
people put out food and water for the animals or leave their trash
unprotected. That invites trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents and visitors at Portal in southeastern Arizona at
the foot of the Chiricahua Mountains had been feeding wildlife
intentionally. Wildlife officers were forced to kill a black bear
because it had lost all fear of humans.
</P>
<P>
   A bear in the Globe area killed a domestic goat. When wildlife
officers approached it, the bear showed aggression and was killed.
</P>
<P>
   A mountain lion in the Sierra Vista area had been killing
chickens and was found sitting on the front porch of residence.
</P>
<P>
   During Memorial Day weekend, a young bear had to be killed after
it became addicted to trash left out along Tonto Creek. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at (602) 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
