<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEGAWA GETS SECOND SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Shigetoshi Hasegawa will make his first major-league
start since Sept. 27, 1997, when he takes Ken Hill's spot against
the Seattle Mariners on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa was a starter in Japan for six years before coming to
the U.S. to pitch for the Angels in 1997, but he made only seven
starts before the Angels put him in the bullpen. But it hasn't been
so long that he has forgotten what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first pitcher, right?'' Hasegawa joked.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa struggled as a starter with the Angels, going 0-3 with
a 6.62 ERA in those seven starts. But he said he's learned a lot
since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed more control,'' he said. ``Now I think I have a
little better control, a good fastball and changeup. Starting and
relieving is the same _ just don't think too much. Take it pitch by
pitch, hitter by hitter. The team situation is a little tough now
with Ken Hill and Tim Belcher hurt. I want to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins said he picked Hasegawa over Mark
Petkovsek and Scott Schoeneweis because of Hasegawa's success
against the Mariners in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Going into this season, Hasegawa had a 1.10 ERA vs. Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn ready: Jarrod Washburn joined the Angels on Saturday
and might start Tuesday's game against Seattle if he isn't called
out of the bullpen before then.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a tough season for Washburn, considering he spent more
than half of last year in the big leagues with the Angels. This
year, he's been in the minors all year and spent seven weeks on the
disabled list with a muscle strain on his right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got beat out in spring training _ I understand that,'' said
Washburn, who was 4-2 last year with the Angels but is 0-4 with
Triple-A Edmonton this year. ``But the injury part was killing me.
Being on the DL drove me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie steps up: Bret Hemphill got his first career major-league
start Saturday, serving as Chuck Finley's catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up watching him pitch and now I'm going to catch him,''
Hemphill, who was born in Lakewood and attended Cal State
Fullerton, said before the game.
</P>
<P>
   If Hemphill had any nerves going into the game, they weren't
calmed by bullpen catcher Mick Billmeyer, who told Hemphill
jokingly, ``I don't want to put any pressure on you, but we're all
counting on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemphill tied a major-league record earlier in the week when he
got hits from both sides of the plate in his first two major-league
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Knuckleball rules: Catcher Steve Decker said he thinks there
should be a new scoring rule in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there's a knuckleball pitcher and the ball gets by
the catcher, it should be ruled a wild pitch,'' Decker said.
</P>
<P>
   Decker has a good case. He was charged with two passed balls in
Friday's game trying to catch knuckleballer Steve Sparks. On one of
them, Decker held his glove up but at the last moment the ball
moved and hit him square in the forehead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
