r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-     07-04 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS COLLAPSE AFTER 7-RUN LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers didn't win the American League
West without reinforcements after the July 31 trading deadline a
year ago. They might again require reinforcements for the final two
months if seven-run leads disappear into The Ballpark in
Arlington's humid air as happened last night in a 13-12 loss to the
Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle right-hander Freddy Garcia gift-wrapped and presented
the Rangers an eight-game advantage in the AL West. The Rangers,
though, turned their noses and matched their club record by
surrendering a seven-run lead in defeat while the Mariners are now
only six games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners third baseman Russ Davis delivered the crushing blow
with his three-run, seventh-inning homer off right-hander Tim
Crabtree (4-1). Thus, the Rangers wasted four runs batted in by
right fielder Juan Gonzalez, who matched a major-league record with
three sacrifice flies, and another three RBI from designated hitter
Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is guaranteed, but if you get a chance to put some
space between you and a good team like that over there, you want to
take advantage of that,'' Rangers shortstop Royce Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers right-hander Aaron Sele went to the mound for his fifth
inning of work as the beneficiary of a 9-2 lead that soon would
vanish. Mariners center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. delivered a
three-run double, and first baseman David Segui supplied a one-out
sacrifice fly ball that left the visitors trailing by three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates said of Sele's not being able to
protect the seven-run lead: ``I'll take Sele with a seven-run lead
most nights. Tonight was one of those nights we just didn't do a
good job pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were still going to win that ballgame. Even when
we fell behind 12-9. We got the tying run on base in the ninth. We
just weren't able to finish it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Danny Patterson inherited what little remained of
the Rangers' once-imposing advantage, but it disappeared before the
completion of the sixth inning. Davis reached after being hit by
one of Patterson's deliveries, and left fielder Brian Hunter and
second baseman David Bell produced consecutive one-out triples.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter scored on his triple after an errant throw by second
baseman Mark McLemore skipped into the Mariners' third-base dugout,
and Bell scored the game-tying run on Alex Rodriguez's two-out,
sixth-inning single off Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   All this occurred after the Rangers pounded Garcia for 3 2/3
innings. The Mariners' rookie-of-the-year candidate surrendered
nine runs on seven hits _ which included McLemore's solo home run
on his second pitch of the game _ and issued five walks.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' final opportunity for redemption fell into the
hands of Palmeiro after Gonzalez's two-out, ninth-inning single
scored left fielder Rusty Greer and pulled the Rangers within a
run.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners closer Jose Mesa, though, induced a game-ending fly
ball from Palmeiro that Griffey caught on the warning track and a
made a winner of right-hander Jose Paniagua (6-7).
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow is a big game,'' Clayton said of tonight's game.
``We'd hate to look back and say we had a chance to put them in a
position where they had to make a huge climb and didn't. Tomorrow
is another two-game swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin would prefer to avoid
trading young talent this season by building a commanding advantage
in the West before the July 31 trade deadline. Thus, the Rangers
would not need to part with a prospect such as Fernando Tatis to
acquire veterans such as right-hander Todd Stottlemyre, Clayton and
third baseman Todd Zeile as the case July 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven days remain until the July 31 trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Rangers put the West to rest or require reinforcements?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
