<DOCNO> NYT19990704.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8829 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-B     07-04 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENSON'S WIMBLEDON QUEST ENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The tabloid fairy tale had a climax only Fleet Street
could love: The heroine got slaughtered in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even her emphatic undoing Saturday in the Wimbledon women's
semifinals by third-seeded Lindsay Davenport _ a 6-1, 6-1
bludgeoning that consumed all of 48 minutes _ could not overshadow
the fact that Alexandra Stevenson was an enchanting, if not
enchanted, princess.
</P>
<P>
   Another rags-to-riches story was ruined when Wimbledon grande
dame Steffi Graf, the No. 2 seed, rallied past unseeded 17-year-old
Mirjana Lucic, 6-7 (3-7), 6-4, 6-3, in the other semi. Sunday Graf
will go for All England Club crown No. 8 against Davenport, who has
never won here but has already reached a peak _ No. 1 in the world
rankings, courtesy of her visit to the final and former top woman
Martina Hingis's first-round loss here.
</P>
<P>
   But the most compelling figure of the day, and perhaps the
tournament, was Stevenson, who was a loser only technically.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old Californian became the first female qualifier
ever to make the semis and never lost her poise, affability, or
ebullience despite the sensationalistic off-court subplot in which
she was basically an innocent bystander.
</P>
<P>
   The latest bombshell that landed in her midst occurred Friday
when Julius Erving confirmed a report he initially denied:
Stevenson is the Basketball Hall of Famer's illegitimate daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that at her postmatch press conference Saturday,
Stevenson answered, ``No comment.'' But before she did, she looked
out into the audience at her mother, former Boston Channel 7
reporter Samantha Stevenson, who shook her head.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha, more recently a freelancer for the Boston Globe and
New York Times, among other papers, was asked the same question.
The journalist offered the same response she has right along: ``No
comment.'' Asked when she intends to reveal Alexandra's paternity,
her mother said, ``Hopefully never.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra was pressed as to when she would address the situation
involving her father and said, ``I don't know. When I feel ready,
maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, wasn't the lone potential distraction with
which she dealt. Samantha started a firestorm last week when, in a
published interview, she alleged racism and lesbianism among the
players.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra acknowledged that she had been the target of a racial
epithet at a junior tournament last year but said it was no longer
relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the small matter of compensation. Stevenson came
here as an amateur but declared after her victory over 11th seed
Julie Halard-Decugis last Saturday that she would forgo a tennis
scholarship to UCLA and was turning pro immediately. The WTA, which
runs the women's circuit, initially refused to honor the
declaration, saying a player couldn't change status mid-tournament.
Samantha threatened a lawsuit, and Wimbledon officials overruled
the WTA, saying that a player is considered professional as long as
she doesn't request beforehand to preserve her amateur status.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson had not done so, and as a result of her efforts here,
she'll pocket some $160,000, which she indicated she might use on a
couple of pricey items _ a house or, at the very least, a washer
and dryer, so her mother will stop complaining about using the
communal facilities in the basement of their apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   But even for that jackpot, was it worth the aggravation?
Stevenson made it seem as if there were no aggravation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't read the newspapers,'' she said. ``I just focus on my
tennis and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   She's also diverted herself by playing soccer with the two young
sons of the people who run the bed and breakfast where she and her
mother are staying.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, you'd never know she had a thing on her mind other
than savoring each moment. Throughout, she has been a portrait of
effervescence, smiling as if that were her permanent expression,
curtsying to the applauding crowd after each match, playing this
occasion to the hilt as if she were still under the spotlight in
the school productions of ``The Wizard of Oz,'' ``Grease,'' and
``The Pajama Game'' in which she's appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Her stay on the main stage, Centre Court, was brief; Davenport
won the first 11 games and never looked back. ``I didn't feel
nervous out there,'' said Stevenson. ``I was rushing everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Davenport expressed admiration and sympathy for her
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the nicest girl,'' said Davenport. ``I mean, she's only
18. She's obviously enjoying the whole Wimbledon experience, played
great, and you know, unfortunately, all this stuff has kind of come
on her because of her mom, and you can't help but feel sorry for
her. I just don't think we appreciate (Samantha) commenting on our
way of life (concerning racism).''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, as always, stood by her mother: ``Whatever comments
my mom made, she's my mother and I think she is right, and it
hasn't clouded anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Advised of Davenport's comments, Samantha Stevenson issued her
stock reply: ``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Davenport shouldn't be shunted to the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get to the Wimbledon final, it just means so much to me,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's old hat to Graf, 30, who is relishing the occasion
nonetheless. After her stunning upset of Hingis in the Paris final,
she announced that the win was her French Open farewell, but even
if she claims her 23d Grand Slam title Sunday, she isn't prepared
to make the same commitment about Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Graf, who later withdrew from the mixed
doubles with John McEnroe, citing a strained thigh. ``I'm looking
forward to playing tomorrow, and everything else, there's some
other time to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for Stevenson, who lasted so long here because she
didn't think about everything else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
