<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8831 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-WHITESOX-B     07-04 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DON'T HAVE THEIR THINKING CAPS ON 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WHITE SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ For those who made the mistake of tuning in to Fox
Saturday afternoon, it must have seemed like Rupert Murdoch was
scraping the bottom of the barrel for a summer replacement series.
</P>
<P>
   The gray uniforms said ``Boston,'' but there was no sign of
Nomar and the other guys looked more like actors than anyone who
has been performing for the Red Sox this season.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no studio-ordained sitcom, just a particularly
inglorious effort by the Red Sox, who played in an unhappy daze in
a 11-2 loss to the White Sox before 18,028 sweating patrons at
Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   The opening credits _ minus Garciaparra, who sat out with a
strained groin _ were still rolling when the Sox came unhinged in a
two-inning sequence that couldn't be duplicated if they tried. And
while Red Sox rookie Brian Rose may have felt a victim of
circumstance as Chicago scored three runs in each of the first two
innings, pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, mincing no words, threw the
responsibility for this debacle squarely in the kid's lap.
</P>
<P>
   And it had nothing to do with Rose's pitching, even though his
line read: 4 IP, 12 H, 9 R, 9 ER.
</P>
<P>
   ``He embarrassed himself not covering first base,'' Kerrigan
said of Rose, who broke late for the bag two batters into the game,
on Chris Singleton's grounder fielded by Mike Stanley on the line.
``That cost him three runs. Then not knowing what to do on a PFP
(pitcher's fielding practice) on a ball hit right in front of the
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan was referring to Magglio Ordonez's two-out chopper that
Rose fielded, but the pitcher then looked home, which had been
vacated by catcher Creighton Gubanich, instead of wheeling to first
for the play expected in such circumstances. A run scored on that
play and Carlos Lee followed with a two-run double that made it
6-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``He embarrassed everybody in uniform today,'' Kerrigan said.
``It's my responsibility as pitching coach that he doesn't screw up
like that. He'll be here bright and early Sunday to make sure he
covers first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``His lack of fielding cost six runs. Young people are like
that. He's got a good head on his shoulders about pitching, and has
a real good feel for the game, but even young people can slip and
he slipped big time.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the third time in four games that the Sox gave up
double-digit runs in losing, the only exception being Pedro Night,
when they beat Chicago, 6-1. Your box score will note that the Red
Sox did not make an error, but in this case the small print lies.
The errors, even if they went unsanctioned officially and were more
mental than physical, came fast and furious.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't just Rose who found the banana peels. In the first
inning, after Ray Durham flared a 130-foot double over the head of
third baseman Wilton Veras and Singleton reached on Rose's delayed
reaction, Red Sox center fielder Damon Buford, normally the most
surehanded of outfielders, appeared to just plain miss Frank
Thomas's drive to the track, which hit the wall above his head for
an RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez then hit a grounder to third, which Veras gloved and
fired belatedly to the plate, where Gubanich dropped the ball as
Singleton scored.
</P>
<P>
   A two-out single by Craig Wilson made it 3-0. The Ordonez
miscalculation followed in the second, leading to the doubling of
the score, and the White Sox strung together four hits in the
fourth for another three spot that made it 9-0, spelling the end of
Rose's afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more. In the fifth, designated hitter Jason
Varitek apparently lost track of the outs and advanced just one
base on Veras's pop fly single. In the ninth, Trot Nixon, who
entered the game as a defensive replacement, had to be told to go
to first base after taking ball four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't know if it was just the first inning,'' manager Jimy
Williams said of the weirdness of the day's events. ``Just put this
game behind us and go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, as is his custom, wouldn't single anybody out. It was
almost only in passing that he mentioned Rose's failure to cover
first, and didn't use the pitcher's name when he did. His idea of a
fall guy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad managing is all it was,'' he said. ``I put 'em out there,
so I take responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who had Lou Merloni hitting third and playing short in
Garciaparra's absence, admitted his team wasn't as sharp as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a game where maybe we were a little mentally tired,''
he said. ``Not making excuses, but we had a couple of guys out, we
had (flight problems on) the trip, not a lot of sleep. Maybe the
trip caught up with us a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, whose record dropped to 4-1, now has one win in his last
six starts, with four no-decisions. This was the first time this
season that he has been charged with more than four runs in a
start; in six of his nine starts, he has held the opposition to a
run or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a tough game overall, tough to chew on,'' he said.
``But I've got to move on. The day was pretty much a disaster for
me. I'll try to put it behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose admitted he should have run harder to first base on the
grounder to Stanley, but defended his actions on Ordonez's chopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there were two outs,'' he said. ``I saw Durham running
out of the corner of my eye, and I thought it would be a tough play
to throw across my body. I know Ordonez can run. Call it a mental
error, but I thought the easier play (was the play at the plate).
But it turned around and bit me in the butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Such wounds for the Sox have usually been superficial, lasting
no more than a day. Rose hopes it won't linger beyond his next
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of guy I am,'' he said, ``I look at the bottom line.
The team got a loss, I got a loss, I've got to put out a better
effort. You've got to do your job, but I didn't do mine today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
