<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8833 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      07-04 1841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENT ON UPPING PACE, BENDER BROUGHT ON 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Donnie Walsh saw the same things you and I did when the
Knicks ran past his Indiana Pacers in the Eastern Conference
finals. He saw Latrell Sprewell (whom Walsh, the Pacers' president,
had tried to get) beat his manatees down the floor. He saw Marcus
Camby swoop in, around and over his landlocked leviathans.
</P>
<P>
   He decided it was time to do something about it and, on draft
night, he did. He traded Antonio Davis, one of his key, inside
guys, to the Toronto Raptors for the fifth pick in the draft. He
then had the Raptors select high school wunderkind Jonathan Bender,
who is athletic, gifted, and young.
</P>
<P>
   The deal hasn't been announced officially and won't be until
Aug. 1 because of salary cap complexities. But it's done. Bender
will enter the NBA under the watchful eyes of Larry Bird while
Davis will move north, leaving a veteran, experienced team for a
younger, promising one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to get more athletic and younger, but without
taking the heart out of the team,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Why Antonio Davis? Well, here's an indication of how things are
today. Walsh talked to him at the end of the 1997-98 season and
Davis told him he would like to start at some point. Walsh talked
to him again at the end of this season and got the same vibes,
although more pronounced and urgent.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was one of the best, most reliable, game-changing sixth
men in the league. He was a huge part of the Pacers' success. But
he wanted to start. It didn't matter that he could be on the floor
when games are being decided. He wanted to be on the floor when
there was no score.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't new or unusual. We heard the same things in the
playoffs from Sprewell. We've heard it from a lot of players over
the years. One player we never heard it from was Kevin McHale, who
was a two-time Sixth Man winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed more guys don't want to do it,'' McHale said of his
stint as a reserve. ``It gives you a chance to get a feel for the
game. And when you do go in, you're usually going in against their
second team, or against the first team that is tired. And they're
usually in the bonus situation so all you have to do is throw a
little pump fake and you're at the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest time is if the team is rolling and they send you
in there and you just don't want to screw anything up. If you're up
like 26-6, you think, `how can I beat that?' But if you're
struggling, it's different. You can make a huge impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he hadn't expressed a desire to start, Davis may well
have been traded. The Pacers did have to make a move, and he was a
very desirable commodity. But he made Walsh's job a lot easier when
he said he felt like it was time. In addition, by trading Davis for
a draft pick, the Pacers get a trade exception of $4.5 million,
which they have a year to use (and will).
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers weren't without in-house friction over roles this
season; Mark Jackson complained about sitting during the fourth
quarters. Now, Bird has a new challenge: nurturing Bender, whom he
has not seen play. The Pacers didn't work him out, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made Larry's job any easier,'' Walsh said. ``But he
accepts that we have to get younger. I'm not worried. We need to
get stars. That's what runs the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers would have settled for Lamar Odom had Bender been
gone by No. 5, but the 6-foot-11-inch high schooler from Picayune,
Miss., is the one they wanted. For good reason, said Celtics
general manager Chris Wallace, whose team also was in on the Bender
Sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bender is a tremendous pick,'' Wallace said. ``It's
not an instant payoff thing. It's a long-term investment. He's not
as ready to play as (Kevin) Garnett was and he's not the
intimidator on defense that Garnett is and he may never be that.
But he has some truly amazing skills and if you're a team that can
afford to be patient with him and wait, as the Pacers can, then
it's fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors, meanwhile, with the trade send a clear message to
Charles Oakley that they are committed to win and win now. They
will renounce Oak (who is on the cap at $15 million) and then
quickly try to re-sign him for considerably less. That's one new
wrinkle in the new rules. Before, if you renounced one of your free
agents, you had to wait a couple months to re-sign him. Now, you
can do so immediately, but only by using money that you have by
being under the cap, now at $34 million. The Raptors also need to
upgrade their point guard situation, so look for them to make a
determined run at Eric Snow, who blossomed last year in Philly. He
will be a very coveted lad, given that Terrell Brandon and Nick Van
Exel are the two most prominent point guard free agents. Snow will
probably attract more interest than Van Exel . . . Speaking of
point guards, the Celtics have let it be known that they are more
than just mildly interested in Tony Delk, who, of course, played
for Rick Pitino at Kentucky. Pitino and Wallace have decided not to
extend a qualifying offer to Damon Jones (the deadline is Monday)
because they want to get a better read on him in the summer league.
Had they qualified him, they would have, in effect, had the right
of first refusal. But there won't be a lot of interest _ he was
there last year for anyone until Boston signed him _ so the Celtics
shouldn't have to worry about a bidding war . . . Each year, the
rating system known as Tendex analyzes the NBA draft, using a
complicated formula ranging from points to game pace to strength of
schedule to rate the prospects. They hit and they miss, like most
services. Last year, for instance, they had Corey Benjamin rated
No. 1. This year, they had Wally Szczerbiak at the top spot and
Andre Miller at No. 2. The big jaw-dropper is No. 3 _ Evan
Eschmeyer, the Northwestern center who didn't go until the second
round. (Elton Brand was fourth, followed by Shawn Marion.) The
service also charts players through their careers, reasoning that
each one should improve and be much better as a senior than as a
freshman. They grade players on how much they've improved, and
Szczberiak got an A. The Celtics' pick, Kris Clack, was given an F.
That might be one reason he slipped; Clack did have much better
numbers as a junior. Another is a possible weight problem (Pitino
will love to hear that) and that he wasn't all that good in the
Chicago pre-draft camp. But he also was the MVP of the Nike Desert
Classic. Regardless, the Celtics had him rated as a late
first-rounder and he was there at 55. ``That's the best you can
hope for with that kind of pick,'' Wallace said . . . And what of
Jumaine Jones, the Georgia forward who was the last Green Room guy
picked Wednesday and already had a tear-splashed face by the time
he greeted David Stern? He slipped for the usual reasons: he
switched agents, he had poor workouts, there were some health
concerns, he was too young, and he should have stayed in school.
``He's a great physical talent,'' Wallace said of Jones, who was
drafted by Atlanta and then traded to the Sixers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando Magic, meanwhile, aren't under any illusions that
their 33-17 record this past season indicates they are one of the
beasts of the East. Far from it. They're rebuilding, which was
further dramatized by the trade of Horace Grant to Seattle for the
promising but raw Corey Maggette and a handful of salaries (Don
MacLean, Dale Ellis, Billy Owens). ``We've been living off the '95
team long enough,'' GM John Gabriel said, referring to the club
that went to the NBA Finals. With Grant gone, the only ones left
from that team are Nick Anderson and Penny Hardaway, the latter
being a free agent who may or may not be back. ``I still see us
being competitive,'' Gabriel said. ``You just have to measure how
much of a shelf life you have when you hold on to your older
players. Horace was a great piece for us. He was great in the
locker room. He will be missed.'' The Magic are rebuilding around
youth for first-year coach Doc Rivers; now you know why he wanted
that final year guaranteed. They talk about Michael Doleac, Matt
Harpring, and the unproven Maggette as their building blocks along
with Anderson and Ike Austin, who was awful last season. ``We
expect Ike is going to play much better,'' Gabriel said. ``We've
added some pieces but we've also maintained our depth, which was a
big reason for our success this past season.'' The Magic also want
to re-sign Bo Outlaw, who will be in demand because coaches
appreciate the unselfish way he plays and the enthusiasm he brings
to the game. Then, next season, they have three first-round picks:
their own, Denver's, and Golden State's, without strings . . . So
why didn't Dale Davis opt-out of his contract and become a free
agent? ``I'm glad he didn't,'' Walsh said. The Pacers might not
have traded Antonio Davis had Dale Davis decided to test the waters
as he did three summers ago. ``I thought it was too big a risk,''
said Davis's agent, Steve Kauffman. However, after next season,
Davis is eligible to sign an extension _ he'll have two years left
_ and it can start at 12.5 percent of his last year's salary. Look
for Shaquille O'Neal to do the same thing next summer. And his
extension will be astronomical, as his final year's salary is in
excess of $20 million . . . The Mavericks' selection of
high-schooler Leon Smith with the last pick of the first round
probably means the kid will be sent to Europe to get some playing
time. Their second-round pick, Chinese center Wang Zhi-Zhi, was
interesting. Teams were uncertain whether he was eligible for the
draft until draft day, when the league sent out a memo saying, as
best as it knew, Wang had been born in 1977 and that would make him
OK. (Foreign players who don't declare early have to be 22 in the
year they're drafted.) Wang is no stranger to hoop junkies in and
out of the NBA. He played in the 1996 Olympics and has been seen in
the LA Summer League as well. ``For whatever it's worth, he's the
best Chinese player,'' said Wallace, who called Wang a ``minor
league Toni Kukoc. He's 6-10, lefty, thin, long-armed and likes to
play on the perimeter. He's a finesse player.'' Getting Wang to the
US may be harder than it is for most foreigners. He's supposed to
be in the Army . . . One more Indiana tidbit: Walsh is very high on
center-forward Jeff Foster, whom the team also got out of the draft
by arranging a deal with Golden State, which ended up with Vonteego
Cummings. The Pacers brought in an astounding 29 players for
workouts _ they went into the draft with the 26th pick _ and the
7-foot Foster was the third fastest, tops for big men. He's one of
those quick-growth stories _ David Robinson is another _ going from
5-8 to 6-9 in high school while retaining his ballhandling skills.
``I really like him and so does Larry (Bird),'' Walsh said. ``But I
don't want to say anything more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-99 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
