<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8834 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      07-04 1721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANCOUVER MAY BE TWIN CITY 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Will they or won't they?
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting question this summer has nothing to do with
what free agent will end up where. It has to do with whether twins
Daniel and Henrik Sedin, who were selected Nos. 2 and 3 by the
Vancouver Canucks in the entry draft, are going to play in the NHL
this coming season.
</P>
<P>
   Canucks general manager Brian Burke, who performed a master
stroke of negotiating to be in position to take both kids, has done
a fine job of giving his team hope for LAP (Life After Pavel).
</P>
<P>
   Before last weekend's draft, the Sedins sounded as if they would
definitely stay home for another year and play for MoDo of the
Swedish Elite League. It seemed unlikely that any team would draft
both of them, which was their wish.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Canucks have succeeded, the Sedins are leaning
toward leaving Sweden for the riches and opportunities of the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone you talk to, in terms of their ability, there is no
question they're ready,'' assistant GM Dave Nonis told the
Vancouver Sun. ``I know schooling is important to the family but I
don't know to what extent it is an issue. I think there are other
factors probably playing into whether or not they'll come. I think
they do feel somewhat obligated to their hometown team and that
there is still a question in their own minds whether they are
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The twins' agent, Mike Barnett, who also represents Bruins
center Joe Thornton, said the oppoartunity to play for the same
team has the Sedins reconsidering their future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not under contract yet with their Swedish team and we
haven't discussed the contract yet with Vancouver because the first
decision is whether the players feel comfortable (joining the NHL).
They're discussing that with their family this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canucks have missed the playoffs for three straight seasons,
but last season was Burke's first, and Vancouver's fortunes are
about to change. Look for Burke to do everything in his power to
get the Sedins, who turn 19 in September, here next fall. With the
loss of Gretzky's star power, the twins would be a shot in the arm
for both Vancouver and the league.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of theories as why wing Theo Fleury, who is
being wooed big-time by the Rangers, didn't re-sign with the
Avalanche. Fleury cited unstable ownership. ``I think the ownership
thing is a lot more than people think,'' Fleury said. ``That would
have been a huge payroll, if you think about it. And Joe (Sakic's
contract) is up next year. I'm not that surprised by what
happened.'' Another report said that while the ownership problem
was a factor, Avalanche management made its decision on Fleury
during the playoffs, specifically Game 6 against Dallas, after
which GM Pierre Lacroix was said to be unhappy with Fleury's play.
The 31-year-old didn't score a goal in his last nine playoff games
and missed Game 5 against Dallas with a stomach virus. The
Avalanche also were not thrilled with the notion of giving Fleury a
no-trade clause, which he reportedly won't sign without . . .
According to New York reports, the Rangers are in the hunt for
veteran Chicago center Doug Gilmour . . . It's the end of an era in
Philadelphia. Veteran Ron Hextall, one of history's most colorful
netminders, was waived by the Flyers to make way for the next
generation of goalies _ in this case 22-year-old Brian Boucher.
Hextall, 35, who backed up John Vanbiesbrouck last season, is the
franchise's all-time winningest goalie and played 573 games for the
Flyers, a club record. After the Flyers buy out the remaining year
of his deal, provided he's not picked up by another team, it's
possible another club could sign Hextall. But it appears more
likely he'll retire and may take a job in the organization. ``I
don't feel very good about it,'' said GM Bob Clarke. ``But I feel
it has to be done for our team. In some ways, it's not right.
Here's a guy who wants to play here and we're telling him he can't.
It seems like there's no nice way to do anything anymore.'' Hextall
could sometimes be a little extreme on the ice but off the ice,
there are few, if any, classier people . . . Steve Smith sat out
the entire 1997-98 season but signed last year as a free agent with
Calgary, and it looks as if the durable defenseman will be with the
Flames again this year. The 36-year-old is an unrestricted free
agent. Flames GM Al Coates said something could be finalized soon .
. . Tough times for former NHL defenseman Bryan Fogarty, 30, who
was arrested for drug possession last weekend in Brantford,
Ontario. Fogarty, who battled alcohol problems as a player, was
charged with breaking and entering and possession of a controlled
substance, possibly cocaine . . . It appears that assistant GM
Anders Hedberg is a candidate for the Maple Leafs' GM job. Toronto
president Ken Dryden, who runs one of the league's most convoluted
front offices, fired associate GM Mike Smith, who last week told
the media that Hedberg had been reluctant to share draft
information with him, a charge Hedberg denied. ``I'm two years more
prepared (to be GM),'' said Hedberg. ``(But) I have not talked to
Ken to see where he stands, so I think it would be premature to
announce my candidacy.'' Word out of Toronto is that the Leafs will
pursue free agent Valeri Kamensky to reunite him with captain Mats
Sundin. The two played together in Quebec before the franchise
moved west to Denver . . . There has been little to celebrate in
the Islanders' front office of late but an offer by co-owners
Howard Milstein and Steven Gluckstern seems to have generated some
optimism. Reportedly, they have said they will privately finance a
$300 million arena to replace aging Nassau Coliseum. Reportedly,
their conditions for financing an arena are that they would manage
it and control the revenue streams for all events held there. One
key stumbling block is that the Islanders' lease runs through 2015
and would have to be severed first . . . Blackhawks GM Bob Murray,
who stunned Bruins president/GM Harry Sinden on draft day when he
criticized him after the Bruins selected defenseman Nick Boynton
with the 21st pick, had some pointed remarks for the league
regarding conduct leading up to the draft. Murray said agent Rich
Winter, who represented No. 1 pick Patrik Stefan, wouldn't meet
with the Hawks and wouldn't provide medical records concerning
Stefan's history of concussions. Islanders GM Mike Milbury also
torched Winter for the same runaround. Murray said he was so
disgusted with his treatment by Winter and the Sedin twins
postponing their meeting with the Blackhawks not once but twice,
that it helped push him toward a deal with the Canucks in which
Chicago acquired defenseman Bryan McCabe. ``This league, for its
own health, has got to get this thing in order,'' said Murray.
``This was wrong. We can't let it happen anymore. (Their conduct)
made me much more anxious to get away from these people.'' . . .
The Florida Panthers dumped Dino Ciccarelli, Terry Carkner, and
Kirk Muller off their roster. The three made $6.475 million last
year and combined for 33 points. That's $196,212.12 per point for
those of you keeping score at home . . . Has Keith Primeau played
his last game for the Carolina Hurricanes? Possibly. The club
offered Primeau a raise that would have doubled his salary next
season (from $2 million to $4 million). As of July 1, Primeau is a
restricted free agent and general manager Jim Rutherford said
Carolina would match up to a $5 million offer. Primeau reportedly
wants in the neighborhood of $6 million, which Rutherford said is
too much. Don't be surprised to see Primeau traded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When he first learned he had been traded from Ottawa to Tampa
Bay, Andreas Johansson was less than happy about going to the worst
team in the league as part of the transaction that had former
Senators GM Rick Dudley taking over the Tampa head job. ``When I
first heard, it came as a shock,'' said the 26-year-old center from
Hofors, Sweden. ``I got mad right away. I know hockey is a business
and I've been traded before but I really liked Ottawa. It's going
to be tough to leave.'' As much as he'll miss his friends,
Johansson, who suffered from a balky knee the final two months of
the season and wound up being scratched by coach Jacques Martin,
knows this could be a positive turn of events. ``This could turn
out to be a good opportunity,'' he said. ``This could be good for
my career.'' It remains to be seen how good it will be for Rob
Zamuner, the Lightning's last original player, who went to Ottawa.
``For seven years, there have been so many ups and downs,'' said
Zamuner. ``It really wasn't a traditional seven years, what with
the Japanese owners and then Art Williams. You really had to be a
professional through all of that. But now everything's going to
turn around and as a player you can sense that. That's the hardest
part of all this.'' Lightning coach/GM Jacques Demers said
Johansson will be moved to left wing to replace Zamuner . . . Wayne
Gretzky and his wife, Janet Jones Gretzky, are expecting a fourth
child early next year. The Gretzkys have an 11-year-old daughter,
Paulina, and two sons _ 8-year-old Ty and 6-year-old Trevor . . .
In a chilling reminder of a tragic event more than two years ago,
Richard Gnida, who was driving the limousine in the crash that
permanently disabled Red Wings defenseman Vladimir Konstantinov and
team masseur Sergei Mnatsakanov, was arrested on a charge of
drunken driving in Westland, Mich. Gnida reportedly ran a stop sign
at 2 a.m. and failed a field sobriety test. On June 13, 1997, Gnida
ran onto a median and hit a tree while driving some of the Red
Wings home after a party celebrating their Stanley Cup victory. He
served seven months for driving with a suspended license, his
second offense. He went back to jail in January after violating
conditions of his parole and was released on good behavior in March
. . . What a sickening development: The NHL's decision to go to a
four-on-four format in overtime is nothing short of a disgrace.
Another victory for gimmickry over what is in the best interest of
the sport. Brutal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
