<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAWED FINLEY FINISHED QUICKLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Chuck Finley is out of whack, much like the Angels'
season.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran left-hander was knocked around for the third time in
a row in the Angels' 9-7 loss to the Oakland A's on Saturday night
before 50,916 at the Oakland Coliseum, the largest crowd ever to
see the A's play in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Finley was tagged for eight runs (six earned) and eight hits in
31/3 innings, his shortest outing of the season. The mechanical
flaw in his delivery obviously hasn't been corrected because in his
past three starts, Finley has allowed 21 earned runs in 112/3
innings, his ERA rising from 4.18 to 5.52.
</P>
<P>
   The A's knocked him out of the game in the fourth inning with
six runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a loss for words,'' said Finley, who fell to 4-9. ``The
last three starts have been brutal. Absolutely terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since I've been hammered three times in
a row like this, if ever. Usually when it gets bad it's the seventh
or eighth inning, but I'm not getting to the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out of spring training and he was our No. 1 guy, and
in my opinion he still is our No. 1 guy,'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``I'm not a pitching coach, but just from my
experience, big, tall guys can get out of whack easily. Mechanics
are really important, especially with a guy like Chuck. He'll get
it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's performance wasn't unlike the rest of the starters on
the staff in recent days. In fact, only one starter _ Omar Olivares
on June 25 _ has made it through the sixth inning in the Angels'
past 11 games. In those games, the starters' ERA is 8.80 (45 earned
runs in 46 innings).
</P>
<P>
   Finley, though, has become more important considering the loss
of Tim Belcher and Ken Hill to injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to do with the rest of the rotation,'' Finley
said. ``The only urgency I have is to pitch better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense has made an appearance the past two nights
with 27 hits, including 13 Saturday. Darin Erstad had three hits,
and Randy Velarde, Mo Vaughn and Orlando Palmeiro had two each.
</P>
<P>
   Still, wasted opportunities hurt them early. Going into the
game, the Angels were hitting only .241 with runners in scoring
position, including just .230 with runners in scoring position and
two out.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, after singles by Erstad and Vaughn, Garret
Anderson grounded into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning after the Angels had scored twice to take a
2-1 lead, Todd Greene came to the plate with one out and the bases
loaded. With a chance to make it a big inning, Greene instead
popped out and Bret Hemphill grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   The A's tied the game with an unearned run on shortstop Gary
DiSarcina's error in the bottom of the third, then broke it open
with a six-run fourth.
</P>
<P>
   A throwing error by third baseman Troy Glaus got the inning
started, but Finley was responsible for the rest. He gave up a
two-run double to Miguel Tejada and an RBI single to Olmedo Saenz,
which brought out pitching coach Dick Pole.
</P>
<P>
   But on the first pitch after the conference, John Jaha blasted a
three-run homer for an 8-2 Oakland lead.
</P>
<P>
   The A's lead was 9-2 when the Angels tried to climb back into it
in the sixth. Palmeiro hit a two-run double and Erstad got his
third hit of the night, an RBI single to make it 9-5.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Worrell relieved A's starter Gil Heredia (4-5), but Velarde
kept the inning going with a single to right. Vaughn followed with
an RBI single and Anderson doubled home another to make it 9-7. But
with the tying runs in scoring position, Jeff Huson, pinch hitting
for Greene, struck out looking at a 3-2 pitch to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Taylor pitched the ninth for the A's to earn his 19th
save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
