<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8836 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      07-04 2663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS AREN'T THINKING WITH CAP 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Capped out . . . Up against the cap . . . Cap poor .
. . No room under the cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Cap this.
</P>
<P>
   Salary cap jargon is getting as annoying as hearing ``Have a
good one'' or ``TGIF.'' When Bob Kraft and his fellow owners put
together a $17.6 billion TV deal, the richest in sports history,
this was supposed to be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it has been in terms of NFL owners getting richer, but
the extra money has created headaches for teams constructing their
rosters. ``Capologists'' around the league are bright men, many of
whom have succeeded in other businesses, but many of them have
entered blindly into ridiculous contracts for players not worth the
riches at the expense of having to cut good players.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco 49ers, for example, had to cut almost $20
million off their payroll because their buy-now, pay-later attitude
snuck up on them so quickly. They had to dump guard Kevin Gogan,
defensive end Roy Barker, and tight end Irv Smith to meet budget.
The 49ers did so much renegotiating of contracts to make ``cap
room'' that they left themselves holding a huge bill down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' Andy Wasynczuk refers to it as a credit card that
becomes payable.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Patriots are sometimes criticized for having lost
players such as Todd Collins, Dave Wohlabaugh, and Curtis Martin,
who were basically sacrificed for Max Lane, Todd Rucci, Bruce
Armstrong, Willie McGinest, and Ted Johnson, they are trying to
avoid a bigger hit down the road, such as the one the New York Jets
will likely feel next year and for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, of course, feel they can win now, and there's
certainly something to be said for going for it _ if you make it.
If you don't, you have no Super Bowl to show for it, and then you
still have to pay the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys recently gave Deion Sanders a five-year, $51 million
deal. They are basically committing a third of their payroll to
four players _ Emmitt Smith ($6.8 million), Troy Aikman ($6
million), Darren Woodson ($4.1 million) and Erik Williams ($3.3
million). Those players are old, and the Cowboys will be paying
after the player is gone. It's like having a car that is no longer
useful, but you still have two years left on the loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago we got into the business of up-front bonuses
because it helps you get more talent on the roster, but it's like
using a credit card because you have to have some discipline,''
Cowboy owner Jerry Jones told the Dallas Morning News last week.
</P>
<P>
   Discipline?
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is 34 years old and coming off a foot operation.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman is one concussion away from calling it a career.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's best days are behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Every team is in the league is now falling into the trap of
paying huge money to a few players. In some cases it's unavoidable.
The NFL is no different than Major League Baseball, the NHL, or the
NBA in that respect. The problem is when players make big money,
they have to perform at a very high level, or the results are
disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy is making $5 million, he's got to be twice as good as
the guy making $2 million, or he's killing your team,'' said
Patriots free safety Willie Clay. ``Because if you have players
making that much, you're probably getting rid of good players so
you can pay out those salaries. Do you sacrifice five or six good
players so you can give one or two guys that money?''
</P>
<P>
   When $5 million players such as McGinest and Johnson go down
with injuries, the Patriots have to plug in with Marty Moore or
Greg Spires. The dropoff is huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous amount of pressure on those guys,'' said
Clay. ``Because they have to justify the expense. It's great that
the money is out there and that they're making it, but once you get
that contract, you have to perform even better or it hurts the team
in other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay is right. In '99, McGinest and Johnson have to play better
than ever. When Ty Law and Lawyer Milloy get their big deals,
probably at the expense of above-average players, they, too, must
continue to play at a high level.
</P>
<P>
   On the Patriots, Drew Bledsoe's $7.2 million cap number may be
the only justifiable big number. You would do that one again and
again.
</P>
<P>
   This cap stuff in the era of big money will eventually be solved
by teams that have very bright financial minds. For now, however,
costly mistakes are being made by all teams, and the fans are
paying. They're watching players they've had an affinity for go
elsewhere because an overrated defensive lineman got one of those
five-year, $25 million contracts teams were handing out a couple of
years ago. Most of the guys who got those deals aren't justifying
them.
</P>
<P>
   And because of those deals, teams are ``capped out . . . up
against the cap . . . cap poor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Patriots training camp coming up at the end of the month, a
few things to watch for:
</P>
<P>
   --Third-year free safety Chris Carter will get every chance to
beat out Clay _ at least that's the bug the Patriots are putting in
Carter's ear to give him a spark. Carter showed a bit of
indifference about the offseason workout program (and no, his
absence was not due to his attending medical school. In fact, he
hasn't even applied to medical school). The Patriots feel this will
be Carter's big chance to go from special teams player to starter.
They like his intelligence and ability to learn and to read what's
going on. Clay is in the final year of his deal ($1.8 million), and
the Patriots may feel they can save money here. Unfortunately, the
Patriots have cut too many Clays the past few years and have left
themselves with few leaders on the field and in the locker room.
Also, watch for third-round pick Tony George, who has been told by
Clay, ``This is your job next year.''
</P>
<P>
   --It'll be interesting to see how the Patriots configure their
receiver depth chart. Terry Glenn is a starter if he's OK, but who
will start on the opposite side? Shawn Jefferson is the
hardest-working and the most dependable receiver, but it's obvious
that second-year man Tony Simmons, also a deep threat, could unseat
Jefferson. That leaves Troy Brown, Vincent Brisby, and Sean Morey
to duke it out for playing time. Brown is too valuable not to play
and Brisby keeps getting contract extensions, which makes Morey's
battle for a spot tough. But fear not, Mr. Morey: A receiver or two
or three will likely pull a hamstring before long.
</P>
<P>
   --Just who will be the Patriots' starting running back come
Sept. 13? Some close to Terry Allen feel he's pretty much agreed to
join the Patriots as soon as they free the cap room. Allen, who
will not win a Mr. Congeniality award anytime soon, could be a
temporary solution, and could help break in Kevin Faulk, who is
represented by the same agent, Tank Black. Lamont Warren appears to
be fixed in that third-down slot, which means Derrick Cullors's
days might be numbered, unless he's used as a special teams player.
The Patriots are also giving Harold Shaw, the last of the running
back Shaws, a chance to show what he can do. Also, look for
fullback Chris Floyd to be given a chance to carry the ball.
</P>
<P>
   --In search of much-needed depth, defensive line coach Ray
Hamilton has liked the offseason work of free agent defensive end
Sterling Palmer, who is known more for his run-stopping, though
he's considered quick enough to rush the passer. Problem is he has
bad knees. Also showing a ferocious side was Illinois rookie free
agent nose tackle Garrett Johnson, and undersized end Willie Cohens
from Florida State. The Patriots have to count on the unprovens,
and hope the players with questions surrounding them get their acts
together, or they may not be able to absorb injuries to their
front-line guys.
</P>
<P>
   --Even Wohlabaugh is a little baffled by the outpouring of
warmth since he left the Patriots to become the highest-paid center
in football with the Cleveland Browns. When he was with the
Patriots he felt he was just another guy. Now that he's gone, he's
an All-Pro. To my knowledge he never earned All-Pro honors, but
he's irreplaceable? All of the accolades Wohlabaugh receives are
well-earned because he's a good guy and a good player who played
hurt. What many forget is that three players on the line _
Armstrong, Rucci, and Lane _ were starters when the Patriots got to
the Super Bowl. They have to find two other players. One of them is
Zefross Moss, a steady starter who may not be around when the
season starts because of salary cap issues. If Moss is sacrificed,
left guard Lane could go back to his old position at right tackle,
where he played pretty well for Bill Parcells, a couple of plays in
the Super Bowl against one of the greatest pass rushers in football
history (Reggie White) notwithstanding. Say what you will about
Lane; he's been a loyal guy who has been moved. He deserves a
chance to return to his natural position. And while the football
jury is out on Damon Denson, Ed Ellis, and Jason Andersen, it may
soon carry a positive verdict on Baylor rookie Derrick Fletcher,
who is a pretty imposing figure at 6 feet 7 inches, 370 pounds. Who
replaces Wohlabaugh? Pete Brock, who was a pretty good center in
the league for many years, thinks Andersen can really play, and he
thinks Damien Woody's athleticism is top notch. Woody will have to
disprove criticism of his work ethic, but he's a first-round
talent. By the way, if Woody makes it as a starter and the Patriots
stay with Moss, Armstrong, Rucci, and Lane, the line will be one of
the few in the league with everyone having a cap number over $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   --Todd Collins, who signed a three-year deal with the St. Louis
Rams, was one of the most respected guys on the football field. His
leadership and work ethic will be missed, as will his field savvy,
but few feel uncomfortable about his replacement, Andy Katzenmoyer.
And don't forget, Tedy Bruschi can be an unrestricted free agent
next year, so this season he will either be labeled as a good
all-around player, or a replaceable role player. It's also a big
year for third-year linebacker Vernon Crawford, whom Collins
considered the most talented outside linebacker on the team.
</P>
<P>
   --In the end it all comes down to Bledsoe, anyway. The best news
for the Patriots is that John Friesz can get the job done if
Bledsoe goes down. Even better news for New England is that if
Vinny Testaverde should fall to injury or is ineffective, the Jets
will have to turn to the Patriots' backup quarterbacks from last
season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to those who know, the Patriots' new stadium will
closely resemble the Baltimore Ravens' stadium . . . For the first
year since 1982, the Green Bay Packers' organization was in the
red. In their annual report to 110,000 shareholders, the Packers
spent $154,000 more than they brought in in their fiscal year,
which ended March 31, 1999, in large part because of the $32
million in signing bonuses they gave out . . . What money problem?
Ravens owner Art Modell finds himself in quite a pickle in
Baltimore. He's about $185 million in debt because of his lifestyle
and needs to attract a minority owner. Don't rule out Orioles owner
Peter Angelos, who was involved in the Redskins' sale at one time.
Under NFL bylaws, Angelos may own another pro franchise in his
market. Modell did throw fuel on his money problems when he gave a
five-year, $18.7 million contract (and $6 million signing bonus) to
guard Jeff Blackshear and vowed more long-term signings were on the
way. Modell is trying to get the league to give him a loan and
waive his relocation fee. That doesn't appear to be in the cards.
Also of interest is a grievance filed by Modell on behalf of the
Ravens against the Redskins, claiming that the team stole the
Ravens' star salesman for luxury boxes and club suites, David Cope.
One of the problems is that Daniel Snyder is not officially the new
owner yet, thus making it difficult for commissioner Paul Tagliabue
to rule that Snyder stole Cope. Cope was lured away with a $400,000
salary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are pretty much sold out for the year, including
exhibition games. Only a few single tickets remain for the
exhibition game against the Redskins. The Patriots' waiting list
for season tickets, even after the Hartford hopefuls dropped out,
remains at more than 50,000 . . . According to those associated
with the Patriots' luxury boxes and club-seating sales, the sale of
luxury boxes is ``moving along'' while a plan for the sale of club
seating should be unveiled soon. There's already a waiting list for
those seats . . . One Patriots rookie felt the wrath of strength
coach Johnny Parker when he was caught skipping a few steps in the
conditioning routine. Hell hath no greater fury than Parker scorned
. . . Giants All-Pro cornerback Jason Sehorn, who missed the entire
1998 season after being injured on a kick return, and coach Jim
Fassel are at loggerheads. Sehorn pretty much blew off the Giants'
offseason, including a week of the team's passing camp, which left
Fassel fuming. The Giants want Sehorn around since he wasn't able
to play last season . . . Where have we heard this before? The
Vikings think they can turn former Patriot Devin Wyman into a
serviceable defensive tackle . . . One of the most sought-after
corners out there is former Bengal Ashley Ambrose, torn between
more money in New Orleans (about $2 million) and playing close to
his best friend, Ray Buchanan, in Atlanta, which can't pay him as
much. It's apparent Ambrose is leaning toward the Falcons because
he turned down a $15 million deal from the Chiefs . . . Are the
Bills down on Antowain Smith? That appears to be a logical
conclusion based on their interest in Lawrence Phillips. Like the
Patriots, the Bills are not usually tolerant of those with shady
pasts . . . Interesting case in Michigan, where former Lion coach
Wayne Fontes is trying to make a claim for worker's compensation as
a result of a 1989 sideline hit he took when Lions defensive back
Bennie Blades drove a Viking receiver out of bounds. Fontes
allegedly suffered back and neck injuries, which he claims impaired
his ability to be a top coach and eventually led to his firing in
1996. Fontes, 60, said he still suffers from back and neck pain,
but is able to play golf once a week. If he wins his case, he could
earn up to $555 per week in benefits for the rest of his life . . .
Mike Holmgren lifted linebacker James Willis under the noses of his
old team, the Packers, last week. Willis, who had played for new
Green Bay coach Ray Rhodes in Philadelphia, was about to sign with
Rhodes, who was offering $400,000 plus incentives, when Holmgren
swooped in and took him away, offering the potential of more
playing time . . . Gene Hackman and Keanu Reeves will star in a
movie ``The Replacements'' based somewhat on the Washington
Redskins' replacement team of 1987 during the NFL strike. The movie
is due out in January and shooting has been taking place around RFK
stadium this summer . . . Quarterback Heath Shuler, a former No. 1
draft pick most thought couldn't miss, is likely facing early
retirement, unable to come back from a foot injury he sustained in
New Orleans last year. Shuler was recently cut by the Oakland
Raiders . . . The Rams have been talking to Jeff Hostetler about a
possible spot as a backup quarterback to Trent Green, whom he
backed up in Washington last year. The Rams currently have Kurt
Warner and Joe Germaine penciled in as backups, but neither has
much or any NFL experience . . . The Dolphins are shopping for more
help in their defensive backfield. One quality player still
available that they're considering is former Ram strong safety Toby
Wright . . . We have Flutie Flakes and Jake's Flakes (named after
Cards QB Jake Plummer). What about Drew? How about Bleds-O's?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
