<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYMPIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LORDS HAVE BEEN ADVISED OF RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Just in case polite men with short haircuts and federal
badges knock on their hotel doors anytime soon, the Lords of the
Rings have been given a brief rundown on the American legal system
_ and Mr. Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the right to speak with an agent if he asks for an
interview and also to refuse to speak,'' Francois Carrard, the
International Olympic Committee's director general, told the
members at their recent meeting in Seoul. ``You also have the right
to be assisted by a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, which is still investigating the Salt Lake City payoff
scandal, has already interviewed several Lords, including
Switzerland's Marc Hodler, the chief whistleblower. And since
members come to the States frequently (and the executive board will
meet in Salt Lake next year), the IOC wants to make sure they're
ready for the ominous knock on the door. Not all of the members
understand (or appreciate) due process and the feds have made it
clear that none are exempt _ not even the chief Lord himself. ``I'm
not worried,'' Juan Antonio Samaranch says. ``If I am interviewed,
there will be an interview. It is no problem for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the IOC members rubber-stamped the new ethics code
proposed after the Salt Lake scandal. In short, the Lords can't
solicit or accept anything of value from bid cities, can't have
conflicts of interest, and can't bring the Olympic movement into
disrepute. The old $200 limit for gifts, which was widely ignored
anyway, was scrapped. All that's allowed now are ``gifts of nominal
value in accordance with prevailing local custom.'' In other words,
no jewel-encrusted samurai swords, custom-made shotguns, or live
bulldogs. The IOC also made it easier to essentially boot out
wrongdoers without having to wait until its annual session. From
now on, the 11-member executive board can exclude members pending
expulsion . . . Lost in the shuffle among the vote for the 2006
Winter Games site and IOC reform was a decision to make Olympic
results unchallengeable after three years. That means that the push
to give medals to athletes (like swimmer Shirley Babashoff) beaten
by doped East Germans in the '70s and '80s is formally dead . . .
Can't convince the Swiss newspapers that Sion's loss to Turin as
2006 host was on the up-and-up. ``Sion _ May the Best Candidate
Lose,'' scowled Le Matin. ``It was revenge,'' declared
SonntagsBlick. Revenge, that is, for Hodler fueling the Salt Lake
scandal by claiming a quarter of his colleagues had been on the
take for years. Nonsense, say the Italians, who claim Sion was
overconfident and arrogant and never took Turin seriously.
Meanwhile, Italian skier Alberto Tomba, Turin's star pitchman,
vowed to open 2006 bottles from his expansive wine collection to
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there was a US outdoor track and field championships last
month. It was merely held a week later than scheduled to avoid TV
conflicts with women's World Cup soccer and golf's US Open. Only a
few surprises and little marquee drama _ Maurice Greene skipped the
100 because he's already automatic for this summer's world
championships in Seville, Spain, Michael Johnson pulled out of the
meet with a quadriceps twinge, and Marion Jones was competing on a
twisted knee. Most notable moments were Regina Jacobs becoming the
first American to pull off the ``Nurmi double'' in the 1,500 and
5,000 and Adam Goucher knocking off US record-holder Bob Kennedy in
the 5,000. Just missing the world team (by .69 of a second in the
1,500) was Brookline's Jonathon Riley, now a Stanford undergrad . .
. Easy preliminary draw for the US men's basketball team (nine NBA,
three collegians) for the regional Olympic qualifier that begins in
San Juan in mid-month _ Uruguay, Canada, Argentina, and Cuba. All
the Americans need do is make the finals (presumably against
Brazil) to get a ticket to Sydney. Since they'll be playing 10
games in 11 days, they're spending minimal time in camp _ a week in
Orlando, Fla., starting Tuesday, with one tuneup against the
Canadians . . . Yet another extension, until mid-September, for the
NHL to make up its mind whether to have its players compete in the
2002 Winter Games. The original February deadline had already been
pushed to August. The sticking points haven't changed _ the league
wants NBC to show games in prime time and wants big games moved
from the E Center to the larger Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quick intervention for Russian world figure skating champion
Alexei Yagudin, who was booted off the Champions on Ice tour last
month for being drunk and offensive. He's already under a doctor's
care back home to see whether the 19-year-old Yagudin is an
alcoholic or just a party boy with too much money and too little
supervision. After Oksana Baiul's nasty drinking problems after she
won the 1994 gold medal, the skating people are taking no chances.
Yagudin's indiscretions _ racially-offensive remarks _ will cost
him between $25,000 and $50,000, what he would have earned on the
tour's final 16 stops . . . The first US Olympians for next
summer's Sydney Games have already been chosen _ Anna Kozlova and
Tuesday Middaugh will be the synchronized swimming duet . . . No
real upsets in the latest batch of US trials for this summer's
world rowing championships in Ontario. Ian McGowan-Dan Perkins and
Norwood's Carol Skricki-Cindy Brooks won the men's and women's
doubles and the camp boat (Ransom Weaver-Dave Sanderson-Marc
Millard-Sean Groom) won the men's lightweight quad . . . The US is
sending more than 270 athletes in 10 of the 12 sports (all but
soccer and tennis) to the biennial World University Games, which
began Saturday in Palma de Mallorca, Spain. New England competitors
include Kristin Beaney (Wayland and Princeton), Emily Carlsten
(Warwick, R.I., and Florida) and Ann Croose (Old Mystic, Conn., and
Virginia) in track and field, Scoonie Penn (Salem and Ohio State)
and Kevin Freeman (UConn) in men's basketball, Katie Zimbone
(Needham and Arizona) in swimming, and Justin Toman (Wallingford,
Conn., and Michigan) in gymnastics. Eight Olympians, five of them
fencers, are on the roster. The Americans, who've topped the medal
table at the last four WUGs, are expected to dominate again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
