<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS AND AGASSI ARE IN FINAL FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Well, that settles it. Now we know who's No. 1. All
that's left is a little formality known as the Wimbledon men's
final, which is also an irrelevancy as far as the ATP Tour computer
is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   By sweeping Patrick Rafter, 7-5, 7-6 (7-5), 6-2, in the
semifinals Saturday, Andre Agassi guaranteed that he will climb
from No. 4 to the top. By beating England's pride and joy, Tim
Henman, 3-6, 6-4, 6-3, 6-4, Pete Sampras guaranteed that he will
fall from first to third no matter the result on Centre Court
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That makes perfect sense, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   It does to the computer, which places more emphasis on Agassi's
recent report card, especially his French Open triumph, than on the
performance of Sampras, who has established a record by ending the
last six years at No. 1 but in 1999 has won only the Queen's Club
Wimbledon tuneup.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who in the past has insisted that preserving his place
at the top and winning Grand Slam events are his top priorities,
didn't seem particularly perplexed by the fact that the bizarre ATP
computations have made such a parlay impossible Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ranking at this point is secondary,'' he said. ``Andre and
I want to hold up the cup, and that's what's on our mind. The
ranking is the ranking, and I'm not concerned about dropping. I'm
more concerned about getting ready for tomorrow and hopefully
winning the Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, he can claim a couple of consolation prizes. Having
won five of the last six Wimbledons, he would displace Bjorn Borg
and Laurie Doherty as the All England Club's most decorated man of
this century. And it would be his 12th career Grand Slam triumph _
joining two Australian and four US Opens atop his mantel _ which
would tie Roy Emerson's all-time record.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, too, has a sense of urgency about Sunday. As unlikely as
it might have seemed, his French conquest made him only the fifth
man ever to win the career Grand Slam. He is seeking to become the
first man since Borg (1980) to win the French Open and Wimbledon in
the same year. But he has only one of each, and he said at the
start of this tournament that he'd like to start acquiring some
companion pieces.
</P>
<P>
   And he, too, wasn't thinking in terms of ratings despite his
astonishing ascendancy to the top from his low of No. 142, where he
plummeted during one of his many phases, the one in question as
celebrity escort/husband of the former Mrs. Agassi, Brooke Shields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't advise it to anybody, dropping to 142 in the world,''
said Agassi, who had fallen off the skyscraper from his No. 1 perch
of 1996. ``It's a long way back. It is (gratifying). It certainly
reflects a lot of hard work, but I'm far from satisfied. I've come
here to win. You don't come here just to accomplish a little
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by recent performances, Agassi looks more likely to
achieve his objective. Saturday's win was his 13th straight, and he
dominated the world's No. 2 player, Rafter, whose loss won't affect
his ranking. Agassi has looked invincible throughout the fortnight,
and Rafter was no match for his flaming returns of serve and
baseline lasers.
</P>
<P>
   Having fulfilled both a singles and doubles agenda until the eve
of this match, Rafter could have pleaded fatigue, but he would have
none of that. It was Agassi who made him look tired, said the
always forthright Australian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was on for him today,'' said Rafter. ``He was very
powerful with everything he did. I know he's capable of doing that,
but he never let me in at all in those first two sets. I was just
totally outplayed. I ran into someone too good on the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Top seed Sampras guaranteed a star-spangled final on the Fourth
of July but wasn't nearly as impressive as his fellow American. For
the second day in a row, he dropped the first set. He got a bye in
the quarterfinals when Mark Philippoussis pulled up lame in the
second set. Saturday Sampras needed to recover after receiving
treatment for a groin strain in the second. He started nailing his
second serves and returning with a vengeance, thus ushering out
sixth seed Henman and extending England's drought without a native
king of its own tournament since Fred Perry, 63 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to come back from being a set down,'' Sampras said,
``but once I got that second set, I really felt that was a huge
turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows he can't afford a similar stuttering start Sunday. Then
again, he's won 45 of his last 46 matches here, and the numbers
don't lie. Do they?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
