<HEADLINE>
TRAMPLED  
 WALKS IN 10TH SINK D-BACKS' BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ In what has become a recurring nightmare, the
bullpen marched the Diamondbacks toward another slow death Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Three Arizona relievers combined to give up a single and three
walks in the bottom of the 10th inning that led to a bitter 2-1
loss for the Diamondbacks, who couldn't put away a struggling St.
Louis Cardinals club.
</P>
<P>
   The loss, coupled with San Francisco's sixth straight victory,
dropped the Diamondbacks two games behind the National League
West-leading Giants. May 10 was the last time the Diamondbacks were
more than one game out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's easy to point to the club's embattled bullpen as
the primary culprit for the two-week slide in the standings, a
closer look reveals the Diamondbacks are getting a firsthand look
at the natural growing pains some of their young relievers are
experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   Byung-Hyun Kim, who walked two in the top of the 10th, and
Vicente Padilla, who walked Mark McGwire on four pitches with the
bases loaded and ended the game, are 20 and 23 years old,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Making their meteoric climb to the majors more difficult, each
has been in the United States less than three months. Kim is South
Korean, and Padilla is Nicaraguan. The two have combined for 27
minor league appearances _ all of them this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a little stage right now _ with Gregg Olson and
Darren Holmes on the disabled list _ where we have no other choices
now,'' Manager Buck Showalter said. ``Consistency comes from
experience. And the only way to get experience is from
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Toss in Vladimir Nunez, a 24-year-old Cuban defector who arrived
in the United States in 1996, and half of the Diamondbacks' six
relievers have less than one combined year of big-league service
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three have a chance to be outstanding major league
pitchers,'' Showalter said. ``But very rarely does a guy come to
the majors and succeed from the beginning. It comes in phases.
Ideally, we would like to phase them in, like we did with Vladimir
late last year and early this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Padilla, who was signed after he was seen pitching for
Nicaragua's national team last year, stepped into as difficult a
situation as possible Saturday when he entered with two outs, the
bases loaded and McGwire stepping to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla's first pitch, a slider, seemed to cross over the heart
of the plate. But veteran home plate umpire Bruce Froemming saw it
as Ball 1. An obviously disturbed Padilla appeared to become
rattled. His next three pitches, all fastballs, were nowhere near
the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, the more you try to throw a pitch somewhere, the
harder it is to do,'' said Padilla, whose stratospheric 81.00 ERA
is the result of just one-third of an inning pitched.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Padilla and Kim sat motionless for more than 10
minutes, staring blankly into their lockers. As Padilla, who has
been with the big-league club 10 days, searched for answers in his
stall, teammate Omar Daal consoled the right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you throw a pitch that's a strike and the umpire doesn't
call it, you have to throw the next one right over the plate,''
said Daal, a Venezuelan native. ``You can't try to find a little
area here or there within the strike zone. Throw it over and win or
lose that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these guys are here, it's because they can pitch. At first,
being here (in the United States) is not that easy. But . . . the
game is the same here as it is in all countries. Whatever language
we speak, we all know the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss spoiled a masterful performance from starter Armando
Reynoso, who threw every imaginable kind of pitch in giving up one
run and two hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks managed to tie the score in the top of the
ninth on a freakish play that ended when Cardinals catcher Alberto
Castillo threw wildly to first base after a rundown. Castillo's
error allowed Matt Williams to easily score from second base and
send the game into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be some situations that are tough,'' injured
pitcher Todd Stottlemyre said of the young relievers. ``These guys
are going to help us win games. They're good. If it was easy, there
would be a lot of major league pitchers out there on the street.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
