<HEADLINE>
TANK EMPTY, JARRETT CRAWLS TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
 400-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ As he turned laps at a torrid pace during
a practice session Friday afternoon at Daytona International
Speedway, Dale Jarrett accidentally flattened a turtle that was
trying to cross the racing surface to get to Lake Lloyd, the body
of water in the track's infield.
</P>
<P>
   While the mishap caused front-end damage to Jarrett's car, it
seemed to be an omen when Saturday &UR;  &LR; night the NASCAR Winston Cup
points leader was forced to maintain a tortoise pace on the final
two laps _ which were run under caution _ to steer his fuel-starved
No. 88 Ford Credit Taurus to Victory Lane in the Pepsi 400 before a
prime-time CBS audience and a live Daytona crowd of 190,000.
</P>
<P>
   When his car finally sputtered on pit row, prompting his crew to
rush out and push it to Victory Lane, Jarrett realized he might not
have won had he run the final two laps at speed. Jarrett said Dale
Earnhardt, who finished second at Daytona for the sixth time in his
career, would've emerged as the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another second place at Daytona,'' said Earnhardt, ``just what
we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a well-executed pit stop for a quick splash of gas during
a timely caution with two laps to go that enabled Jarrett to hold
on for his third victory of the season. His car crawled across the
finish line with nothing more than fumes in the tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would've been close,'' said Jarrett, who along with earning
$164,965 for the victory extended his lead in the points race over
second-place Bobby Labonte to 177 points (2,674 to 2,497). ``I was
trying to save fuel. I ran out after the checkered on the
backstretch, so it would've been awful close. I think I would've
made it, but, man, it was awful close.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin, who had qualified third fastest during Thursday
night's pole qualifications, was relegated to the back of the field
when he smashed up his primary car in a wall crash along the
backstretch during Friday night's practice session. Martin, who
initially reported some tenderness in his left wrist, wound up
suffering a fracture and had it placed in a cast Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   He was forced to start 43d in his backup car, which was the same
one he crashed in February's Daytona 500. He finished 17th
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   Pole-sitter Joe Nemechek faded from view after the first dozen
laps of close-quarter action, dropping back to 23d on Lap 44.
Nemechek first surrendered the lead to outside pole-sitter Ricky
Rudd, who led Laps 5-14 before relinquishing it to Rusty Wallace,
who held the lead for the most laps (75).
</P>
<P>
   With 16 laps to go, the field pitted under green-flag
conditions. Jarrett, who along with many of the leaders, came in
for fuel and emerged in first place ahead of Wallace. Earnhardt,
however, was the only driver among the leaders to take on tires, on
the right side, in addition to fuel.
</P>
<P>
   That loomed as a huge advantage when the leaders were bunched up
by the second caution of the night on Lap 147. There was debris on
the track when Kenny Irwin's car tore out of the pits with the gas
catch-can still attached. But Earnhardt's advantage was neutralized
when Jeremy Mayfield spun out in front of heavy traffic as he
exited Turn 4 and prompted the race's third and final yellow,
allowing the field to make pit stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is special,'' said Jarrett, a two-time Daytona 500
winner, of his first Pepsi 400 victory. ``To be here in Victory
Lane on July 4th weekend, when all of America is celebrating, is
special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
