<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT IN WINSTON DRIVER'S SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The last time he visited Daytona
International Speedway, Dale Jarrett wiped out in the Daytona 500
and limped away from the monster 2.5-mile trioval after finishing
37th. After completing 134 of 200 laps Feb. 14, Jarrett crashed his
red, white, and blue No. 88 Ford Credit Taurus in a Turn 4 melee
and left in 36th place _ a distant 36th place _ in the
all-important Winston Cup points standings.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Daytona for Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's Pepsi 400,
Jarrett arrived as the series points leader and expanded his
cushion to 177 points over second-place Bobby Labonte (2,674-2,497)
with his third victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Did Jarrett ever imagine, after duffing it in February, it was
possible to return to Daytona in July, at the halfway point of
season, as the early leader in the clubhouse?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yeah,'' said Jarrett, who leapfrogged from fifth to
first in the points after a May 15 victory at Richmond. ``I mean,
it's a long (season), and you realize how crazy this sport is. I
can't say that I thought we would not have any problems to this
point, but we basically haven't. Since Daytona, the closest we've
come to a problem in a race was at Las Vegas, our only race where
we finished out of the Top 10.''
</P>
<P>
   After his disappointing Daytona effort, Jarrett quickly
rebounded with a runner-up effort at Rockingham, N.C., but suffered
a setback in the third race of the season when he finished 11th at
Las Vegas. ``And that's because we ran out of gas,'' Jarrett said.
``That's the only setback we've really had. Now there have been
days where we've struggled, but we've made something out of it. But
I know we've got the team that's capable of putting together these
type of races and these type of streaks. I just hope that we can
continue, and hopefully the next time we're talking in Daytona,
it'll be about our first Winston Cup championship.''
</P>
<P>
   So what kind of marks would Jarrett give his crew at the halfway
point?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think for a total performance, I guess, as far as
getting the most out of what you got, the guys definitely would
have to get an `A,' '' Jarrett said. ``Can we get better? Yeah, I
think we can be an A-plus team. We can run better. We can finish
fourth or fifth without having to come from 25th to do that. That's
one side we want to improve this second half of the season. On days
when we're struggling to run fifth, maybe we can take those days
and turn them into seconds or firsts.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jarrett were to capture his first Winston Cup championship
this year, he would deliver Ford Motor Co. only its third title
since 1988. The late Alan Kulwicki was the last to do so in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's surprising, especially with all the good Ford
teams they've had over the years, that they haven't been able to
win the championship,'' Jarrett said. ``But hopefully it's
something that's going to change this year.''
</P>
<P>
   And Saturday &UR;  &LR; night Dale Jarrett was halfway home to that goal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd's self-owned Winston Cup outfit _ Rudd Motorsports _
was thrown for a loss Wednesday afternoon when the veteran driver
learned his No. 10 Ford Taurus had lost its sponsor of nine years,
Tide, to an upstart team being fielded by Cal Wells. Procter &AMP;
Gamble, maker of Tide, offered Rudd the opportunity to continue
driving the Tide car for Wells's team. Rudd, in so many words,
politely declined. ``To anybody that's been around a while, it
doesn't make any sense,'' said Rudd, who seemed embittered by the
fact an upstart operation with no track record stole his sponsor.
``I don't understand it myself. Had they said, ` we're going with
Robert Yates or Rick Hendrick,' or something that is established
and outperforming us this year _ and I even told them, `Hey, guys,
if you've got a chance to go with Mark Martin, Jack Roush, or Jeff
Burton, that's the place to go right now. They've got the hot
team.' But I don't understand this.'' Said Jarrett: ``I'm in no
position to judge what a company does with their money, but a guy
who's won at least one race for 15 or 16 years like Ricky has,
there aren't a lot of people who can say that. They've been in
Victory Lane, which is something a lot of people can't say, then to
go to a totally unproven team, you wonder sometimes exactly where
their strategy is at.'' Tide's move also caught Larry McReynolds
off guard. McReynolds, crew chief for Mike Skinner, had designs of
starting his own Winston Cup team and mistakenly thought he had
convinced Tide to come aboard as a sponsor, but, evidently, Tide
didn't come clean. ``They basically told us everything was right,''
McReynolds groused. ``We had all the I's dotted and all the T's
crossed. They were a little nervous about going with a new team.
But they kind of threw that theory out the window.'' . . . In other
surprising sponsor moves, US Tobacco Co., out of Greenwich, Conn.,
and Valvoline announced they were pulling the plug on their
commitments. Wednesday, US Tobacco announced it was not renewing
its Skoal Racing sponsorship with Andy Petree Racing next year due,
in large part, to the company's compliance obligations under the
Smokeless Tobacco Master Settlement Agreement signed last year.
Garnis Hagen, VP of marketing and promotion for US Tobacco, said
the company's ``departure as a team sponsor _ whose span of 18
consecutive seasons is second only to STP _ marks a change in
direction, but not in our company's belief in the sport of NASCAR
and its legion of adult race fans.'' Friday, Valvoline announced it
was pulling out of open-wheel racing, leaving CART owner Derrick
Walker without a sponsor for his driver, Gil de Ferran.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Juan Montoya continued his hot streak in the CART FedEx
Championship Series by winning last week's Medic Drug Cleveland
Grand Prix at Burke Lakefront Airport. Montoya, the 23-year-old
Colombian whiz kid, staved off a hard-charging de Ferran and
overcame wet and wild conditions at the rain-soaked 2.106-mile
temporary road course to record his fourth triumph of the season .
. . Montoya's first victory at Cleveland wound up being his last
when the race's promoter, IMG Motorsports, bolted from the CART
series and signed a deal with the Indy Racing League to become an
oval event in 2000. CART officials moved quickly to shore up the
loss on its schedule by announcing a multiyear contract extension
with the Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course. ``It was CART's desire to
continue to race at Cleveland, and it is unfortunate we could not
come to an agreement,'' said Andrew Craig, CART chairman and CEO. .
. . As part of his comeback from a serious right leg fracture
suffered in the season-opening Busch Series race at Daytona, Andy
Santerre, the 30-year-old native of Cherryfield, Maine, will
attempt to qualify for two Busch North Series events at New
Hampshire International Speedway and Watkins Glen. Santerre will
attempt to qualify for the Pennzoil/Replacement Auto Parts 100 at
NHIS. ``I always love racing at Loudon,'' said Santerre, whose plan
is to gain more seat time in the Busch North cars so that he can
make up for lost time. ``I consider it my home track, and I have
more laps around that track than probably any other Busch Series or
Winston Cup driver.''
</P>
</TEXT>
