<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADEN PROVES TOUGH ON OUT-OF-TOWNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE _ Forget about Indiana. Downey's Steve Paden showed
they can race in California, too.
</P>
<P>
   Paden proved the point by winning Saturday night's USAC Western
Midget series feature race before 5,434 at Irwindale Speedway, a
midget event that included some of the top drivers from Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to beat those guys from Indiana,'' Paden said,
referring to national midget standout Tracy Hines of Newcastle,
Ind. ``That's where we all want to be, so to run with those guys
and beat those guys, that says a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Other feature winners were 16-year-old sensation Josh Wise in
USAC TQ Midgets and Reedley's Jim Tartaglia in CAM 360 Super
Modifieds.
</P>
<P>
   Neither were as dominant as Paden, who the final 21 laps and won
by 2.126 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first time I've run this car,'' Paden said. ``I
was just feeling it out and watching the lines everyone else was
taking. I don't like to lead early on, once I saw where everyone
was, that's when I picked it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Points leader Mark DeBeaumont finished second, with Bobby Boone
third. Wally Pankratz, who qualified second, finished 18th,
retiring with a mechanical problem. Hines, who set a track record
in qualifying, finished 18th after suffering an engine failure
after four laps.
</P>
<P>
   Tartaglia, who qualified second, took advantage of a late
caution to win the 25-lap feature.
</P>
<P>
   Tartaglia trailed leader Jim Birges by nearly 10 car lengths
when Willie Northamer blew an engine, bringing out the caution on
lap 15.
</P>
<P>
   Birges got the jump on the restart, but Tartaglia quickly closed
the gap and passed him for the lead between turns 3 and 4 on lap
18.
</P>
<P>
   Birges, not fazed, reclaimed the lead on the backstretch. But
Tartaglia responded a second time and went low in turn 3 to take
the lead for good on lap 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to credit the crew,'' Tartaglia said. ``The car was
just perfect. It would stick wherever I put it. I was just lucky
enough to drive it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tartaglia took it from there, leading the final six laps before
winning by 2.79 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is just awesome,'' Tartaglia said. ``It's one great
race track and I'm glad I won here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise showed his ability to come back as well. He started sixth,
then took advantage of a caution on lap nine to take the lead for
good. Wise, who won here in May, took the lead on the restart,
going low between turns 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   He then dominated the final 11 laps before beating Greg Edenholm
at the finish by 1.205 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to be patient, said Wise, who narrowed the
gap between him and TQ Midget points leader Randi Pankratz.
``(Edenholm) was having a little problem on the restarts. He did a
little bobble and I was able to get by him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
