<HEADER>
A8884 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPALACHIA05-COX     07-04 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPALACHIA05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appalachia residents pull themselves out of poverty's pit
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCKEE, Ky. _ Tracy Bingham and her family grew up like many
around here. The rugged Appalachians corralled them, funneled them
to tobacco fields then cut them off from the economic explosion
that has roared through the South this decade.
</P>
<P>
   But, slowly, like the mountains themselves, the economic
landscape is shifting. Patches of homegrown commerce poke through
heavy layers of poverty in Jackson County.
</P>
<P>
   In between valley tobacco, abandoned Chevy pickups and rocky
outcrops next to winding two-lanes, a new convenience store springs
up here, a tax office there.
</P>
<P>
   Bingham's 18-year-old daughter, Misty, didn't like her options
after high school _ a minimum-wage factory job or boring college
courses. So in March, mother and daughter opened a combination
bakery-photo studio.
</P>
<P>
   Visions &AMP; Sugarplums isn't about to challenge, say, Pepperidge
Farms. The shop might not make money for another three months in a
county where the U.S. Census says nearly four of every 10 people
live in poverty. Still, the Binghams breathe hope into Appalachia
as business owners in a land commerce forgot.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was scheduled to visit Jackson County and
other parts of eastern Kentucky today as he starts a six-state trip
designed to encourage industry and entrepreneurship in America's
poorest communities. Clinton is courting congressional votes for
his New Markets Initiative. The plan proposes corporate tax credits
for companies that invest in what he calls the country's ``untapped
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since Lyndon Johnson came to the Kentucky Highlands 35 years
ago has a presidential visit focused on Appalachia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says we've made a mark,'' said Bingham, the wife of a
tobacco farmer. ``They know we're out here. We do matter, and there
is hope.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Clinton announced that Jackson and two other Kentucky
counties qualified for one of the nation's first rural
``empowerment zones.'' The anti-poverty program made available $40
million in federal grants and tax incentives for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   There's been some success. Jackson County's unemployment rate
has plummeted. A police department will be built. A new theater and
new sewer system are planned. More business prospects are calling,
including an Internet company whose parent firm is in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   But empowerment zones promised more than jobs, which come and
go. The bigger promise was giving a voice to residents who had been
left out while the community broke down. Some Jackson County
residents claim the zone lets small-town bosses wield control like
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it's perfect, because nothing is,'' said Mary
Purkey, a McKee native and Jackson County's third empowerment zone
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Purkey's customers include the Binghams. Now, they hope to find
better lives in French vanilla cakes and the one-room photo studio
next to the display case of crullers, raspberry pastries and
bourbon balls.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Bingham, 39, funded her start-up with a $20,000
``microloan'' to pay for her $500-a-month lease, freezers, stoves
and refrigerators. The money came from the empowerment zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been decorating cakes out of my home for 10 years but
couldn't think of starting my own business,'' said Bingham, a
full-time aide for the county school board. ``I really couldn't
afford to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   She keeps her day job for the health insurance. Bingham gets off
work at 4:30 p.m., comes to the shop and bakes sometimes till
midnight. A part-time cashier, Misty Bingham shoots prom photos and
weddings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year will be hard, but we just hope to build on
that,'' Tracy Bingham said.
</P>
<P>
   Her business would have been plum crazy 10 years ago. Decades
before that, coal companies in neighboring towns had gone bust.
That meant farmers who had been lured away by more money in a month
than they could make in a year returned to their fields in isolated
Jackson County.
</P>
<P>
   Towns failed to build their own tax bases, leaving them unable
to fund basic services. Coal money stopped flowing into school
systems, and now nearly half the residents in the Kentucky
Highlands don't have a high school education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any factories. Nobody had any money,'' Bingham
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, Jackson County's unemployment rate raged at
24 percent, poverty hung like a heavy fog and the Wal-Mart 30
minutes away killed local clothing stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of development that occurred produced a dependency on
these companies to provide services,'' said Ron Eller, director of
the Appalachian Center at the University of Kentucky. ``There's a
myth that Appalachia is poor from the lack of development. It's
just that the development patterns bypassed rural places like
Jackson County.''
</P>
<P>
   The president will fly to the Mississippi Delta on Tuesday to
tour another empowerment zone. Clinton might have ventured deeper
into Appalachia but the closest airport that could accommodate Air
Force One was in Lexington. He's travelling by helicopter to seven
other Kentucky counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a statement unto itself,'' Eller said.
</P>
<P>
   In the name of making life better, economic expansion in the
mountains has produced deep growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   The zones were designed to draw visions from the whole
community, not just traditional small-town cronies. However, a 1997
report by a Jackson County citizens group assembled to monitor the
empowerment board concluded that grass-roots participation was
discouraged by longtime insiders who pushed their own agendas.
Meetings that were supposed to be open were conducted secretly, and
residents rarely showed up when the meetings were public.
</P>
<P>
   The county administrator at the time, since voted out of office,
responded then that anyone who would say that ``has to be not just
ignorant but completely stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tremors, Jackson County seems to be climbing out of
its hole. Unemployment stands at 4.1 percent. The roll of welfare
families in the county has fallen nearly 80 percent the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not been easy,'' said Purkey, the county empowerment zone
administrator. ``We've had a generational pocket of poverty. It
descended on us in the 1940s and kept us there. People couldn't
learn how to get out. Instead of a helping hand they had a handout.
People just accepted poverty as a lifestyle, `I'll go get my food
stamps today.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Purkey's father grew tobacco and ran a grocery store. What he
couldn't buy he traded for with saws, pigs, tires _ whatever was on
the farm. The family got by all right but Purkey didn't realize how
poor they were till she traveled with a friend to Ohio and saw a
house with hallways. Her childhood house had four big rooms shared
among five siblings. ``We didn't have hallways. We had doorways,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   McKee (population 1,000) now boasts a plastics factory that
makes field vests for U.S. Marines, video rental stores and the
brand-new Deer View convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround began in 1985 when Mid-South Electrics opened a
plant in a Jackson County tobacco field. With 800 workers, the
company is the county's largest employer. It has taken out nearly
$2 million in empowerment zone loans. It is expected to be the
first stop on Clinton's tour.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor is JCR Industries Inc., a company that trains
people others have given up on. Some are uneducated while others
just don't know the basics it takes to keep a job _ showing up on
time, showing up every day, combing your hair. Most prospects are
referred by social agencies.
</P>
<P>
   JCR teaches skills that transfer to the factory floor _ sewing,
plastic injection, wire harnessing. The company moved into a $1
million building funded by the empowerment zone and now employs 100
people.
</P>
<P>
   Darlene Wilson, 40, has worked there for a year. Just before
coming to JCR, the electricity and water had been cut off at her
two-bedroom house. She married at 16, has four kids, and was about
to tumble into Appalachia's deepest crevice, a hole filled with
generations that followed generations of poor.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, James, worked odd jobs because he lacked education.
Wilson, whose parents received food stamps when she grew up, failed
her GED, has no driver's license and depends on public transit.
</P>
<P>
   In her new job, Wilson has learned to fasten a terminal at the
end of a strand of wires that is used in telephone handsets.
Minimum wage goes a long way in paying bills, even letting Wilson
splurge on a few new dresses for church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel good about myself that I'm being trained,''
Wilson said. ``I've always had hope.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
