<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   APPALACHIA _ MCKEE, Ky. _ Tracy Bingham and her family grew up
like many in these parts. The rugged Appalachians corralled them,
funneled them to tobacco fields then shielded them from the
economic explosion that's roared through the South in the 1990s.
But, slowly, like the mountains themselves, the economic landscape
is shifting. Snatches of homegrown commerce poke through heavy
layers of poverty in Jackson County. Bingham opened a bakery in
March and now searches for prosperity and a better way for her two
kids in French vanilla cakes and the one-room photo studio her
daughter opened next to the display case of crullers, raspberry
pastries and bourbon balls. In some ways, she's a symbol of the new
Appalachia, an entrepreneur in a land that commerce forgot. Today
in Jackson County and other parts of eastern Kentucky, President
Clinton starts a six-state trip designed to encourage industry and
entrepreneurship in some of America's poorest communities.
Manuel.w/photos shot by Manuel. Graphics: A map showing poverty in
Appalachia. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35 WITH PHOTOS.
MOVED
</P>
