<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, July 5:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNISTS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN _ Details to come. By William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (Moving in ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ENGLANDER-INTERVIEW _ An interview with Nathan Englander, the
young author of ``For the Relief of Unbearable Urges,'' tales about
Orthodox Jews. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-ART-AUCTION (London) _ Four disappointed bidders were
prepared to spend more than $24 million on a Degas pastel at
Sotheby's here last week in a telling sign about today's art
market: there is plenty of money to be spent but not enough great
works to spend it on. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   MARYGORDON-WRITERS _ There may be some writers who contemplate a
day's work without dread, but I don't know them. Beckett had,
tacked to the wall beside his desk, a card on which were written
the words: ``Fail. Fail again. Fail better.'' It's a bad business,
this writing. By Mary Gordon. (Another in the Writers on Writing
series.)
</P>
<P>
   SANFRANCISCO-NOTEBOOK (San Francisco) _ The words of Hitler rang
out the other night over Lower Sproul Plaza, on the campus of the
University of California at Berkeley. OK, it was part of a play,
``The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui,'' by Bertolt Brecht, in the
first-ever American appearance by Brecht's own company, the
Berliner Ensemble. (And it was Berkeley.) Still, it was a little
startling, even for a visitor to the Bay Area bent on attending a
number of events, each of which, in its way, was attracting
attention for the disjointed cultural elements it brought together.
By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   OUT-BOOK-REVIEW _ Stephen O. Murray reviews ``Out for Good: The
Struggle to Build a Gay Rights Movement in America,'' by Dudley
Clendenin and Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINE-TV-REVIEW _ Edward Said, America's foremost
Palestinian patriot and polemicist, sets forth tonight on a journey
``In Search of Palestine.'' He carries a heavy load of memories of
a homeland that was taken by force, leaving many of its people in
refugee camps or under Israeli occupation. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Moving in ``f'' category unless otherwise noted)
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-FRAUD (Undated) _ Among the factors that allowed
Martin Frankel to get away with a decade of insurance fraud was the
fact that insurance is regulated by the states. In addition to a
general lack of communication among the various state insurance
commissions, which itself offers numerous opportunities for fraud,
some states have more effective laws and regulatory agencies than
others; some states, in fact, are downright backward. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REPLAY (Undated) _ Will the new replay machines hitting the
market change television forever? By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-GARTER (Undated) _ How much will the battle to tame Year
2000 computer problems cost? When will Year 2000 computer
malfunctions hit? Which countries or industries are furthest along
_ or furthest behind _ in dealing with Y2K, as the computer
challenge is popularly known? One name comes up repeatedly when
such questions are posed: Gartner Group Inc. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC-ASSESS (Undated) _ Assessing the impact of the
music industry's technical accord over digital music. By Matt
Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Digital Commerce column: Typing
public messages is the one thing that people cannot seem to get
enough of online. Which is why Internet executives believe that the
future of even the commercial Internet depends upon making this
critical component more satisfying for everyone. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   FIBER-CHANNEL-TECH (Los Angeles) _ The Qlogic Corp. and the
Emulex Corp. are vying for leadership in fiber channel technology,
a new industry-standard approach to high-speed data transfer
between computers and separate data-storage disk drives. By Andrew
Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Items covered include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A deluge of how-to books has accompanied the introduction of
Microsoft's Office 2000 software.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two FCC commissioners take umbrage at the assumption that they
will accept the terms of the SBC-Ameritech that the agency's staff
has negotiated _ even if the commissioners plan to do precisely
that.
</P>
<P>
   _ Three Dearborn (Mich.) High School students, in town for the
Streaming Media conference, demonstrate that the coming generation
of new-media tekkies combine the skills of computer nerd and
audio-visual club geek.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-BOOKS-ONLINE (Undated) _ VarsityBooks.com, an online
seller of college textbooks, has lined up deals with a group of
colleges and universities to become the exclusive seller of
textbooks for their courses.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Teresa
Riordan.
</P>
