 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, July 5:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-MARCH (Portadown, Northern Ireland) _ Some 15,000
members of Northern Ireland's Orange Order on Sunday marched to a
towering iron wall barring them from a Catholic street here, handed
in a letter of protest, and promptly turned around. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LEESON-RETURNS (London) _ Nicholas W. Leeson set foot on
British soil Sunday for the first time since his wild trades on
Asian futures markets in 1995 ran up debts of $1.4 billion, which
brought down Britain's oldest investment bank and landed him in a
Singapore jail. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-VOTE (Mexico City) _ Mexico's largest state votes for a
governor, in a race closely watched as the last major testing
ground before the country's presidential elections next year. By
Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   KUWAIT-ELECTIONS (Kuwait) _ A landmark effort to extend voting
rights to Kuwaiti women won a substantial boost here Sunday as the
results of elections on Saturday showed big gains by liberal
candidates who will now form a substantial bloc in the Persian
Gulf's only elected Parliament. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-RUSSIA (Kuwait) _ A surprise trip to Russia by Syrian
leader Hafez Assad is looming as the first step in an expected
flurry of Middle East diplomacy that, for the first time in three
years, is suddenly showing signs of life. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak took
a few more steps Sunday toward completing what looks like a
strongly dovish Cabinet, appointing David Levy to be foreign
minister for the third time. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-PAKISTAN (Washington) _ President Clinton meets with
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif about the latest fighting
with India over Kashmir. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S.-BASES (Kadena Air Base, Japan) _ As Americans
celebrate Independence Day this weekend, Okinawans are invited to
attended an ``America Fest'' at the U.S. air base here, to them a
longtime symbol of ``great tyranny.'' By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-BIRTHRATE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Before Yugoslavia
and the Serbs went to war with the West, Vesna Markovic wanted
three children. Since the Kosovo conflict, she has often been sorry
that she has one. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-OPPOSITION (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ A leading Serbian
opposition leader, Zoran Djindjic, returns from abroad. By Blaine
Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MISSING (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ On Flora Brovina,
president of the League of Albanian Women, who was arrested by
Serbian special police two months ago and is still in prison in
Serbia, reportedly gravely ill. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TRUCKSTOP-MAKEOVER (Commerce City, Colo.) _ To the typical
``four-wheeler'' _ truck-driver slang for motorists _ the image of
the American truck stop is a grungy, tobacco-infused place serving
chicken-fried steak and 48-hour coffee. But as they zoom down I-70
toward the Rockies this weekend, travelers might be tempted to
brake for the new truck stop built by Travel Centers of America
endowed with architectural fireworks: ribbed aluminum (a nod to the
American diner), a huge striped awning (the traditional sign of
welcome) and the ultimate highway seducer _ neon. By Patricia Leigh
Brown. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POVERTY (Manchester, Ky.) When President Clinton begins
his tour of some of the nation's most entrenched poverty regions on
Monday, the entrepreneurial impulse in the eastern hollows of
Kentucky will be on his agenda as he makes his first stop in
London, Ky., 20 miles to the west down the Daniel Boone Parkway. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EVANS (Austin, Texas) _ Back in Midland, in the harrowing,
exhilarating oil days of rising gushers and falling prices, they
all had nicknames: Dennis Grubb was ``Wemus,'' George W. Bush was
``Boosto'' or ``the Bombastic Bushkin,'' Joe O'Neill was ``Spider''
and Donald L. Evans was usually ``Evvie'' or ``Donnie.'' But
sometimes, just to annoy the future politician in the rambunctious
Bush, the friends used to call Evans by another name: ``Governor.''
It's more than a little early to start casting a Bush cabinet, but
as the chief fund-raiser of Bush's campaign, Evans has shown
impressive results. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   ILL-DRIVEBY-SHOOTINGS (Chicago) _ Another shooting in the
Chicago area, possibly by the same man. An Asian-American student
was seriously wounded. By Bill Dedman.
</P>
<P>
   NH-CAMPAIGN-FOURTH (Merrimack, N.H.) _ With some of the
presidential candidates as they do holiday campaigning in New
Hampshire. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   CITIZENSHIP-TEST (New York) _ As part of one of the biggest
naturalization movements in the country's history, 1.8 million
applicants for citizenship _ the biggest group ever _ are waiting
anxiously to be tested on their knowledge of English, civics and
history. The test is at the core of one of the weightiest decisions
any nation can make: who should be a citizen? By Susan Sachs. (With
photos.)
</P>
<P>
