</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CNN-MEDIA-930&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER UPHEAVALS AT CNN, AN EXECUTIVE STILL STANDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Richard N. Kaplan, the president of CNN/U.S.A., it has been,
to say the least, an intense year of news, both on the air and off.
</P>
<P>
   First came the fiasco known as ``Tailwind,'' a report about the
alleged use of nerve gas by U.S. forces in Vietnam, which appeared
on the initial edition of Kaplan's creation _ the news magazine
series ``Newsstand.'' The ``Tailwind'' report was retracted one
year ago this week, with an abject apology to the viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Then the three-night-a-week ``Newsstand'' fell flat in the
ratings and its future became the subject of wide speculation both
in and outside CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Finally came the Lou Dobbs episode. CNN lost its star in June,
the anchor of its big moneymaker ``Moneyline News Hour,'' when
Dobbs left for an Internet venture and article after article cited
Dobbs' tense relationship with Kaplan as a reason.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after the year of turmoil, Kaplan is still standing and
is readying a plan to revamp the ``Newsstand'' format, which he and
Tom Johnson, the chairman of the network, are expected to present
soon to Ted Turner, the CNN founder and now vice chairman of its
parent company, Time Warner. ``I feel Rick has provided splendid
leadership,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   His critics inside CNN say Kaplan still has not come up with an
overall plan to find answers to one of CNN's biggest continuing
problems: generating ratings for CNN during slow news periods. But
he is generally credited with making a number of improvements,
including a total redesign of CNN's on-air look, consolidation of
its news anchors to improve quality and the elimination of repeats
in the network's hourly news cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The changes initiated by Kaplan have included bringing in news
anchors like Jeff Greenfield, Judd Rose, and Willow Bay, reducing
the number of daily anchors from 26 to 12, building separate staff
for each of the day's hourlong news segments, and increasing the
number of special reports turned out by the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made steady progress every week on all sorts of little
things,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the big things that got most of the notice. Dobbs was
one of the most important figures at CNN, not only because he was
the president of its financial news network, CNNfn, but because
``Moneyline'' brought in the biggest per-commercial price of any
show on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs declined to tie his departure directly to his differences
with Kaplan. But Kaplan acknowledged that ``there was tension''
between him and Dobbs. ``We were clearly different people,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he had been thrust into the middle of the dispute
between the two men, which he called ``a clash of two dynamic
personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   The main area of disagreement, Johnson said, was Dobbs'
conviction that Kaplan's ``Newsstand'' franchise was sucking up
financial resources that could have been going to CNNfn. ``Lou
really believed that,'' Johnson said. ``But he was mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said money allocated to ``Newsstand'' was in a totally
separate budget that was never available to CNNfn, a point
supported by Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But the focus on resources being directed toward ``Newsstand''
only underscored what one CNN executive, speaking on the condition
of anonymity, called ``the little secret'' inside the network: that
``Newsstand'' has not performed up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit of a politically sensitive subject at CNN,'' the
executive said. ``Nobody has said much about it. It's a little like
criticism in the Kremlin. The one person who criticized it was Lou
Dobbs. But the show has really had zero impact, and it has been
losing millions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratings for the series have certainly been low, and they got
even worse when Kaplan decided to move the show from a starting
time of 10 p.m. to 8 p.m. But he argued that an audience for any
show in television ``takes time to build.'' He said, ``It's about
continuity.''
</P>
<P>
   When he created the three-weekly edition of ``Newsstand,''
Kaplan was taking advantage of the associations with magazines also
owned by Time Warner. The shows are produced in conjunction with
Time, Fortune and Entertainment Weekly. Kaplan said he was
attempting to create ``appointment shows'' for the network.
</P>
<P>
   That had become a priority for CNN because the network's ratings
_ and profits _ tend to rise and fall with the tides of breaking
news. During big stories, the network does well; in slow news
periods, it struggles. Now that CNN has competition from both MSNBC
and Fox News, it is even more important to generate more dependable
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said CNN prized its reputation as the breaking-news
network. ``But I am not content simply being the breaking-news
network,'' he said. ``I really want us to have other shows that
people come to us for that are still within the news category.''
</P>
<P>
   But both executives conceded that it was possible viewers had
such built-in expectations that CNN would be reporting on the news
every hour that a preproduced news magazine might not be what they
were looking for. ``Viewers tuning in to see Kosovo may not want to
run into `Entertainment Weekly,''' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kaplan nor Johnson would say specifically what changes
they had in mind for the series. Johnson would only say, ``We may
be looking at doing segments of these shows inside other news
shows.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kaplan disputed the charge that `Newsstand'' had been an
unusually expensive project to mount. He said that the three
editions of ``Newsstand'' cost less than a single edition of any
news-magazine program on a broadcast network.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That is an area Kaplan is intimately familiar with, because he
was the original executive producer on ABC's ``Prime Time Live.''
He also served as executive producer on both ``Nightline'' and
``World News Tonight'' for ABC, winning more than 30 Emmy awards,
four Alfred I. Dupont-Columbia University Journalism Awards and
numerous other journalism prizes during his tenure at ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the credentials that induced Johnson to recruit Kaplan
so aggressively. He said he had worked on bringing Kaplan to CNN
for more than two years before he finally agreed to join the
network in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But in the aftermath of the ill-fated ``Tailwind'' report on the
very first edition of the Time/CNN Sunday night edition of
``Newsstand,'' some CNN staff members engaged in serious debate
about Kaplan's future at the network.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson defended Kaplan then and he continues to now. He said
that while the ``Tailwind'' incident ``hurt badly,'' it ``hurt all
of us,'' and not merely Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people who worked on that report were at CNN long
before Rick arrived,'' Johnson said. He added that he believed the
network was now past the fallout from the incident, and cited a
recent poll that showed 70 percent of the public saying they
trusted CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he continued to trust Kaplan. ``We are a much
stronger channel journalistically now,'' Johnson said. And, as if
to tamp down any doubt that might remain, Johnson added the
endorsement of the vice chairman and chairman of Time Warner for
good measure: ``Ted Turner and Gerry Levin feel the same way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
