 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Monday, July 5. The N.Y. Times News Service Weekend Editor
is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-PAKISTAN (Washington) _ President Clinton meets Sunday with
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif about the latest fighting
with India over Kashmir. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-BIRTHRATE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Before Yugoslavia
and the Serbs went to war with the West, Vesna Markovic wanted
three children. Since the Kosovo conflict, she has often been sorry
that she has one. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TRUCKSTOP-MAKEOVER (Commerce City, Colo.) _ To the typical
``four-wheeler'' _truck-driver slang for motorists _ the image of
the American truck stop is a grungy, tobacco-infused place serving
chicken-fried steak and 48-hour coffee. But as they zoom down I-70
toward the Rockies this weekend, travelers might be tempted to
brake for the new truck stop built by Travel Centers of America
endowed with architectural fireworks: ribbed aluminum (a nod to the
American diner), a huge striped awning (the traditional sign of
welcome) and the ultimate highway seducer _ neon. By Patricia Leigh
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   CITIZENSHIP-TEST (New York) _ As part of one of the biggest
naturalization movements in the country's history, 1.8 million
applicants for citizenship _ the biggest group ever _ are waiting
anxiously to be tested on their knowledge of English, civics and
history. The test is at the core of one of the weightiest decisions
any nation can make: who should be a citizen? By Susan Sachs. (With
photos.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POVERTY (Manchester, Ky.) When President Clinton begins
his tour of some of the nation's most entrenched poverty regions on
Monday, the entrepreneurial impulse in the eastern hollows of
Kentucky will be on his agenda as he makes his first stop in
London, Ky., 20 miles to the west down the Daniel Boone Parkway. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-FRAUD (Undated) _ Among the factors that allowed
Martin Frankel to get away with a decade of insurance fraud was the
fact that insurance is regulated by the states. In addition to a
general lack of communication among the various state insurance
commissions, which itself offers numerous opportunities for fraud,
some states have more effective laws and regulatory agencies than
others; some states, in fact, are downright backward. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN (Wimbledon, England) _ Pete Sampras
strengthened his place in tennis history Sunday in an all-American
final on the Fourth of July, winning with a flawless grass-court
performance in overwhelming Andre Agassi 6-3, 6-4, 7-5 for his
sixth Wimbledon title in seven years. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN (Wimbledon, England) _ Lindsey Davenport
defeated Steffi Graf 6-4, 7-5 on Sunday to win the most coveted
tennis title in the world. After the match, just as she had done in
Paris last month after winning the French Open _ her 22nd Slam
title _ Graf announced that she was retiring from this Slam event.
By Robin Finn.
</P>
