<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8986 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAR-SPANGLED-CANDIDA     07-04 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-SPANGLED-CANDIDATES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE DOODLE DANDIES: BUSH AND GORE NOT REALLY SUCH BORES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors _ TIMELY for 4th of July)   (This excellent 1,000-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 3 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The flags are out, the barbecues smoking, but this Fourth of
July in America has an odd feel about it. It seems more like Labor
Day 2000, the date next September that will kick off the
presidential election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The two front-runners, Al Gore for the Democrats and George W.
Bush for the Republicans, are all but nominated and anointed. There
seems almost no point in dragging things on for another 14 months,
through tedious caucuses and primaries and party conventions.
Surely it's all over now.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent inevitability of these two candidates springs,
first, from money. Gore raised $18.5 million in the first half of
this year, scaring off all his rivals except Bill Bradley, a former
senator from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush raised $35.5 million, a record. And both have netted
almost all the political endorsements that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Thus armed, they will proceed into primary elections in which
three big, delegate-rich states _ California, New York and New
Jersey _ have moved up their vote to March 7, much earlier than
usual.
</P>
<P>
   If these three plump for the same candidate, the parties'
nominations will be tied up then and there.
</P>
<P>
   Upsets are not impossible, of course. On the Democratic side,
Gore _ for all his attempts to distance himself _ may find he
cannot shake the disreputable shade of Bill Clinton, and may suffer
more than he supposes from Bradley's popularity in the states that
vote on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, where ten rivals are squeaking around
him, George W. may yet be tripped up by his rakish past or by his
father's old ailment, foot-in-mouth disease.
</P>
<P>
   For both men, the close embrace of their party establishments
may damage them with voters. But by the same token, it is hard to
imagine _ short of giant scandal _ that either party will now
abandon the candidate on whom it has staked so much.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, this turn of events seems depressingly
undemocratic. The political debate has apparently ended before it
has even begun.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing Republicans and left-wing Democrats alike are
dismayed, even furious, that the field has been left to two bland
centrists whose mottoes (Bush's ``compassionate conservatism'' and
Gore's ``practical idealism'') seem no more than vapid mush.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fears are misplaced. Yes, there will probably be two
centrist nominees; but that has very often been the result of the
primary process in recent years. Looking beyond the primaries to
the election itself, the prospects are as tantalizing _ and as
unpredictable _ as they have ever been.
</P>
<P>
   First, the candidates themselves. It is true that both are,
broadly speaking, centrists, but important distinctions are
emerging.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is a meddler, whereas Bush believes in keeping government
in check; Bush is an unabashed free-trader, but Gore hedges his
enthusiasm with conditions; Bush has pledged not to raise taxes,
Gore has kept his powder dry.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, these positions mean little to voters lulled
along on the eighth year of an economic boom. And Alan Greenspan's
decision this week to raise interest rates by just a quarter of a
point, never mind that it was the first increase for two and a half
years, will do little to disturb their equanimity: the change had
been widely expected and when it came the markets applauded
politely.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fact remains, labor markets are too tight to avoid
wage-pressure indefinitely; and Wall Street remains exuberantly
overextended. These are risks.
</P>
<P>
   By election day, voters may well be asking themselves which
candidate, Bush or Gore, will do less harm to the economy. Looking
further ahead, voters must ask which man can meet the country's
biggest social-policy challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Two of America's costliest entitlement programs, Medicare
(health care for the elderly) and Social Security (pensions), will
go bust within a generation if they are not reformed. Both need
thoroughgoing change, not tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   Such change is made possible by budget surpluses that may be
$500 billion larger than estimated just last February. But it is
not yet clear which candidate would be braver.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is more inclined to keep Medicare and Social Security
solvent by spending budget surpluses on them. Bush may be willing
to privatize Social Security by introducing individual retirement
accounts (as The Economist would like) but he may well succumb
instead to an across-the-board tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   So this election is wide open and its effects long-lasting; and
not just in respect of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In both the House of Representatives and the Senate, the
Republican majority is so slender that it might well be overturned
_ and popular loathing for the House Republicans means they could
suffer on election day even if Bush triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   If either candidate has coattails that reach right down to state
level, he can influence the party balance in the state legislatures
which, after 2000, will be redrawing the lines of congressional
districts (hence affecting future elections).
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, whoever wins will have the chance to change the color of
the Supreme Court. At present, the court has a very narrow, but
highly active, conservative majority which has been working, most
notably, to change the balance of power between the federal
government and the states.
</P>
<P>
   With two or three retirements likely to come in the next
presidential term, the conservatives could either be strengthened,
under Bush, or, under Gore, consigned to the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   In all these ways, the election of 2000 could prove more
exciting, and more decisive for the course of America, than many
before it.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Gore and Bush caravans roll remorsely on, crushing
all before them; even if next year's primaries have all the
suspense of a seaside Punch and Judy show; even if neither
candidate puts a foot wrong (and that makes a lot of even-ifs), the
American political scene has seldom been so open to change.
</P>
<P>
   There is everything to play, and vote, for. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,000-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
