<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONDURAS-KID-MEDIA-NY     07-04 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-KID-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUPED EDITORS SHRUG OFF CONCERNS OVER PROMINENT PLAY FOR RUNAWAY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Journalists are often accused of being cynical. But you wouldn't
have known it last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bewitched by a 13-year-old Honduran boy's virtuoso fabrications,
every news outlet in New York passed along his fanciful tale: that
he had lost his immediate family in the mudslides caused by
Hurricane Mitch; that his father had sent him a letter with money
to bring him to New York and instructions to meet outside La
Guardia Airport; that he had traveled 3,200 miles to New York, by
hitchhiking and taking a bus, in search of a father he had never
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, sweetheart. Get me rewrite! The New York news media,
reputed to eat nails for breakfast and disbelieve its various
mothers, swallowed it whole. On the kind of day that harked back to
the era of journalism romanticized in the Ben Hecht play ``The
Front Page,'' reporters clamored for details. And they found
confirmation everywhere they turned. Kind cafeteria patrons in
Florida had helped the boy. So had a Bronx livery driver. Most of
all, the police said they believed it.
</P>
<P>
   Even the neutral language of slugs _ abbreviated article names
used in newsrooms _ reflected the appeal of the young tale spinner.
``Boy's Quest'' was the slug The Associated Press gave its initial
article. Like the accounts themselves, it was poignant _ not to
mention false _ as reporters for Newsday and the AP discovered on
Tuesday when they visited the village of San Buenaventura, where
the boy, Edwin Daniel Sabillon, once lived with his grandmother. It
turned out that the boy's father had recently died and the boy had
been living with an aunt in Hialeah, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   If there was no joy in the city's newsrooms at the discovery,
there was little self-flagellation either. Stuart Marques, The New
York Post's managing editor, said the story should have been
questioned. ``I don't know what the lessons are,'' he said. ``You
don't want to always be so cynical. To say, `Oh, this kid is
pulling our legs.' The first reaction is to help the kid. Your
heart goes out to him. I think I'd rather be burned once in a while
than have no heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Purnick, the metropolitan editor of The New York Times,
which, like the Daily News, published the account on its front
page, said: ``I don't see this as a major black eye for the media.
I know that's the temptation. But I don't see it. Thanks to the AP,
we self-corrected pretty quickly. Other than putting a line in here
and phrase in there, we couldn't have done anything differently.
Ideally, we check out every fact we can _ but we couldn't.
Everything was pointing to this account being true.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with reporters who covered the story and their
editors revealed crucial obstacles to fact-checking. Most
importantly, the primary source, Edwin Sabillon, was unavailable,
so reporters fell back on the people he spoke to _ all of whom were
themselves fooled.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the New York City Police Department had alerted
police-beat reporters to the boy's existence early on Monday
morning. When City Hall learned of the media interest in the story,
it clamped down on information. But there were leaks, some
reporters said, from people who seemed to be in the know.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the leaks indicated that there were documents partially
corroborating the boy's story. Messages were passed implying that
the police had read the letter the boy's father had supposedly sent
_ a letter that, it seems now, did not exist. Reporters received
strong hints that a firm that wires money to Central America had
confirmed it had sent money from the father, Grevis Sabillon, to
his son, and was searching its records for documentation.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Edwin Sabillon is a child, and children tend to get the
benefit of any doubt _ particularly children who are suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect children to be as deceptive as this young boy
was, on such a grand and inventive scale,'' said Arthur J. Browne,
the senior managing editor of the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had fictionalized the minor details, he may have gotten
caught a lot easier,'' Browne said. ``The story was so larger than
life, and he had just enough of the brush strokes to make it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Moss, a professor at New York University who runs the
university's Urban Research Center, said the boy's account was a
parable that fit neatly into the symbolic shorthand that most
people use to understand events. ``Honduras became a symbol of
disaster,'' he said. ``Then there's immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Everybody wants to believe good news about New York.
This reinforced the mythology that people are dying to come here,
and when they get here, it welcomes them. Everyone wanted to
believe.''
</P>
<P>
   What three of the five major print outlets failed to do,
however, was telegraph prominently that, essentially, the boy was
the sole source for many crucial details. Only the New York Post
and the AP explicitly gave sources _ ``officials'' or ``the
police'' _ for the basic facts at the top of their articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone probably would have been well advised to use words
like `the boy says,' or `the boy says and the proper authorities
have invested it with a great deal of credibility,' '' Browne said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Purnick agreed. ``In retrospect, of course, we should have
attributed'' the account. But even that ``wouldn't have changed the
tone'' of the final article, she added.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the best place to check the boy's tale was the
Honduran village where his grandmother lived. Newsday and the AP
were the only news organizations that moved quickly to get
reporters there _ though not, their editors say, because they were
skeptical of the boy's account. They simply wanted a good follow-up
article.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday morning, Newsday's reporter, Geoffrey Mohan, was in
the village of San Buenaventura, hearing the boy's grandmother and
uncle contradict the story. On Tuesday afternoon, Freddy Cuevas of
the AP was in the same place hearing the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end,'' Browne said, ``this was not an error that causes
any harm. If anything, it's a misdemeanor of the heart. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-99 1645EDT &QL; 
