<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`OLD-GLORY'-FLAG-WAVING-600&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S CHIC NEW PATRIOTISM  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for 4th of July coverage!)   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week
beginning 3 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A HELPFUL 175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 600. TOTAL UNCUT VERSION
IS 1,100 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It flutters over every public building, and above thousands upon
thousands of suburban front doors; children salute it at school;
soldiers stand to attention before it; in its presence even
presidents sometimes shed a tear.
</P>
<P>
   There is surely no flag in the world quite as famous, quite as
instantly recognizable, as the ``stars and stripes'' _ ``Old
Glory,'' as Captain William Driver named it when in 1831 he set
sail from Salem, Mass., for the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign malcontents (be they Iranians under Ayatollah Khomeini,
or Serbs under Slobodan Milosevic) may detest it, but good-hearted
Americans worship it.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, as on every July 4th, they will show their faith
by the millions as they variously sing and screech their way
through Francis Scott Key's ``The Star Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   But what exactly does this profession of faith mean? ``Nothing
is more embarrassing in the ordinary intercourse of life,'' wrote
Alexis de Tocqueville in 1835, ``than this irritable patriotism of
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Since ``chauvinist'' derives from a Frenchman, this is perhaps
an example of the pot calling the kettle black. But it is easy for
non-Americans to see what de Tocqueville had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Most foreigners reserve their vocal outbursts of patriotism for
tennis matches and other forms of symbolic warfare. Americans are
less discriminating.
</P>
<P>
   Of course they love their sports teams, which is why much of the
televised Olympics coverage, for example, was edited to show the
American competitors in the best light _ regardless of reality in
some far off, foreign stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But is it really necessary for the typical television commercial
to proclaim that a breakfast cereal or a headache pill is
``America's favorite?'' Would sales plunge if it were also known to
be Mexico's favorite?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they would, given the average American's disdain for his
southern neighbor, although other foreigners do better: some TV
commercials proudly proclaim a product's ``European'' design.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying question is why the nationality has to be
defined in the first place _ and whether the constant allusion to
patriotism devalues it.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, depends on what you mean by patriotism.
``Our country, right or wrong'' is a definition that would make a
traitor of every American who disapproved of the Vietnam war _
which seems a bit harsh not just on ``Hanoi Jane'' Fonda but also
on the draft-dodger at present residing in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The better definition is surely a belief in those
characteristics that make America the envy of the world: the rule
of law; the democratic process; and the rights of the individuals
to believe and say whatever they wish.
</P>
<P>
   It is heartening that in a recent poll by the Pew Research
Center, the top three reasons cited for America's success are the
Constitution, free elections and free enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   How disheartening, then, that the great majority of Americans
apparently believe these strengths will be diminished unless the
star-spangled banner _ a piece of cloth with 50 stars and 13
alternate stripes _ is protected by law from burning and other acts
of ``desecration.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, the House of Representatives voted
305-124 for a constitutional amendment saying: ``The Congress shall
have the power to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of
the United States.'' All the states except Vermont have passed
similar legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, if just two senators in Washington change their
minds, there will be enough votes in the country's legislatures to
amend the Constitution for only the 28th time in two centuries. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 600) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lest theory become reality, Americans would do well to consider
why the flag is not protected in the first place. On two occasions,
in 1989 and 1990, the Supreme Court has ruled that to desecrate the
flag is a right protected by the first amendment's guarantee of
free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Is it really sensible to limit that right for the sake of a
symbol? And how exactly would ``desecration'' be determined? There
have been only 70 or so political acts against the flag in the past
decade, but the image of the flag has been debased on coffee mugs
and T-shirts by the millions.
</P>
<P>
   By definition symbols convey meaning, and people therefore
tamper with them at their peril (witness the mixed emotions of race
and tradition when the Confederate flag is flown in the South, or
the horror when some white supremacist burns a cross or daubs a
swastika).
</P>
<P>
   But the flag that has represented the Union ever since 1777 will
be truly threatened only if Americans start tampering with their
idea of patriotism. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country right or wrong'' is a definition that
traditionally implied a willingness to die for America and its
values.
</P>
<P>
   In the First World War that meant some 114,000 American
servicemen sacrificed their lives in a conflict that was
essentially Europe's; in the Second World War, the American toll
was 292,000; in Korea it was 54,000; in Vietnam it was 58,000; and
in the Gulf war it was 383 (235 of them from accidents, training
deaths or ``friendly fire'').
</P>
<P>
   But what was it in Kosovo, supposedly the first war waged by
America solely for the humanitarian and civil ideals it holds dear?
The answer is that not one American lost his or her life in combat
(though two died in a helicopter accident).
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton asserted that because of America's
values, it was America's duty to go to war; yet, from the
beginning, he declared his unwillingness to put ground troops ``in
harm's way,'' as Captain John Paul Jones once put it when fighting
the British.
</P>
<P>
   War was to be a high-tech affair, waged from 15,000 feet above
the ground and pictured on the nation's TV screens almost as a
video game. This is not to belittle the skills of the high-tech
warriors, but it does raise an interesting question.
</P>
<P>
   If something is not worth dying for, can it still be worth
fighting for?
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters like to argue that America's patriotism is alive
and well, and that it has recovered from its post-Vietnam malaise
(some 70 percent of Americans polled last year considered
patriotism ``very important,'' compared with only 43 percent in
1976).
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that in the Vietnam era patriotism was put to
the test, and was genuine on both sides of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, today's patriotism too often seems for show, a
matter of waving the flag as if that alone will sustain America as
the land of the free and the home of the brave. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,100-word (uncut) ECONOMIST article, it
must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-99 1648EDT &QL; 
