<HEADER>
A8994 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERRIES-OF-WRATH-WASH     07-04 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERRIES-OF-WRATH-WASH-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHERRIES OF WRATH: THE MISERY OF WASHINGTON'S MIGRANT WORKERS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Seattle, Washington-State Editors)   (This excellent 525-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 3 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ No, the people of Washington state are not all
Microsoft millionaires or comfortably middle-class Boeing
machinists. Just now, thousands of migrant workers are laboring to
harvest cherries.
</P>
<P>
   This is a lucrative crop, worth more than $1,800 a ton to
growers. Picking is a skilled job, requiring nimble fingers to keep
the stalk attached to the fruit and avoid damage to the tender
cherry bud just above. It also entails rising at 4:30 a.m. and
working well into the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Pickers earn between $2.50 and $4 a box. If a picker skips lunch
and works until dark, he can get perhaps $80 or $100 a day.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the work has been made even tougher. Thousands of
workers who formerly camped in makeshift but at least convenient
camps on growers' farms are now scrambling to find shelter in
forests, beside rivers, or in private or state-run campgrounds,
many of them far away from the cherry orchards.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: federal regulators at the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration (OSHA) ruled in May that the growers' camps
were not clean or safe enough. But no alternatives have been
provided.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say they were caught off-guard by OSHA's
decision. This assertion is somewhat undercut by the fact that, two
years ago, the courts ruled that the state could not use camps that
failed to meet federal requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the state had been using farm camps as a stopgap
until better housing could be found not only for cherry pickers but
also for pluckers of the state's apples, pears and peaches.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA, for its part, waited until pickers were heading to
Washington state from as far away as Texas before clamping down. By
that time, 5,000 pickers were already hunting for places to stay;
up to 1,600 more have since arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The 60,000 or so farm workers of Washington state, many of whom
are Latinos speaking little or no English, are all but powerless.
</P>
<P>
   The farming-dependent eastern half of the state (Republican and
conservative) stoutly resists efforts by the western half
(Democratic and liberal) to improve things.
</P>
<P>
   The result is misery for pickers in small towns such as Mattawa,
on the banks of the Columbia River near the center of the state.
</P>
<P>
   A thin crop caused by a cool spring has kept down the number of
pickers, but even so many are living in awful conditions, without
electricity, running water, toilets or even ways of keeping their
modest property safe during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, whose road-weary workers are sluggish on the job, are
not happy either. But many growers seem to realize that a bit more
of their profits had better be spent on the workers.
</P>
<P>
   After all, growing cherries is proving so profitable that the
amount of land used for it has doubled in the past decade, and may
double again in the next. That will mean some 30 billion cherries
needing to be picked in the next ten years.
</P>
<P>
   The pickers whose hands reach into the trees will need a place
to live. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 525-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
