<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-SUCCESSES-SOUR-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY HITS `SUPERMODELS' CHILE AND COLOMBIA  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week
beginning 3 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO _ Through all the unhappy turbulence of Latin America's
recent economic history, two countries have shone radiantly, Chile
and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   In Chile, economic growth has averaged 7 percent per year since
1990, income per person has almost doubled and annual inflation has
fallen from 27 percent to under 5 percent _ all mainly thanks to
the market policies adopted by General Augusto Pinochet's
dictatorship and maintained by its democratic successors.
</P>
<P>
   And Colombia, despite mounting political violence, managed to
sustain growth averaging 4.1 percent a year from 1984 to 1997,
chiefly because of its consistently prudent policies.
</P>
<P>
   In different ways, both countries have been models for the
region. This year most of Latin America is suffering recession,
mainly because of low prices for exports of raw materials and
investors' retreat from emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is recovering more quickly than expected after its
January devaluation, and Mexico is still growing, thanks to its
close links to the booming economy in the United States. But
elsewhere, recent data suggest that the slump will be deeper and
longer than forecast, with little recovery until next year.
</P>
<P>
   This time the region's two model economies have not been spared.
Both are in recession _ for the first time since the early 1980s in
Chile and, remarkably, since the 1930s in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   But Chile's problems look far more manageable than those of
Colombia. Chile's economy came to a halt a year ago; since
September, it has been shrinking, compared with the same period in
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In May, unemployment reached 10 percent, its highest level in a
decade. The main reason: the collapse in Asia's demand for copper,
which accounts for about two-fifths of Chile's exports, and whose
price has fallen to its lowest level since the 1930s (though
recovery may now be under way).
</P>
<P>
   To that, add bad luck and policy mistakes. One of Chile's worst
droughts this century has affected the (mainly hydroelectric) power
industry; energy shortages shaved at least 0.7 percent from GDP
between January and March.
</P>
<P>
   And Chile's exports of manufactures have suffered from recession
in Argentina and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, President Eduardo Frei's officials had confidently
predicted that Chile, with its budget surplus and solid
international reserves, would easily weather the storm. But
domestic consumption, fueled by new prosperity, was increasing well
ahead of income, while higher investment was financed largely by
foreign borrowing.
</P>
<P>
   The current-account deficit rose to a worrying 5.4 percent of
GDP in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Having stoked an overheated economy with interest-rate cuts, the
Central Bank eventually had to douse it. It squeezed liquidity so
sharply last year that commercial banks almost stopped lending.
</P>
<P>
   With a presidential election in December, the government is now
trying to speed recovery. On June 21 Frei announced a spending
package, designed to stiffen the sagging construction industry and
tide small businesses over the next few rough months.
</P>
<P>
   To help out, the supposedly independent Central Bank cut
interest rates for the tenth time since October. Business leaders
cheered. Critics fear that the new measures, which will not have an
effect for several months, could fuel more overheating next year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Chile can no longer take rapid growth for
granted. It may already have harvested most of the benefits of the
structural reforms of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The task for the next president (likely to be Ricardo Lagos, a
moderate social democrat) will be to reduce his country's
dependence on copper, by fostering innovation and entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   And Chile may find itself more dependent on international
financial markets. In the past, it has taxed short-term inflows of
foreign capital to reduce its vulnerability to sudden outflows. But
domestic savings, stuck at 20-24 percent of GDP, are too low to
finance another decade of growth on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos says that 7 percent growth is possible from 2001,
providing savings increase to 28 percent of GDP. But higher savings
are a consequence more than a cause of growth.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts are more cautious. Leonardo Suarez of Larrain
Vial, a Santiago stockbroker, forecasts growth of less than 5
percent per year for the next decade. Not bad, but no longer in the
supermodel class.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's decline is more marked, and its causes more complex.
The immediate issue is the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   After spending $220 million of its $8.7 billion of reserves in
two days, on June 27 President Andres Pastrana's government in
effect devalued the currency by 10 percent, by lowering (and
widening) the band in which it trades.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came just as Richard Grasso, the chairman of
the New York Stock Exchange, was visiting a leader of Colombia's
FARC guerrillas, to give him ``a tutorial,'' he said, ``on...(the)
democratization of capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the peso did not immediately sink to the floor of its new
band, it is by no means certain that the new rate will hold.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's recession is more severe than Chile's: output has
been falling since the middle of last year, and may shrink by up to
2.5 percent this year (though the official forecast is of 0.5
percent growth).
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment in the main cities now stands at almost 20 percent,
up from 12 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The government has no appetite for increasing interest rates (as
it did last year) to fend off any further attack on the currency.
</P>
<P>
   The international credit-rating agencies have indicated that
they may deprive Colombia of its coveted ``investment grade''
(low-risk) rating.
</P>
<P>
   What has driven Colombia's economy into its worst mess in almost
70 years?
</P>
<P>
   Decentralization of public spending has undermined traditional
fiscal prudence; so too, did Pastrana's predecessor, Ernesto
Samper.
</P>
<P>
   Under his government, between 1994 and 1998 Colombia borrowed to
spend: the public finances moved from balance to a deficit of 3.8
percent of GDP, while the current-account deficit ballooned from
4.5 percent of GDP to 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, an intensifying guerrilla war has
undermined investment and confidence. An earthquake in January
shook the main coffee-growing region. The woes of neighboring
Venezuela and Ecuador have hurt exports. And banks have been hit by
a surge in bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes of recovery depend partly on financial reform. Officials
claim that a scheme to help private banks clean up their balance
sheets is at last starting to work.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the private banks managed to make a profit in April and
May, says Juan Carlos Echeverry at the national planning
department.
</P>
<P>
   The government also proposes to bring in further fiscal reform.
That may not be easy _ especially since Pastrana must try to
satisfy demands for more social spending as he tries to persuade
his country's guerrillas to make peace.
</P>
<P>
   How he must envy Frei, who, thanks to Chile's fiscal virtue, can
afford to speed recovery though pump-priming, and whose political
difficulties seem minor. &QL; 
