<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANFRANCISCO-NOTEBOOK     07-04 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANFRANCISCO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENTION GRABBERS IN A CULTURAL OUTPOURING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C.)  (nk) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The words of Hitler rang out the other night
over Lower Sproul Plaza, on the campus of the University of
California at Berkeley. OK, it was part of a play, ``The Resistible
Rise of Arturo Ui,'' by Bertolt Brecht, in the first American
appearance by Brecht's own company, the Berliner Ensemble. (And it
 &UR; was &LR;  Berkeley.) Still, it was a little startling, even for a
visitor to the Bay Area bent on attending a number of events, each
of which, in its way, was attracting attention for the disjointed
cultural elements it brought together.
</P>
<P>
   The classical extravaganzas _ the San Francisco Symphony's
Stravinsky festival and the San Francisco Opera's Wagnerian
``Ring'' _ that commandeered the cultural headlines here in late
spring yielded the spotlight to more cross-cultural fare. For one
thing, on June 16, near downtown in the not-so-long-ago downtrodden
area south of Market Street, the Sony Corp. opened Metreon, a
mammoth (350,000 square feet) $85 million indoor entertainment
complex that is not a food court, not a theme park and please not a
mall, employees say, though Metreon has elements of all three.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first weekend, more than 150,000 people had
passed through the doors, heading for one of the 15 movie theaters
plus the Imax theater, several restaurants and retailers (including
the first Microsoft store, which has, among other things, a display
informing people they can plan a wedding with technology products)
and three ``interactive attractions'' for children. Well, mostly
for children.
</P>
<P>
   One is based on David Macaulay's book ``The Way Things Work''.
The second recreates, on a large scale, the Maurice Sendak fable
``Where the Wild Things Are.'' And the third, half video arcade,
half flight deck of the Starship Enterprise, is known as the
Airtight Garage, a high-tech game room (with a bar) whose video
displays are drawn from the work of Jean Giraud, the graphic
novelist.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the crowds _ the place was overflowing with
teen-agers and families on a midweek midafternoon _ it makes vast
sense as a commercial enterprise. The oddity is in its location,
just across the Yerba Buena Gardens from the San Francisco Museum
of Modern Art, the two buildings now the twin pillars of a
flowering arts district that a mere five years ago was a wasteland
but that now includes the Moscone Center, a convention center and a
performance hall and is awaiting completion of a Jewish museum and
a Mexican museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was wino country,'' said David A. Ross, the executive
director of the modern art museum, still somewhat amazed, like many
San Franciscans, at the changes being wrought in the neighborhood.
He spoke over dinner at Montage, Metreon's upscale restaurant,
where a screen above the table was showing an excerpt from a
surreal video by the artist Bill Viola, subject of a 25-year
retrospective currently featured at the museum across the square.
Ross had just emerged from the Airtight Garage, and the contrasting
uses of imaginative video had not escaped him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely sets up an alpha-omega situation in which the
uses of advancing technology are shown at their extremes,'' he
said. ``Viola creates an immersive, emotional and spiritual
response, a quiet zone, and Metreon is about generating a maximum
of excitement, interactive and enervating.'' Realizing he sounded a
bit grudging in his enthusiasm, he continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be less than honest if I said I hadn't been looking
forward to this place opening,'' he said, ``looking forward to what
businesses can do with technology, finding new ways of thrilling
us. That's how the movie business got started.''
</P>
<P>
   Metreon predicts that 5 million to 7 million people will pass
through its attractions annually, dwarfing the 800,000 who visited
the museum last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still are telling the story of modern art in an enjoyable
way,'' said Ross, whose first museum job, at the Everson Museum in
Syracuse, N.Y., in the early 1970s, was as curator of video art. He
sounded only a tad jealous. ``But let's face it. We're not an urban
entertainment center.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he predicted that the crowds drawn to the area by Metreon
would increase visitors to his museum enough that he would end up
expanding museum hours to encourage and accommodate the crossover.
</P>
<P>
   A short walk from Metreon, at the Geary Theater, around the
corner from the tourist mecca of Union Square, the American
Conservatory Theater was presenting ``Tartuffe,'' in a production
directed by Charles Randolph-Wright, who reimagined the
17th-century French farce among upper-class blacks in Durham, N.C.,
in the 1950s. Moliere's charlatan man of the cloth is not entirely
transfigured in the guise of a hypocritical black cult figure out
to claim the virtue of rich women and the purse of rich men, all in
the name of God.
</P>
<P>
   Played with jaunty ribaldry by a largely black cast speaking the
cleverly singsong verse translation of the poet Richard Wilbur with
a varying commitment to formal diction, and closing with the Frank
Sinatra recording of ``Love and Marriage'' made familiar to a
contemporary generation by the sitcom ``Married With Children,''
the production sought actively to meld comic sensibilities three
centuries apart. ``Reverend Ike meets Dracula'' is how the director
described it; Moliere meets the WB network would also be apt.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, perhaps, to judge by some eavesdropping after one
midweek performance, audiences left the theater either appalled or
tickled. Among the latter was Jessica Milner Davis, a professor of
theater and film studies at the University of New South Wales in
Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was brilliant,'' she said. ``Totally faithful to
Moliere's original spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
