<DOCNO> NYT19990704.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANFRANCISCO-NOTEBOOK     07-04 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANFRANCISCO-NOTEBOOK-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SAN FRANCISCO: original spirit.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Davis was in town to deliver a paper on styles of humor in
literature at the International Humor Conference, which was held
last week at Holy Names College across the bay in Oakland. An
annual gathering (the first was held in Cardiff, Wales, in 1976) of
academics who study humor _ only some of whom, even they will
admit, are funny _ is a funny notion in itself, of course.
</P>
<P>
   But the range of papers, from the blindingly arcane (``Indecency
or Innovation? Sexual and Esthetic Transgression in Early
20th-Century Comic Drama by Women'') to the sociologically
semirelevant (``Clinton Jokes as a Window to American Culture'') to
the seemingly useful (``Humor's Link to Reduced Substance Use by
Early Adolescents'') in disciplines encompassing psychology,
literary history, physiology and pop culture studies, made an
interesting case for a still-nascent and not entirely accepted
academic field of study. There were more than 200 attendees from 30
states and 21 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two purposes for the conference,'' said Martin D.
Lampert, this year's organizer, a psychology professor at Holy
Names. ``To bring researchers together, so people doing theater
work, psychology work, medical work, can share ideas and build a
discipline. And to bring attention to the field, so people begin to
think of it as something relevant to study.''
</P>
<P>
   A day of traipsing about from session to session turned up a few
good jokes (mostly dirty) and a few genuinely amusing if
extraordinarily narrow fields of interest. In the latter category
was ``A Good Start: Death Wish Jokes and the American Legal
Profession,'' in which Marc Galanter, a law professor at the
University of Wisconsin, disclosed that of the 23 extant jokes that
urge or celebrate the killing of lawyers (e.g., ``What do you call
6,000 lawyers at the bottom of the ocean? A good start''), 19 were
created after 1980, which reveals something or other about the rise
in a national antipathy toward lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the back of the room was John Elman, a 64-year-old
insurance salesman (and nonpracticing lawyer) from Palo Alto, one
of the few nonacademics at the conference. In an interview he
summed things up rather nicely. ``I came here to learn,'' he said.
``I didn't come here to laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that same evening, a mere bellowing bullhorn's distance
from the Vietnam-era birthplace of the free speech movement, that
an actor, making an unannounced appearance at a microphone on the
roof of Zellerbach Hall, declaimed excerpts from Hitler's public
addresses to an initially perplexed crowd of early-arriving
theatergoers and others who were just passing through Lower Sproul
Plaza. Many did double takes at the earnest, exhortatory calls for
German unity and eerie praise for the Nazi's elite formations.
</P>
<P>
   ``SS?'' cried a man, standing on the plaza. ``Did he say SS? Are
you listening to that? He ought to get the hell out of here. That's
how it all started.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was, as it happened, the point. The actor, an American,
Christopher Peak, speaking in English, had been engaged by the
Berliner Ensemble, the German theater troupe founded by Brecht in
1949, which made its first appearance in the country last Thursday.
And this was the company's way of opening its production of
``Arturo Ui,'' Brecht's viciously comic parable of the ascension of
Nazism in Germany, which places heavy emphasis on the parallels
between the seduction of an audience by a commanding actor and the
more sinister seduction of a nation, willing to suspend its
disbelief, in the thrall of a commanding leader.
</P>
<P>
   The play, set in Depression-era Chicago, is the story of Arturo
Ui, an Al Capone-ish figure bent on taking over the city's
greengrocers' union. He is played with cartoonishly physical
villainy by Martin Wuttke, who begins the show on all fours,
panting like an overexcited German shepherd, and as the show
proceeds, rises _ literally and metaphorically _ to a
goose-stepping, self-appointed master of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Highly stylized and visually stunning, the production used
music, from Shubert lieder to strident American rock-and-roll; the
evil comic intent was clear from the stagecraft. Unhappily for some
in the restless audience, it had to be. The text was performed in
German, and though supertitles were provided, they were at a height
that made it impossible to take in the action and the text in a
single glance. Nonetheless, it was an important occasion; the
company moves to Los Angeles for four performances at the Freud
Theater at UCLA, after which it is to be essentially disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, most in the theater got the message, as did the
horrified man on the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I get it,'' he said, after the stagecraft had been
explained to him. ``Always remember, never forget. Right?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
