<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-GARTNER-ART-2TAKE     07-04 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-GARTNER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARTNER, AN EARLY Y2K ANALYST, DOMINATES THE NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How much will the battle to tame year 2000 computer problems
cost? When will computer malfunctions hit? Which countries or
industries are furthest along _ or furthest behind _ in dealing
with the year 2000 challenge?
</P>
<P>
   One name comes up repeatedly when such questions are posed:
Gartner Group Inc. From congressional hearings to corporate
boardrooms, year 2000 progress reports and risk assessments often
begin, and sometimes end, with Gartner's research. The consulting
firm's thousands of information-technology clients include not just
the business elite but foreign governments ranging from economic
powers like Japan to the sorely distressed like Russia and
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   That gives the use of Gartner's year 2000 projections the same
cachet that went with corporate decisions to buy IBM computers in
the 1960s, even though many year 2000 experts say Gartner's
research process raises as many questions as it answers.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner's year 2000 star rose rapidly after a 1996 congressional
hearing when it suggested that American companies might spend as
much as $600 billion finding and dealing with end-of-century
computer flaws, making it the first prominent
information-technology firm to put a hard, eye-opening number on
the problem in a public forum.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting publicity encouraged the firm, based in Stamford,
Conn., to expand its research on the subject; today, its rankings
and data permeate year 2000 print and broadcast reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I took Ronald McDonald and put a Gartner suit on him, he'd
be interviewed by all the big media outlets for Y2K expertise,''
said William Ulrich, a consultant based in Soquel, Calif., using
the popular shorthand for year 2000 issues.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent figure in the Gartner suit on a given day is
often Louis Marcoccio, the company's director of year 2000
research. A 52-year-old computer-management veteran with an MBA, a
law degree and teaching credentials to go along with three
engineering degrees, Marcoccio's life is a whirl of speeches at
year 2000 conferences, private consultations with Gartner clients,
and interviews.
</P>
<P>
   He talks to scores of journalists each week, often for foreign
audiences. One recent week included television broadcasts in Japan
and Israel and a radio program in Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had requests to be in movies, and a Canadian rock group
wanted to dub me over one of their songs,'' Marcoccio said, smiling
with a mixture of amusement and dismay at the idea that year 2000
mania could bring a conservatively attired consultant such brushes
with celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   For all the attention, though, year 2000 issues are such a small
part of Gartner's overall consulting business that it is almost
irrelevant to investors, according to analysts who follow the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner says the sale of year 2000 research and advice will
bring in less than $8 million of the $750 million in total revenue
that Wall Street is projecting this year. The eight full-time year
2000 analysts represent just 1 percent of the 800
information-technology specialists working for Gartner worldwide.
Most clients get the research at bargain rates as an addition to
other research services.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner's stock is down 37 percent in the last 12 months,
compared with a 13 percent climb in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index. It has lagged behind the market's rise because of concerns
about the growth prospects of the rest of the business and, more
recently, about a complicated financial restructuring and stock
buyback plan scheduled during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But however puny from the perspective of the balance sheet,
Gartner's year 2000 effort speaks to giant fears about the
inability of some computers, programs and electronic devices to
handle dates after Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner had been advising clients since the late 1980s to get to
work on year 2000 issues, though it was not until 1993 that it
tried to analyze the extent of the potential problem.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said they were startled when the analyst they
hired, Kevin Schick, came up with a cost estimate of $300 billion
to $600 billion. Schick, who left Gartner in 1996 and later founded
Enterprise Solution Partners, an Internet publisher in Chicago,
said he had simply put together Gartner estimates of the lines of
computer code in use with data on the average cost of hiring
outside programmers to repair faulty mainframe-computer software.
</P>
<P>
   It later became apparent that lines of code were too crude a
measurement to accurately project a company's year 2000 costs. In
addition, computer users surprised Gartner and most other experts
by doing most of their repairs internally instead of hiring outside
contractors, which cut their reported costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way spending could get to the upper limits they
calculated,'' said Thomas Oleson, head of year 2000 research for
International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Gartner estimate has never completely yielded
the spotlight that it gained in the 1996 congressional testimony,
in part because its scope was changed. Today it is used as a
worldwide figure, not, as Schick had calculated, the cost for the
United States alone, and it includes expenses overlooked in the
original estimate, like testing.
</P>
<P>
   Later, more cautious projections, like Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter's recent estimate that the information technology bill in
the United States would be less than $86 billion, still attract far
less notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are first, and you are recognized as a big provider
of data, you are going to catch people's attention,'' said James
Woodward, head of the year 2000 practice for CAP Gemini America in
New York, a consulting and software repair firm that has sponsored
independent research on year 2000 programs at big companies.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner's influence also rests in part on its business strategy.
Because it is known for selling assessments and visions of where
technology is going rather than particular products, many computer
users see it as an independent voice with no ax to grind, like
Consumer Reports looking at television sets or autos.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Several smaller competitors, like Giga Information, Jupiter and
Forrester Research, offer similar independence but lack Gartner's
global reach and huge stable of big-name clients. Gartner, which
was founded in 1979, has 9,100 corporate and government clients.
</P>
<P>
   But Gartner, like other year 2000 researchers, relies heavily
even today on unverifiable reports by computer users of their plans
and progress in dealing with these problems. Ideally, data would
come from much more thorough investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes two or three weeks of a consultant's time to find out
where a large company really is on Y2K,'' said Bruce Hall, who was
Marcoccio's predecessor at Gartner and is now vice president at
Trigent Software, a company in Southborough, Mass., that uses
offshore programmers to help companies do year 2000 repairs and
other software projects.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gartner's research extends far deeper than the written
questionnaires that many others rely on.
</P>
<P>
   The basis for many of its rankings now, according to Marcoccio,
is quarterly polling of 15,000 companies in 31 nations by 11
universities that do the work in exchange for free consulting
services. The companies are asked 330 questions in long phone
interviews, which are considered more reliable than written
questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   The results are then cross-checked against a variety of public
and private reports and made available to other Gartner analysts
for review.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner does not disclose the rankings of individual companies,
but private clients can get breakdowns of how different industries
are doing, country by country, and in comparison with clusters of
clients that Gartner Group views as leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gartner's methodology leaves something to be desired, but it's
as good as it gets,'' said Edward Yardeni, chief economist at
Deutsche Bank Securities in New York. ``At the end of the day, they
are the only game in town when it comes to global assessments.''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. For global assessments and many other year 2000
measures, multinational companies and industry groups have recently
put together private research efforts that have better or more
recent information than Gartner.
</P>
<P>
   Many large banks and other financial institutions, for instance,
take part in Global 2000, which has a 22-member committee headed by
James Devlin of Citibank that updates country assessments every
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became more positive on Japan and Germany well ahead of
Gartner,'' Devlin said, citing one difference. But Global 2000, at
the request of government regulators and several key members, keeps
most of its research private. Gartner's results are more widely
available and are based on more data, Devlin said.
</P>
<P>
   That makes them subject to disproportionate influence, according
to some year 2000 experts. ``At a minimum, if you are a Y2K
coordinator in a foreign country, you need to know what Gartner is
saying about you,'' said Bruce McConnell, head of the World Bank's
recently formed International Y2K Cooperation Center in Washington
and a critic of the weight often given to Gartner Group ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner readily concedes that those it rates have every right to
be concerned about how its research _ especially the public
summaries of it _ is being used.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are meant to be a flag, not a basis for
decisions,'' Marcoccio said. He added that Gartner constantly warns
clients that a low rating for a country is a signal for them to
look more closely at their exposure, not a reason to pull out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
