<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: RAPID LAUNCHING OF FIREWORKS; DISPOSING OF CONTRABAND;
AWARDS FOR INVENTORS; FIREWORKS FOR CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Pa., Md., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American inventors have been in pursuit of pyrotechnic
perfection ever since fireworks were shot off in 1777 during the
very first Fourth of July celebration in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney resorts, of course, like to shoot off fireworks even
when it's not the Fourth of July. Kyle Poor and John Sogge, two
inventors who are based in Orlando, Fla., and affiliated with Walt
Disney Co., were recently granted a patent for a type of Roman
candle that launches high-altitude fireworks in quick succession.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, according to the patent, a Roman candle launches from
eight to 12 fireballs from a cardboard tube every three to six
seconds, with the fireballs, or ``stars,'' reaching a maximum of
150 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Poor and Sogge have patented a new type of launching tube in
which stars are propelled out of the tube by pressured gas rather
than by ignited black powder. The stars either can be coated with a
combustible material, so that they ignite by friction as they are
forced from the tube, the inventors state, or can be lighted by a
flame as they pass through the tube.
</P>
<P>
   ``The launcher is capable of launching a plurality of the
fireworks projectiles at a rapid rate of fire, up to six shots per
second or more,'' the patent says. ``Furthermore, the launcher is
capable of launching the fireworks projectiles at relatively high
altitudes approaching 300 feet or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor and Sogge received patent 5,917,146, which was assigned to
Walt Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Helping Get Rid of Dangerous Stuff
</P>
<P>
   Randall Paul Voorhees and Joseph Ernest Voorhees, two
Pennsylvania inventors, have come up with a new way for
law-enforcement agencies to dispose of combustible contraband such
as ammunition and fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors note that their ``portable armored incinerator for
dangerous substances'' is an improvement over the method currently
favored by law-enforcement agencies, which involves ``digging a
pit, placing the contraband in the pit, pouring gasoline or other
flammable liquid over it, and setting it afire.''
</P>
<P>
   The Voorheeses' mobile incinerator has armored walls made with
steel plates and reinforced by steel channel beams, which insulate
the incinerator, from explosions created by burning such material.
</P>
<P>
   ``This invention eliminates the need for hazardous
transportation of explosive substances that are to be destroyed, as
the invention can easily be brought to the site where they are
located,'' the patent says.
</P>
<P>
   It also reduces the amount of pollution emitted, according to
the inventors. ``The primary and secondary combustion chambers
minimize pollution from the incineration by ensuring that there are
no unburned combustible airborne particles or vapors emitted,'' the
patent says.
</P>
<P>
   The Voorheeses received patent 5,727,481.
</P>
<P>
   Group Names Inventor of Year
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Intellectual Property Owners Association, in
Washington, bestowed its Inventor of the Year Award on Dr. Curt
Civin, a researcher at Johns Hopkins University.
</P>
<P>
   Civin isolated the CD34 monoclonal antibody, which made it
possible to separate stem cells _ the grandmother cells of the body
which give rise to all manner of progeny cells _ from the body's
mature cells. By using the antibody, Civin was able to develop a
refined version of bone-marrow transplantation for cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   Civin's discovery has ``revolutionized basic research and
provided many new options in cancer therapy, and particularly
bone-marrow transplantation,'' said Dr. Martin Abeloff, director of
the Johns Hopkins Oncology Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Association also gave Distinguished Inventor Awards to
researchers at Genentech and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Vehar, Richard Lawn, Daniel Capon and William Wood of
Genentech were acknowledged for their work in developing a
treatment for hemophilia patients that is free from HIV and
hepatitis contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Meyerson, director of telecommunications technology at
IBM, was recognized for his role in developing silicon germanium
transistors, which operate faster than ordinary silicon devices.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks for Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   You've heard of Christmas in July. But July in Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   John Fuu Liu, an inventor in Huntington Beach, Calif., has
patented Christmas-tree lights whose bulbs look like miniature
firework displays. Inside the bowl-shaped bulbs are fiber-optic
sticks whose tips flash on and off, thus simulating fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Liu received patent 5,865,533.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
