<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, July 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Exceptionally hot and humid weather will grip much of the East
Monday and Tuesday as a large high pressure system, extending from
the earth's surface up to 20,000 feet, strengthens over the region.
Near the ground, the clockwise circulation around the high will
direct sultry air from the lower Mississippi Valley into the
Northeast. Hazy sunshine and breezes from the southwest, warming on
descent from the Appalachians, will promote near-record heat from
eastern Virginia to eastern Massachusetts. Indeed, afternoon
readings will exceed 100 degrees from Washington to Boston,
including metropolitan New York and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Currents of sinking air associated with the expansive high
pressure will limit rainfall over most of the East. Isolated
afternoon thunderstorms may form, however, in the Appalachians and
near the Southeast coast where developing sea breezes undercut and
lift the muggy air.
</P>
<P>
   A disturbance traveling along the southern flank of the jet
stream will spark clusters of thunderstorms near the Canadian
border, especially over the northern Great Lakes and in northern
New England. Some of the storms will contain prolific rain and
damaging wind gusts.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonal temperatures and ample sunshine will cover the West
Monday. An exception will be near portions of the Pacific coastline
where gentle onshore breezes bring patches of morning low clouds.
Additionally, scattered clouds and spotty afternoon thunderstorms
will accompany a plume of moisture streaming into the Southwestern
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Hot Sounds
</P>
<P>
   Heat waves are noisy. Near busy airports, the number of
complaints about noise from commercial jets increases during hot
weather. As temperatures rise, the density of air decreases as air
molecules move faster and spread farther apart. The relatively low
density of hot air reduces aerodynamic lift. As a result, large
jets take longer to climb after take-off, exacerbating noise
problems in residential areas along flight paths. With temperatures
rising toward 100 degrees over much of the Northeast early this
week, the hot sounds from jet engines will reach a crescendo at
major airports.
</P>
<P>
   EXTENDED FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Thursday: A cool front preceded by thunderstorms will
lessen the heat and humidity in the Northeast. The Middle Atlantic
states will stay hot. Sultry weather with scattered thunder will
prevail in the Southeast. Meanwhile, most of the Plains will be hot
with little rain. A resurgence of heat and humidity will promote
thundery conditions in the upper Middle West. Most of the West will
be hot with ample sun. The Northwest will be seasonal.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Saturday: Heat and humidity will increase in most of the
Northeast. Farther west, strong thunderstorms will precede a cold
front from the Great Lakes to the central Plains. In the wake of
the front, the northern Plains will be cooler and drier. Showers
will become more numerous in the sultry air over the Southeast.
Afternoon thunder will be common over the central and southern
Rockies. Otherwise, the West will be sunny and very warm.
</P>
</TEXT>
