<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9060 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUCKSTOP-MAKEOVER-AR     07-04 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCKSTOP-MAKEOVER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TRUCK STOPS DESIGNED TO WOW BOTH TRUCKERS AND MOTORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Colo., Ohio, Ind., Iowa, Ariz., Utah, Calif., Texas) (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 BY PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMERCE CITY, Colo. _ To the typical ``four-wheeler'' _
truck-driver slang for motorists _ the image of the American truck
stop is a grungy, tobacco-infused place serving chicken-fried steak
and 48-hour coffee.
</P>
<P>
   But as they zoom down I-70 toward the Rockies this weekend,
travelers might be tempted to brake for the new truck stop built by
Travel Centers of America endowed with architectural fireworks:
ribbed aluminum (a nod to the American diner), a huge striped
awning (the traditional sign of welcome) and the ultimate highway
seducer _ neon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reminds me of Disneyland,'' said James La Porte, a
self-employed trucker from Brighton, Colo., who was buying lube
oil. ``Haven't seen a truck stop lit up like it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he hadn't even been inside the marble shower stalls, modeled
on the Ritz-Carlton. (Today's travel tip: The showers are free with
the purchase of 50 gallons of diesel fuel.)
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in its 80-or-so-year history, the American
truck stop has been ``re-imaged,'' as designers like to say, with
nostalgic roadside touches harking back to the California coffee
shops of the 1950s (called ``Googies'') and the original parabolic
McDonald's. Though ``truck stop design'' seems like an oxymoron, it
is the latest transformation of the province of professional
haulers into a ``stopping center'' styled to lure the car and
recreational vehicle trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question was, was it the wrong image?'' said Paul
Westlake, the Cleveland architect for the new truck stop, speaking
of the Donald Trump-like red Spanish marble in the showers _ a
ritzy material highly forgiving with soap scum. ``Would truckers
perceive it as too upscale, that they'd be paying for it in their
diesel fuel?''
</P>
<P>
   In a design trend as yet unheralded by Architectural Digest, a
new building type has been born, one that seeks to revive ``the wow
factor,'' as Westlake calls it, that dazzled motorists of the '50s
before television advertising and computer reservations took over.
It may one day stand proudly with such giants of the American
highway as Bob's Big Boy (circa 1949) in Toluca Lake, Calif., a
building-as-billboard relished by aficionados as the architectural
equivalent of a double-decker cheeseburger with pickles on a sesame
seed bun.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, shrinking profit margins on diesel fuel and
increasingly efficient truck engines have caused companies like the
Ohio-based Travel Centers of America, the largest full-service
truck stop company in the country, to look to four-wheelers,
including RV's, for profits. A 1995 study commissioned by NATSO,
formerly the National Association of Truck Stop Operators,
estimated that if just 1 percent of rural auto traffic were
diverted to buying gas and eating meals at truck stops, the result
would be an extra $300 million annually for a $37 billion a year
industry. (Most budget-conscious truckers, noted Forrest Baker, a
retired trucking industry consultant, do not eat two sit-down meals
a day and ``one may consist of bread and bologna.'')
</P>
<P>
   At least 80 percent of truck stops now call themselves ``travel
plazas.'' Travelers can visit a massage therapist, see a
chiropractor, get a manicure or, in the case of Sierra Sid's 76
Auto/Truck Stop Casino on I-80 in Sparks, Nev., marvel at Sid's gun
collection and Elvis memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger is better at the Petro Co.'s Wheeler Ridge center, which
just opened on I-5, near Bakersfield, Calif., with a 40-seat movie
theater and an Internet lounge. At most Petro and Travel Center of
America stops, subscribing truckers can plug into the popular park
and view system, which turns their cabs into motel rooms, complete
with 24-hour e-mail, cable television and a wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   But Commerce City, just northeast of Denver, is the vanguard of
new design and will be replicated at 40 or so sites by Travel
Centers of America _ which is owned by Clipper Group, a Wall Street
investment firm _ around the country this year. The goal is a 50-50
trucker-traveler ratio, though 80 percent of customers are
currently truckers, said Michael O'Connor, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The building, which opened in June, is an improbable piece of
choreography for two somewhat clashing cultures _ one predicated on
the notion that architecture can make opposites attract. There are
separate entrances, one snazzy with the neon facing the highway for
motorists (leading to a gift-and-convenience store), and a
no-nonsense ``professional drivers only'' door at the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want the trucks seen first,'' O'Connor explained,
``because that would scare off the motorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel Centers did extensive research to determine what truckers
wanted. The answer: a clean shower (foggy mirrors and mop buckets
being prime pet peeves, along with recreational vehicles that move
an infuriating 20 mph up a slope).
</P>
<P>
   ``We like them way big,'' said Dale Curry, a freshly shampooed
trucker from Fort Worth, speaking of the preference for double-wide
showers. ``We sit around all day. You're in kind of a coffin, you
might say.''
</P>
<P>
   For truckers' comfort, Travel Centers studied ``the essence of
the Ritz-Carlton bathroom,'' O'Connor said. At a test site in Gary,
Ind., marble, granite and fiberglass showers were offered. Marble
won unanimously in exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists and truckers share bathrooms, a drop-off laundry and
the attention of waitresses. But there is a special truckers-only
shaving room because ``when motorists come in they don't want to
see a half-dressed trucker shaving,'' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to make the trucker feel at home, the repair shop
``celebrates the machine,'' said Westlake, whose firm, van Dijk,
Pace, Westlake, usually specializes in cultural facilities. One day
in June, light streamed through a bank of glass block windows,
glinting off the stacks of Kenworths and Peterbilts, spotlighting
them like beauty queens on a stage.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike fast-food restaurants and gas stations, truck stops never
had a distinct style. ``The tradition was there wasn't any,'' notes
Steven Izenour, a partner of Venturi Scott Brown, the Philadelphia
architecture firm, and a co-author of ``Learning from Las Vegas,''
a scholarly celebration of commercial architecture and the Las
Vegas strip. ``Architecturally, they've been amorphous boxes strewn
across the tarmac.''
</P>
<P>
   Before superhighways, any place a trucker could fuel his rig and
get a bite to eat counted as a truck stop. Most were mom-and-pop
operations with one pump, a part-time mechanic and a pot of coffee
on the stove; ``open all night'' meant the keys were on a nail next
to the door.
</P>
<P>
   As Jessica Rowcroft, an architectural historian with the
Massachusetts Historical Commission noted, most of the growth of
the modern truck stop came in the 1960s with the heyday of the
interstate highway and the rise of franchises. From a motley array
of separate buildings, the truck stop was consolidated under one
roof, leaving more room for parking. Truck stops began luring
automobiles with intensely lighted gasoline fuel islands. ``We call
it the moth syndrome,'' Westlake said.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving his truck-stop commission, Westlake gathered
images that evoked the emotion of road travel _ including ``roofs
that look like they braked at 60 mph.'' Then he hit the road,
visiting truck stops with character like ``Iowa 80'' in Walcott,
Iowa, a timber-framed chalet billed as the world's largest, and
not-so-fabled ones that ``reeked of diesel fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether truckers and motorists will latch on to each other
like lug nuts to an axle is still a question to be mulled,
preferably over coffee and chocolate-silk pie, as David Kinney, a
lease operator with C.R. England &AMP; Sons, a trucking company in Salt
Lake City, did one recent afternoon in Commerce City.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of friction,'' he said between forkfuls. ``See
that store there? Motorists buy trinkets. Truck drivers are bargain
shoppers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clark, a trucker from Wheatland, Wyo., said that tourists
were the reason he avoided the entire state of Arizona. ``You can
stand in line forever behind 20 tourists buying candy bars,'' he
said, fuming. ``A truck stop should be a place to park, fuel and
get out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Standing near a battalion of truckers and tourists playing video
games, the freshly showered Curry waxed philosophical. ``I don't
mind if  &UR; they &LR;  don't,'' he said of sharing the truck stop. ``You
get tired of looking at truckers all the time.'' Which is one
reason the architects included panoramic windows.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Merrit, a trucker from Cheney, Wash., was thinking more
about what the designers left out: separate bathrooms for women
truck drivers. Most truck stop bathrooms ``are so nasty,'' said Ms.
Merrit, she keeps a personal jug in her garnet Freightline cab.
</P>
<P>
   A former librarian with neat upswept hair, Ms. Merrit met her
future husband, Louis Delp, a trucker, while she was driving her
car in California. He waved. She waved. She plastered her phone
number in the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Before pulling off from Commerce City with her load of Coors
beer, Ms. Merrit offered a last word on the importance of design to
truckers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it when my husband's shirts don't come out tie-dyed
from the laundry,'' she said. ``And what really matters more than
anything is if someone's decent to you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
