<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEK BANKS AGREE TO JOIN IN A $5.2 BILLION MERGER
</P>
<P>
   In another move toward consolidation in the Greek banking
industry, Bank of Piraeus has agreed to buy Ergo Bank for $5.2
billion in cash and stock. The deal would create Greece's
third-largest bank by assets and thwart a competing hostile bid by
EFG Bank Group of Geneva, which has until July 14 to raise its
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Greek banks have been racing to merge and create alliances to
fend off competition from larger European rivals. No more than four
Greek banking groups are likely to survive Greece's planned entry
into Europe's single currency in 2001, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   HARDENED CITY BUYS INTO HOAX
</P>
<P>
   Bewitched by a 13-year-old Honduran boy's fabrications, every
news outlet in New York passed along his fanciful tale last week:
that he had lost his immediate family in the mudslides caused by
Hurricane Mitch; that his father had sent him a letter with money
to take him to New York; that he had traveled 3,200 miles to New
York by hitchhiking and taking a bus. But if there was no joy in
the city's newsrooms at the discovery that the story was false,
there was little self-flagellation, either.
</P>
<P>
   A SPINOFF COMPETES WITH ITS PARENT
</P>
<P>
   Qlogic and its former parent, Emulex, are vying for leadership
in fiber channel technology, a new approach to high-speed data
transfer between computers and disk drives. With corporations
needing ever faster access to larger amounts of data, particularly
to run Web sites, fiber channel sales look set to soar.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS TURN TO WEB FOR TEXTBOOKS
</P>
<P>
   Varsitybooks.com, an online bookseller, plans to announce this
week that it has signed contracts with nearly a dozen small
universities, colleges and other schools to sell textbooks. In some
cases, the arrangements mean that schools are completely closing
their book-selling operations and sending their students to the
company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   IMPROVING THE LEVEL OF CHAT ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Noting a seemingly insatiable appetite for public messaging,
some people argue that the future of the Internet depends on making
this crucial component more satisfying for everyone. To move people
beyond the graffiti quality of much online messaging, two projects
are developing software and discussion practices that encourage
them to talk to, rather than at, one another.
</P>
<P>
   STREAMING IS GEEKS' CUTTING EDGE
</P>
<P>
   Judging from three Michigan high school students who were in New
York at the Streaming Media convention, the nerds have gone online.
The students demonstrated a project from their advanced
video-production course, a wearable computer with a Webcam. Besides
functioning as a standard personal computer, the system contains a
wireless transmitter that can send everything the wearer hears and
sees to the school's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   TWO NETWORKS GETTING IN THE RING
</P>
<P>
   Two networks are joining the professional wrestling fray, with
UPN scheduling two hours on Thursdays in the fall and TNN, the
Nashville Network, signing a deal for an hourlong show on Friday
nights.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States are closed Monday in observance of the Fourth of July. Most
overseas markets, however, are open. U.S. markets will reopen
Tuesday.
</P>
