<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-PEPSI-FOLO05-COX     07-04 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PEPSI-FOLO05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Close call between Jarrett, Earnhardt
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ It was one of them Dales.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's Pepsi 400 at Daytona International Speedway _ the
first U.S. auto race ever televised on prime-time network
television _ lacked the climatic finish NASCAR and CBS officials
were hoping for, but the race under the lights still turned into a
late shootout between Dale Jarrett and Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   After debris on the track _ Kenny Irwin's fuel ``catch can'' _
seemed to set up a 10-lap sprint to the finish between a handful of
cars, Jeremy Mayfield spun out with three laps to go.
</P>
<P>
   That ignited a multicar accident in turn 2, which brought out
the race's second yellow flag, allowing Jarrett to finish under
caution for his third victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The win gave Jarrett the Winston Cup points lead for the seventh
week in a row, this one a 177-point advantage over Bobby Labonte
heading into the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt finished second, followed by Jeff Burton, Mike Skinner
and Labonte. Jeff Gordon, who was attempting to become only the
fifth driver to win three races in a row at Daytona, finished a
disappointing 21st.
</P>
<P>
   With 17 of 34 races remaining, Jarrett seems to have a
commanding lead in his quest for his first Winston Cup title. Not
since 1992, when the late Alan Kulwicki overtook the late Davey
Allison in the last race of the season, has a driver leading at the
halfway point failed to win the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good stat to know,'' said Jarrett, who finished
third, second and third in points the last three years,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to end that string,'' he said. ``Without sounding
cocky or overconfident, if we can continue doing what we've done,
they'll have trouble catching us. But it only takes one race to
make this a close battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's fortunes finally changed at Daytona, where he'd
finished 34th, 23rd and 37th in the last three races on the
2.5-mile superspeedway. In the season-opening Daytona 500, Jarrett
completed only 134 laps after his No. 88 Ford made contact with
teammate Irwin's No. 28 Ford, leaving him 36th in points.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, Jarrett finished outside the top 10 only
once _ 11th at Las Vegas on March 7. He finished in the top five in
all but two of the last 15 events, and won three of the last seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember being involved in anything like it,'' Jarrett
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've overcome some things where we shouldn't have finished in
the top 10 and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett probably wouldn't have finished in the top 10 on
Saturday night without the final caution flag. After taking only a
splash of gas on his last pit stop, Jarrett's car ran out of fuel
after finishing the cool-down lap. His crew members had to push the
car from pit road to victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett says the outcome wouldn't have changed if the race had
been completed under green. Earnhardt, who finished second to
Gordon in the Daytona 500, isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think within a few more laps we would have gotten by
Jarrett,'' Earnhardt said. ``He might have run out of gas, because
he was really close. That caution really helped him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
