<DOCNO> NYT19990704.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PTREE-ROADRACE05-COX     07-04 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PTREE-ROADRACE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A peach of a day
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The big story at the 30th Peachtree Road Race on
Sunday was the new finish, and not just the change to the end of
the course. For only the second time since 1991, a Kenyan failed to
capture either the men's or women's title at the world's largest
10K.
</P>
<P>
   Khalid Khannouchi of Morocco defended his Peachtree title in 27
minutes, 45 seconds, well ahead of John Korir of Kenya. Elana Meyer
of South Africa won the first Peachtree she ever entered in 31:34,
nipping another Kenyan, Catherine Ndereba, by 9 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi and Meyer won $25,000 each from the Professional Road
Racing Organization, which tags the Peachtree as its championship.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the river of 55,000 runners past a starred, striped and
clapping crowd pumped up Khannouchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to win this on the Fourth of July, because I'm
trying to get my citizenship,'' said Khannouchi, who lives in New
York. ``It's just great.''
</P>
<P>
   The race's third decade dawned with a new downhill finish on
10th Street, which received mixed reviews from those in the swollen
middle of the pack. As the lanes narrowed approaching Piedmont
Park, runners had to stop and walk, and that made some grumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like that bottleneck at the end,'' said Claudia
Ritchie, 52. ``I was trying to beat my (best) time.'' Others said
the slowdown was much worse in the old, winding finish through the
park.
</P>
<P>
   The new finish meant that the old course records were just that.
In the wheelchair race, Saul Mendoza of northern Atlanta, by way of
Mexico, clipped a second off the old record with 19:05. Chantal
Petitclerc of Canada (24:13) defended her title and beat her course
record.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who crossed the line an hour later on this sunny
holiday, though, took home the coveted T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely lived up to its hype,'' said Andy Goldberg, 32,
a dental technician from Cumming, holding up his shirt after
completing his first Peachtree. ``I'm going to wear this around
like a trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
