<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9077 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BIRTHRATE-     07-04 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BIRTHRATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN WOMEN ATTRIBUTE PLUNGING BIRTHRATE TO FEAR OF THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Before Serbia went to war with the West,
Vesna Markovic wanted three children. Since the Kosovo conflict,
she has often been sorry that she has one.
</P>
<P>
   To raise the money to provide her 8-year-old son with food,
clothes and toys, Mrs. Markovic, 27, an economist who works at an
electric utility in Belgrade, has become a smuggler of gasoline and
disposable diapers.
</P>
<P>
   Most evenings after work, she and her husband, Zoran, a Serbian
policeman, make a 200-mile round trip from here to the Bosnian town
of Bijeljina to buy about 30 gallons of gas and six boxes of
Pampers _ goods that are in chronic short supply in the collapsed
Serbian economy. For each round of nocturnal smuggling, they
usually pocket about $57.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all become poorer and it is not good to raise children
like this,'' said Mrs. Markovic, who says she has learned how to
tune out her parents, who continue to nag her to have more babies.
</P>
<P>
   It is called the ``white plague.'' Policy makers in Serbia have
been grumbling for decades about the decline in the birthrate, as
have politicians and pundits across much of Europe. But the decline
has accelerated among the Serbs as never before under the rule of
Slobodan Milosevic _ a 12-year span scarred by four lost wars, an
imploding economy and the mass exodus of young people, often the
best and brightest.
</P>
<P>
   During a decade in which Milosevic has sent legions of Serbian
men off to carve a Greater Serbia out of the ruins of the old
Yugoslavia, the women of this country, in perhaps the most intimate
and pivotal decisions of their lives, are quietly choosing to make
a less populous Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The damage from NATO bombs to factories and bridges will have
much less effect in the long run on Serbia than the rapid decline
in the birthrate,'' said Dr. Spasoje Petkovic, an
obstetrician-gynecologist who is acting director of the Clinical
Center of Serbia, the country's largest hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Population statistics, along with interviews with women and
their doctors, suggest that Serbian women of child-bearing age are
deciding in unprecedented numbers that Milosevic's Serbia is not
the place to raise children.
</P>
<P>
   According to government statistics, there were 58,000 babies
born in central Serbia in 1998, a 15 percent decline since 1990 and
the lowest total since the end of World War II. In central Serbia,
the population growth rate has slid this decade from 1.2 percent on
the plus side to 1.8 percent on the minus side, government figures
show.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Serbia's abortion rate appears to be rising
sharply and increasing numbers of young women are telling doctors
they do not want to give birth, according to two senior
obstetricians at Serbia's largest maternity hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reasons for the accelerating decline in the
birthrate, according to woman and their obstetricians, is anxiety
about the war in Kosovo, fear of civil war in Serbia and
unwillingness to raise children in a nation that once had the
highest living standard in eastern Europe but over the past decade
has gotten poorer every year.
</P>
<P>
   Vanja Kovac, wearing a blue nightgown she brought from home,
waited her turn last Friday for an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old supermarket clerk from Belgrade already has two
children.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was now in the Clinical Center of Serbia for an
abortion because she and her husband, who is a night watchman,
simply cannot afford to feed another child. Abortions are available
on demand here for anyone over age 18 during the first 10 weeks of
pregnancy. They cost about $25.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easier in these times not to have a child than to have
one who does not have enough clothes and food,'' said Mrs. Kovac.
``It is also very risky because of the radiation from the bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors are rampant in Serbia that American bombs have created
high levels of radiation that causes birth defects. Alarmed by the
rumors and by hospital reports of a spike in the number of
abortions here, the Serbian government issued a statement in late
May saying that the radiation rumors had been investigated and
proven scientifically to be false.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, however, government officials had issued alarming
warnings about chemical pollution to the air and water near
Belgrade after NATO bombings of refineries and other industrial
facilities close to the capital.
</P>
<P>
   On May 28, the Serbian Ministry of Information appealed to
future mothers and medical workers ``not to interrupt lives that
have begun.'' The government warned darkly that belief in such
rumors ``represents a form of special genocidal war that affects
the basic biological substratum of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The declining birthrate in Serbia has apparently been perceived
by at least one of the country's leading nationalist politicians as
anti-Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   Vojislav Seselj, the hard-line leader of the Serbian Radical
Party and a deputy prime minister in the Yugoslav government, early
this year floated the idea of imposing a special tax on young
couples who did not have children. The idea died for lack of
support.
</P>
<P>
   Obstetricians in Belgrade say that with each passing year this
decade, more and more women of childbearing age seem frightened by
the idea of raising children in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense that women feel insecure in every sense of the word,''
said Dr. Darko Plecas, head of the Institute for Obstetrics and
Gynecology at the Clinical Center of Serbia. ``Graduating from the
best universities in this country no longer solves the problem of
finding a job or being able to afford an apartment. It is also more
difficult to find a husband, because many young men have left the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   According to various estimates, between 100,000 and 300,000
young men have fled Serbia to avoid the draft in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   When women do get pregnant, they are under more stress than 20
years ago, Plecas added. ``It used to be that I was just an
obstetrician; now I am a part-time psychologist.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a Belgrade obstetrician who did not want to quoted
by name, young Serbian women never go to a doctor and say: ``I want
an abortion because of Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that is the context,'' the doctor said. ``They are afraid
of what will happen to their children. They fear what family life
will be like. They fear how good the schools will be. They are
already certain that they will not be able to give their children
what their parents gave them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In this culture,'' he added, ``if you cannot pamper your
children, it is better not to have them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is fear of falling living standards _ plus fear of
radiation-caused birth defects _ that brought Sladzana Misic, 32, a
mother of two sons, to the Clinical Center of Serbia last Friday
for an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband own a bakery that she said clears a profit
of about $210 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the right time to have a baby,'' said Mrs. Misic.
``My husband and I don't have money for milk, diapers or clothes
for another baby. Also, I am afraid of the rain. It is weird. I
think there is something wrong here now because of radiation from
the bombs and chemical weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Misic, who waited for her abortion while wearing a flannel
nightgown with tiny purple and yellow flowers, said she and her
husband are strong supporters of Milosevic. She said, too, that she
believes the Serbian leader did the ``right thing'' by going to war
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we did down there in Kosovo was justified,'' she
said. ``Milosevic is not the problem. The one to blame is the U.S.
government. There was a conspiracy that we cannot know. Kosovo was
a part of an American plan for power and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her deep belief in the rectitude of Milosevic's
government, Mrs. Misic said she was having an abortion because she
and her husband want to get out of the country and find better
paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go anywhere,'' said Mrs. Misic. ``It is easy to
travel with my kids now. They are 7 and 10. And I could not take
the nine months of pregnancy in this country because of the
stress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
