<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT DETHRONES GRAF IN WIMBLEDON FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Determined to make peace with Wimbledon's
grass courts, which had never before been kind to her, Lindsay
Davenport conducted her own cram course last month in the privacy
of a friend's backyard court in Tustin, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   She learned how to turn a lawn into a launching pad for her
boisterous groundstrokes and penetrating serve, trained her
sneakers to trust the terrain beneath them, and built up the kind
of comfort zone she needed to cope with grass court wizards like
the one she faced in Sunday's finale, seven-time champion Steffi
Graf.
</P>
<P>
   Though Davenport killed the neighbor's court, her conversion
from a grass court hater to a grass court enthusiast achieved its
ultimate confirmation Sunday afternoon when, after a searing ace
took her to match point, she defeated Graf, 6-4, 7-5 to win the
most coveted tennis title in the world.
</P>
<P>
   With a shriek of surprise and an apologetic hug for the
retirement-bound legend across the net, Davenport, who regained the
world's No. 1 ranking by reaching Sunday's final, added the 1999
Wimbledon crown to her resume. Davenport said her first reaction,
besides amazement, to accepting her silver salver and a check for
$614,213 ($110,000 less than her fellow Californian Pete Sampras
pocketed for his record sixth title) was relief that she would
never again have to worry about the likes of John McEnroe accusing
her of being a one-Slam wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my second Slam and my third major, because I include the
Olympics,'' said Davenport, who won a gold medal at the 1996 Games
and won her favorite Slam, the U.S. Open, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win two Slams on two different surfaces means I'm a pretty
good all-around player, and to come in here with 15-1 odds and kind
of defy the experts, it just feels incredible,'' Davenport said.
``It's such a tough tournament to win with the rain delays, with
the surface and everything, to pull through and to be such a
fighter as this, I'll never forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1 hour, 16 minute match was unforgettable too for the
bombshell Graf dropped shortly after she left Center Court without
waving goodbye. Just as she had done in Paris last month after
winning the French Open _ her 22nd Slam championship _ Graf
announced that she was retiring from Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of having to treat every Slam as a two-week torture test
in pain management _ she wore a bandage on her left thigh Sunday
and has been bothered all year by back pain _ but reluctant to make
her intentions public for fear of seeing her title quest undermined
by sentiment, Graf waited until she and Davenport were off the
court, and out of earshot of royalty, before disclosing that her
14th Wimbledon would be her last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm a little sad about everything, which is normal
for the moment, but in a way I still feel like a winner getting out
of this tournament,'' said Graf, a winner in seven of the eight
Wimbledon finals she had played before. Not since 1987, when she
fell to the nine-time champion Martina Navratilova, had Graf
faltered upon reaching a final here, and when the Duchess of Kent
approached her Sunday with the runner-up trophy, she told Graf she
felt as if there was some mistake being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish I could have shown more and maybe gotten into the
third set or something,'' said Graf, who managed only two break
chances on Davenport's serve and missed on both of them.
</P>
<P>
   But Davenport laced into her shots with the precision of a
diamond cutter and handled Graf's low backhand slice as if this
were a calisthenics competition. The lower the ball slithered, the
more deep knee bends Davenport performed.
</P>
<P>
   Authoritative on Center Court, the showplace where the
30-year-old Graf was hoping to secure her eighth and last Wimbledon
crown in her 31st Slam final, Davenport put the German on the
defensive right from the first game of the match by breaking her
serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think obviously if you get broken right in the first game,
it gives the opponent a good feeling going into this match,'' said
Graf. ``She served more consistently than I did. She had me always
guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport called Graf, who refused to reveal whether she would
play in the 1999 U.S. Open, ``probably the greatest player that's
ever played, but at the same time I think it's really cool that
she's been able to go out on her own.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's choosing when she wants to go out, and I think that's
how we'd all like to end our career,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been unbelievable times, and it's been a lot of
fun,'' Graf said, but adding ``there's got to be a certain time
when I've got to move on with something else in my life. I won't be
here as a player again.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport went about the business of claiming her first
Wimbledon title the same way she had made her Grand Slam
breakthrough last year at the U.S. Open. She erased her beginner's
jitters and won the title on her first-ever trip to its final
round.
</P>
<P>
   After Graf snubbed Davenport's first set point of the opening
set with a blistering forehand return, Davenport converted her
second one and claimed the set 6-4 with a backhand rally as Graf's
final shot, a backhand slice, landed in the net.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport didn't let the rain delay at 4-5 of the second set
interfere with her plan to attend Sunday night's Champion's Ball
(an event for which she hadn't yet bought a dress). After holding
for 5-5, she broke Graf with a pair of corner-to-corner
crosscourts, the set-up shot a forehand and the break-getter a
backhand to grant herself the single opportunity needed to serve
out the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got up serving for the match, I believed, no matter
what, I could do this,'' said Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Davenport and Corina Morariu won the ladies' doubles,
defeating Mariann de Swardt and Elena Tatarkova, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
