<HEADLINE>
IF DODGERS DON'T COME BACK, HAVE A COMEBACK READY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As hecklers, Los Angeles baseball fans are pathetic. And,
probably just as sad, a little apathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's our stereotyped laid-back nature or just a fear of
speaking in public, one obvious thing we lack is the ability to
shout out clever, cunning phrases at appropriate moments. We can
boo, as we did during the weekend series against the Giants, but
where does that get ya?
</P>
<P>
   At the Baseball Heckle Depot
(http://web.ionsys.com/(tilda)tolley/index.html), there's hope that
the art of yelling the appropriate phrases at the appropriate umps,
players or fans can be learned.
</P>
<P>
   Start at ``Heckling 101,'' which discusses etiquette (such as
don't make it personal, watch your language, etc.), then clock onto
several lists that have things to yell during your next outdoor
viewing. Some samples:
</P>
<P>
   At an umpire: ``Wake up, you're missing a great game.'' (A
classic, of course, but one that gets the crowd started.)
</P>
<P>
   At a batter: ``You're not in a slump, you're just not hitting.''
Or: ``Them curveballs sure is curvy, eh?'' Or after he hits it:
``Run, Forrest, run!''
</P>
<P>
   At a relief pitcher: ``I don't know what ERA means, but you've
got 7. . . . That's gotta be good, right?''
</P>
<P>
   At a Giants fan? Don't know. The site doesn't get that detailed.
It also has a place you can heckle the Web master _ try ``you
byte!'' _ and submit your favorite heckling stories.
</P>
<P>
   __ CNNSI.com has started a new area called ``Statutudes''
(www.cnnsi.com/statitudes) that attempts to make sense of all the
numbers that an average sports fan is asked to consume on a daily
basis.
</P>
<P>
   Stats are put into context with features such as ``On the
Money,'' which shows who's worth his salary and who isn't, plus
tracking streaks and record pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   __ At the updated U.S. Olympic Committee site
(www.olympic-usa.org), you can download the 928K tax-exempt
disclosures that the organization has filed over the last three
years. Just don't expect to find anything easy to read on
dirty-scanned documents.
</P>
<P>
   __ The hot-hot calendar these days that features 12 women's
track and field athletes in various stages of clothing is available
on a Web site (www.trackgirls.com) for $21.95. It's not endorsed by
the USA Track and Field body but a project started by UCLA high
jumper Amy Acuff. Half of the proceeds go to the Florence
Griffith-Joyner Community Empowerment Foundation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
