<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-LEESON-RETURN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADER WHO BROKE BARINGS BANK IS OUT OF ASIAN PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Nicholas Leeson set foot on British soil Sunday for the
first time since his wild trades on Asian futures markets in 1995
ran up debts of $1.4 billion, which brought down Britain's oldest
merchant bank and landed him in a Singapore jail.
</P>
<P>
   He is sorry for what he did at Barings Bank but he wants to
start over and rebuild his ruined life, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leeson, 32, was released Saturday from Tanah Merah prison in
Singapore and flew home overnight after serving just over half of a
6 1/2-year sentence for fraud and forgery as well as months of jail
time awaiting trial and sentencing. He is a free man physically,
released early for good behavior, but remains shackled financially
by a court order freezing his assets and restricting his access to
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to state clearly here that I know I did wrong,'' he
said, reading a statement at a hotel near Heathrow Airport. ``I am
not proud of my activities as a trader with Barings Bank in
Singapore. I was foolish and very much regret what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have done my time. I have taken my punishment, and now I
want to get on with the job of rebuilding my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in an open-necked shirt and chino slacks, a smile
flickering across his pale features, he did not take questions and
left the news conference immediately after reading his 25-line
statement. It was not clear where he would spend his first days
back in Britain, the country he was trying to reach when he fled
Asia in February 1995. He was seized by police while in transit in
Frankfurt, Germany, and sent back to Singapore for trial.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Stephen Pollard, said a court order obtained Friday
by Barings' liquidators allowed Leeson access to $7,900 a month of
his money. From that, he has to pay living costs, legal fees and
any medical bills for his treatment for colon cancer, which was
diagnosed last fall. The Singapore health authorities treated the
illness with surgery and chemotherapy. But, his lawyer said, Leeson
has been told there is a 30 percent chance that the cancer will
recur within four years.
</P>
<P>
   The former trader, who once lived a life of high-voltage risks
and high-ticket rewards on the Asian futures markets, returned to
England to face an array of questions from Barings' creditors about
his financial gains from a 1996 memoir, ``Rogue Trader,'' which has
been made into a recently released movie starring Ewan McGregor.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, a British newspaper has offered $160,000 for his
story. Many creditors do not want to see him profit from any of
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has now paid his dues, and perhaps that should be it,''
said Jill Frankel, a retired schoolteacher who, along with her
husband, lost $320,000 when the bank collapsed. But, she said in a
radio interview, ``I wouldn't like him to profit from his crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Simon Forster, the spokesman for Barings Preference
Shareholders Action Group, people had invested ``part or a very
substantial amount of their life savings in what was reputedly an
organization as safe as the Bank of England,'' adding, ``They feel
very let down indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   The court order bars Leeson from selling his story to news
organizations or from cashing in his profits from his memoir or the
movie. Pollard, the lawyer, dismissed suggestions that Leeson had
stashed away secret funds from his trading days or had returned
from Singapore with considerable assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has nothing left of any substance,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The court order requires Leeson to give Barings' liquidators two
days' notice before drawing on his funds. He must state where the
money originated and how he plans to spend it.
</P>
<P>
   Money is not the only problem he faces. After his imprisonment,
Leeson's wife, Lisa, divorced him and married another financial
trader. And Leeson's father has also had a diagnosis of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can perhaps imagine, this is a very emotional day for
me,'' he said Sunday. ``I've been in prison in a foreign land for
four years and four months. Just to be home and see my family again
is something I have longed for all that time.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not directly mention his former wife but said: ``When I
entered prison for the first time, one of the first things that was
said to me was, `Now you will find out who your friends are.'
Nothing could be more true. I have found out who my friends are,
and I would like to thank them all for their support.''
</P>
<P>
   Leeson ran up losses in arbitrage trades in futures contracts on
the Singapore and Japanese stock markets. His employers sent
millions from London to Singapore to cover his positions,
apparently without realizing that he was desperately trying to bid
up a falling market and losing more by the day as the Japanese
market spiraled down after the Kobe earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   But of all those involved in the bank's collapse and its
subsequent sale for one pound sterling to the Dutch group ING Groep
NV, Leeson was the only one to serve time in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard said Sunday that ``to his credit, from day one, Nick has
said he was the only person who was involved in criminal action''
relating to the bank's collapse. Nonetheless, the lawyer said,
Leeson felt he was the only Barings employee who has ``really paid
a serious price.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said his client had not yet made long-term plans.
``The shock of coming out of prison after four and a half years and
the knowledge of a 30 percent chance that he may be dead in four
years are not really conducive to long-term planning,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
