<SLUG> BC-TOURDEFRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAST IS PROLOGUE FOR TOUR'S ARMSTRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHALLANS, France _ Two days into the 86th Tour de France, the
jury is still out on whether the race has kept its popularity with
a public weary of doping scandals. But there was no doubt Sunday
that Lance Armstrong's victory in the opening prologue on Saturday,
after his battle with cancer, was exactly the symbol the race
organizers had wished for.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was happy with Saturday's result, Jean-Marie
Leblanc, the Tour's director, flashed a smile rarely seen in the
last year of turmoil and said: ``Yes _ for me, for the Tour and for
Lance above all. This is the Tour of renewal, of a return to the
top level, and look at him: He incarnates that.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, the 27-year-old Texan who returned to full-time
competition a little more than a year ago, looked splendidly happy
in the yellow jersey of the race's leader Sunday morning before the
start of the first of the Tour's 20 daily stages.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of his U.S. Postal Service team emphasized that it
would not go all out to keep his jersey in the week of sprinting to
come, which began with a 129-mile stage from Montaigu to the
poultry center of Challans in western France.
</P>
<P>
   ``There've been years when we would have killed to defend that
jersey,'' said Dan Osipow, the team's director of operations. ``But
not now. It's not worth our energy. We'll need that in the Alps.''
Saying that Armstrong will not risk injury in contesting mass
sprints, Osipow added, ``If we lose the jersey in the next week, we
aim to get it back in the mountains and keep it then.''
</P>
<P>
   After an early scare, Armstrong did keep the jersey for at least
another day, maintaining his lead over Alex Zuelle. The stage,
which was watched by big crowds during hours of rain, was won by
Jaan Kirsipuu, an Estonian with the Casino team.
</P>
<P>
   Thierry Gouvenou, a French rider for the Big Mat-Auber team,
launched a one-man attack at the 48th mile and built a lead that
nearly reached seven minutes, far more than enough to overcome his
54-second deficit after the prologue.
</P>
<P>
   Gouvenou, a journeyman rider from Normandy, is accustomed to
rain. What he is not accustomed to is maintaining a long lead over
179 pursuers. After more than 60 miles of solitary effort, he was
caught. Then it was the turn of another amphibian, the Belgian Ludo
Dierckxsens, who rides for Lampre, to test his luck.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few miles, however, the sprinters' teams brought
everybody together and the victory went to Kirsipuu, who finished
half a wheel ahead of Tom Steels, a Belgian with Mapei, and Erik
Zabel, a German with Telekom. Kirsipuu was timed in 4 hours 56
minutes 18 seconds, a speed of 26 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The pack, including Armstrong, finished in the same time. He
continued in the lead by 7 seconds over Zuelle, a Swiss with
Banesto, and by 11 seconds over Abraham Olano, a Spaniard with
ONCE. They finished in that order in the prologue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kirsipuu, who was 40 seconds behind in the prologue, used his
20-second victory bonus and a smaller one en route to move up to
sixth place, 16 seconds back.
</P>
<P>
   The huge numbers of spectators along the roads testified to the
continuing, if fragile, place of the Tour in the national psyche,
even though the crowd at the prologue on Saturday had seemed
smaller than usual.
</P>
<P>
   In the starting town of Montaigu, an informal poll of a dozen
people selected at random seemed to indicate that the public was
willing to give bicycle racing another chance despite the series of
doping scandals that began in the last Tour and have not yet ended.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anybody who rejected the race would not have been
found standing in the rain to see it go by.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a great race and worth watching, even if I don't
entirely trust the riders,'' a middle-age man under an umbrella
said. Hiding in a bus shelter against the squall, a young woman
said: ``One more scandal and it's all over. Till then, I remain a
fan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
