<SLUG> BC-KUWAIT-ELECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION SEEN AS BOOST TO EFFORT TO GIVE KUWAITI WOMEN THE VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT _ A landmark effort to extend voting rights to Kuwaiti
women won a boost here Sunday as the results of elections on
Saturday showed gains by liberal candidates who will form a
substantial bloc in the Persian Gulf's only elected Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In the 50-member Parliament, the liberal or liberal-leaning
deputies will hold 14 seats, up from four in the Parliament that
was dissolved in May. Most are expected to back an emiri decree
that would allow women to vote and hold office beginning in 2003.
Their support, along with that of pro-government candidates, is
likely to be enough to override Islamic opposition to the edict.
</P>
<P>
   But Kuwaiti analysts and Western diplomats said a victory for
women's rights was not yet guaranteed. The idea of political rights
for women is still controversial in Kuwait, and even liberals who
favor the idea may prefer to score points by standing up to the
royally appointed government.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Kuwait's ruling al-Sabah family has permitted a
level of political expression unknown elsewhere in the gulf,
creating a kind of safety valve for dissent. But its own centrist
supporters lost ground in the elections, and at least two-thirds of
the parliamentary seats will now be held by government critics,
either liberals or Islamists.
</P>
<P>
   In a hint of an olive branch, Deputy Prime Minister Sheik Sabah
al-Ahmed al-Sabah, who is now seen as the country's day-to-day
leader, said in remarks published on the weekend that he hoped the
legislative and executive branches would be able to work ``in
harmony as we enter the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   The government, still formally led by Sheik Saad al-Jaber
al-Sabah, the crown prince and prime minister, resigned Sunday to
await reformation later this month. But Saad, who is not a popular
figure, was expected to retain his powerful post, and some Kuwaiti
analysts predicted new storms in the notoriously unsettled
political environment.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the emiri edict to provide political rights to women
is being closely watched by Western governments, which had long
urged the step, and by Kuwait's Persian Gulf neighbors, who have
watched Kuwait's experimentation with democracy with a mixture of
admiration and dread.
</P>
<P>
   Under existing Kuwaiti law, only men were permitted to vote in
Saturday's elections. The biggest gains were by candidates aligned
with the National Democratic Movement, a two-year-old group whose
calls for expanding political rights to more Kuwaitis and limiting
government power make it Kuwait's most outspoken liberal body.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Islamists, from several political alignments, will
retain 20 seats, guaranteeing a firm platform for agendas that aim
to move Kuwait to the right, and that generally oppose the idea of
women voting or holding political office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, under Kuwaiti law, the government is guaranteed an edge
in the battle over the edict, which must be approved by the
Parliament. Cabinet ministers, appointed by the government, will be
allowed to vote, and if they can enlist the support of the new
liberal bloc, it will be difficult for opponents to muster the
votes necessary to block the decree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
