<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SEXTUPLETS-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERSHADOWED TEXAS SEXTUPLETS RECEIVE BELATED HELP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARBARA WHITAKER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For the parents of the world's first surviving
octuplets, born here in December, the birth was followed by a
wealth of gifts, including a 5,300-square-foot home, a tractor
trailer loaded with baby furniture, and all the diapers they
needed.
</P>
<P>
   But as the octuplets of Nkem Chukwu and Iyke Louis Udobi
captured the public's imagination and donations, another couple in
the Houston area were struggling to figure out how they would
provide for their less publicized accomplishment: the birth of the
first sextuplets in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Ann Collins gave birth to the first of the six children,
Christopher Allon on Oct. 18, with three girls and two boys coming
along on Nov. 11. Christopher Allon died shortly after birth, but
the other five children are home with their parents in Kingwood, an
unincorporated village of about 40,000 people 25 miles north of
downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowed by the birth of the McCaughey septuplets in Iowa in
November 1997, all of whom survived, and the octuplets, seven of
whom survived, the Collinses made few headlines and garnered few
gifts until this spring, when members of their church learned about
their plight. The Collinses also have a 2-year-old son with
cerebral palsy,
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that there are surviving septuplets, sextuplets aren't in
the limelight,'' said Janet Bleyl, president of the Triplet
Connection, an organization for families with multiple births of
three or more. ``It's terrible, but that's media.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Ms. Bleyl said, companies that once donated baby
items to couples with multiple births of at least three are
beginning to do less and making policies about what they will give.
Susan Lauritsen, who knew the Collinses through the Woodlands
United Methodist Church, found that out firsthand as she started
trying to help the family in early February.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I thought was needed was a phone call and people with
sextuplets were provided for,'' Ms. Lauritsen said.
</P>
<P>
   But once she started making calls, she found reality was very
different. Working from an Internet list of companies that provided
give-aways for newborns, she found that nearly one-third had
discontinued their programs for couples with multiple births.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Little Tikes Co., a subsidiary of Rubbermaid Inc.,
recently asked the Triplet Connection to publish a note in its
newsletter saying that the company was discontinuing a program that
provided donations for families with multiple births.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a listing of companies you can write to for some of
the freebies,'' Ms. Bleyl said, ``but there is no long-term
sustained kind of help out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lauritsen said she also sensed some backlash against parents
with children from multiple births.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Collins, sitting in the living room of her four-bedroom
home in Kingwood, said she had been challenged by people about why
she had not aborted some of the babies in a process known as
selective reduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tell us you should have gotten rid of some of them,''
she said. ``I look at them and say, `Who should I have reduced, who
should I have gotten rid of?'''
</P>
<P>
   Others say, ``You shouldn't have them if you can't afford
them,'' said her husband, Christopher Collins, who earns $41,000 a
year as a technician for Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Collinses, who went to a fertility specialist, said that
when they went through with a fertility procedure, it appeared that
there were only two eggs that would develop, so it was a surprise
when they learned they would have sextuplets.
</P>
<P>
   The Collinses had always wanted a family of seven. They just had
not expected to have all their children at one time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not begging for help,'' Christopher Collins said. ``These
kids are my responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Collinses have about $100,000 in medical bills remaining
after insurance covered the rest of the $2.5 million cost of the
births and extended hospital care.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Bleyl says that what families with multiple births receive
depends to some extent on where they live.
</P>
<P>
   ``The McCaugheys had an incredible community, an incredible
church community,'' she said of the Iowa family. ``If you live in
Los Angeles you probably don't know who lives next door, much less
get involved with who's having a baby down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   It was members of the Collinses' church, led by Ms. Lauritsen,
who began organizing their assistance.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of these efforts, the family has received donations
including diapers, baby food, strollers, five cribs and bedding.
Efforts are also being made to get them a bigger home and to
provide for the children in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see these kids through college,'' said Randall Reed,
who owns four Ford dealerships in Texas and has set up an education
and health fund for the children at Chase Bank of Texas. ``That's
my mission. I can't imagine what these people go through every day.
Their spirit consumes you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
