<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-OPPOSITION     07-04 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-OPPOSITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY OPPOSITION FIGURE RETURNS TO YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ A key figure in the Yugoslav opposition
movement who fled during the war with NATO returned Sunday evening
and dared President Slobodan Milosevic to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   Zoran Djindjic, a central figure in the opposition alliance that
two years ago staged the largest and most sustained street
demonstrations ever held against Milosevic, is facing up to 20
years in prison for avoiding military service during the Kosovo
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe Milosevic can take the risk to arrest me and
provoke protests around Serbia,'' Djindjic said at the Belgrade
airport, adding that he would appear in court here this week to
defend his decision to flee the country.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic, 46, a philosopher and former mayor of Belgrade who was
educated in Germany, fled the capital in early May after he said he
had received information that paramilitary thugs were planning to
kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before he left, a prominent opposition journalist,
Slavko Curuvija, was shot dead in the street after being accused on
state television of being a traitor. The government news media and
pro-Milosevic politicians made the same charge against Djindjic.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport, Djindjic told reporters he had flown into
Belgrade on Montenegrin Airlines, rather than drive through Serbia
in a private car, so that Milosevic's police could not arrest him
away from the glare of television cameras. He arrived from
Montenegro, the small, independence-minded republic that with
Serbia makes up Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic said he believed that the opposition movement here had
a matter of months to force Milosevic from power before world
attention wandered away from the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not too much time,'' Djindjic said. ``If we have
Milosevic in power after six months, it will be too late. The
attention of the international community will focus on us maybe
three or four months more.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the threat of being imprisoned by courts that Milosevic
controls, Djindjic is facing daunting political problems inside
Yugoslavia's fractured opposition movement.
</P>
<P>
   He has been criticized by other opposition leaders for fleeing
the country at a time of national crisis. Some of that criticism
has come from inside his own Democratic Party, which he helped
found and of which is president.
</P>
<P>
   A number of political analysts here say his standing as an
opposition leader has been weakened by his decision not to stay
with the people of Yugoslavia as they were being bombed.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic said that he had been of more use to the opposition
movement and to the future of Yugoslavia during the 11-week war by
getting out of the country and lobbying European governments to
give aid to individual cities where opposition to Milosevic was
strong.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and many European countries have said that
until Milosevic is removed from power, they will give only relief
assistance to Yugoslavia but will not help rebuild roads and
bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some countries are ready to make exceptions and help
opposition towns,'' said Djindjic, who spent much of the last two
months meeting with European leaders and talking to the press in
European capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic must also deal with the refusal of Vuk Draskovic,
leader of the largest single opposition party, to join with smaller
opposition parties in the Alliance for Change, an umbrella group
that is staging anti-Milosevic rallies around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, who accuses Djindjic of cowardice for fleeing during
the war, has said that the time is not right for street
demonstrations and that he wants to work from ``within the system''
to force Milosevic from power.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the opposition can succeed with Draskovic, who is by
far Yugoslavia's most charismatic politician and who has a proven
record of being able to bring tens of thousands of people into the
streets, Djindjic said popular disgust with Milosevic did not
depend on the personality of anyone in the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the feeling of the people is that they want change,''
Djindjic said. ``They cannot accept compromise. Those parties that
cannot accept that should leave the political scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic said it was not he who was taking a risk by returning
to Yugoslavia, but rather Milosevic who, by staying on in power,
risked his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best solution for him would be to go to The Hague,''
Djindjic said, referring to the International War Crimes Tribunal
that meets in The Hague, Netherlands. ``He is very clever. Maybe he
can explain himself _ I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
