<HEADER>
A9141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-MARCH-940(2T     07-04 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-MARCH-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORANGEMEN SCALE DOWN ULSTER MARCH, AVOIDING CONFLICT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ After British troops mounted the
tightest security operation seen in this most volatile of Ulster
towns, marching Orangemen Sunday scaled their procession from
Drumcree Church down to a token protest and said they hoped their
step back from confrontation would gain them an end to the ban on
parading along their traditional route.
</P>
<P>
   With arguments over disarmament stalling Northern Ireland's
moves toward ending decades of conflict, British troops went to the
greatest lengths to prevent a Protestant-Catholic confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as marathon talks in Belfast failed to resolve
differences between Ulster Unionists and Catholic politicians, the
troops erected barricades, dug trenches, strung miles of barbed
wire, flooded a stream to make it a moat, and plowed under fields
and then soaked them with tubfuls of water dropped from military
helicopters to make them boggy and impassable.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, nine officers of the Protestant marching order, dressed
in their dark suits, black bowler hats, white gloves and orange
bib-like collars strode purposefully to the 20-foot steel and
concrete barrier erected this week to block their path through an
adjoining Catholic neighborhood. Union Jacks, white and red Ulster
flags and pennants reading ``Drumcree: Here We Stand. We Can Do No
Other,'' fluttered in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Halting at the wall, they issued a verbal challenge to the Royal
Ulster Constabulary officer there to meet them, demanding an
explanation from Prime Minister Tony Blair and other British
officials for why they were being denied what they called their
civil right to proceed with their parade. Then they grimly marched
back to the church while thousands of Orangemen lining the country
lane by the parish graveyard applauded.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second straight year that the government-appointed
Parades Commission had ruled that the Orangemen could not march
down a road that is lined with Catholic housing blocks. In past
years, the event has been the flash point for firebombings in this
staunchly Protestant town, of riots on the hillside at whose crest
stands the stone church, and of violence in towns across the
province. The simple word ``Drumcree'' has come to connote the
moment each year when Northern Ireland is at its most explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Portadown is known as the Protestant citadel because the Orange
Order was founded near here in 1795, and the parade from the
downtown lodge hall out along Dungannon Street to Drumcree Church
and then back along the Garvaghy Road dates from 1807. The
Orangemen view their summer parades as cherished expressions of
traditional culture, but Catholics see them as triumphalist shows
of their one-time domination of life in Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sunday remained peaceful, the scene of neighbors
standing on adjoining hillsides separated by the no man's land
bristling with military equipment and staring at one another
through binoculars was a wrenching reminder of the tribal divide in
the British province. ``The rolls of razor wire I see stretched
along the fields across from the church and the metal barrier on
the road is again this year a symbol of the sad divisions of
Northern Ireland,'' said the Rev. John Pickering, Drumcree's
pastor.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally in a nearby field, the Orangemen called the Catholic
residents terrorist sympathizers and people who would rather live
off the state than work. Harold Gracey, worshipful district master
of Portadown Loyal Orange Lodge No. 1, said he would continue the
vigil he has kept at Drumcree since last year's turning back of the
parade and vowed never to meet with the leaders of the Garvaghy
Road residents.
</P>
<P>
   All the speakers stressed the peaceful nature of Sunday's
demonstration and said that Blair had hinted in the four meetings
he held last week with the Portadown Orange officers that
disciplined behavior Sunday might earn them reconsideration of the
parade ban in future.
</P>
<P>
   Their pleas that troublemakers stay away proved effective. In
the only arrest, the police stopped four men from Protestant East
Belfast headed here in a car with pickax handles, wire cutters,
combat clothing and gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The speakers attacked the prime minister for the plan that he
and his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, issued Friday night that
calls for the admission of Sinn Fein leaders into the new Northern
Ireland government on July 15 before there is any disarmament of
the Irish Republican Army. ``His plan is down the tubes, and the
sooner that sinks in, the better,'' Denis Watson, the County Armagh
grand master, said to loud cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Graffiti painted across the top of the barrier at which the
Orangemen halted proclaimed: ``No government for Sinn Fein-IRA''
and a sign on the wall depicted a ski-masked gunman with the simple
question ``Education Minister?'' beneath it.
</P>
<P>
   Other posters took on David Trimble, head of the Ulster Unionist
Party. Trimble is an Orangeman who once led the Portadown marchers
but is now reviled here because he signed the April 1998 peace
settlement, talked with the Garvaghy Road leaders and, as first
minister of the Northern Ireland Assembly, regularly meets Sinn
Fein figures.
</P>
<P>
   The plan produced by the two prime ministers after last week's
talks says that Sinn Fein will produce IRA arms on a timetable that
begins in September and ends in May of next year. The plan
threatens to shut down the hard-won new Northern Ireland
legislature if Sinn Fein does not meet the targets, and also if the
Ulster Unionist Party, the Protestant party that is the province's
largest, refuses to allow Sinn Fein to take up its two seats in the
10-member Cabinet to be named in two weeks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Trimble has called the plan ``fundamentally unfair'' to the
Unionists and told Blair in weekend telephone calls that his people
do not believe in the Sinn Fein commitment on disarming. He said he
had ``very serious problems'' with the proposal and that he thought
Sinn Fein leaders Gerry Adams and Martin McGuinness had succeeded
in ``deceiving'' the prime ministers with their disarmament talk.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in The Sunday Times of London, Blair urged the Unionists
not to misjudge this opportunity, saying it would be ``tragic and
inexplicable'' if they did not approve the blueprint and get the
new government embodied in the April 1998 peace settlement up and
running.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern tried to reassure Unionist doubts about the pledges from
Sinn Fein by saying that he and Blair had found the party more
credible than before. He also expressed hope that the IRA itself
might make a statement addressing widespread doubts that it will
ever dismantle its arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have always said in their phraseology `Sinn Fein-IRA'
in one breath, but I think it has become clearer in the last period
of time that it is not as simple as that,'' Ahern said in a Sky
News interview. ``Sinn Fein have stated their position
categorically and have given a Sinn Fein commitment that there
would be decommissioning by May next year. But there is not the
same clarity in what is in the IRA's position, so I do hope we get
a clear and unambiguous statement from the IRA in the not too
distant future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-99 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990704.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POVERTY-645&AMP;A     07-04 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POVERTY-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO START POVERTY TOUR IN KENTUCKY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., W.Va., Ohio)  (lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, Ky. _ ``The economic boom?'' asked Donna McDonald at
her roadside flea-market rack of used clothes _ humbly frayed
offerings that she has been buying more than selling lately as
local customers survive until their welfare checks this week.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDonald stared wide-eyed at the question of the boom, as if
directions were being sought to some nirvana far beyond the green
highlands and idle coal mines in this hard-core heart of
Appalachia. ``Not here,'' she noted of the whirring economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now a lot of people need extra money and sell me their
clothes instead of buying,'' Ms. McDonald said, explaining the
economic cycle as she lives it. ``It's tough here; we need jobs and
the economy ain't helped,'' she said, speaking as the daughter of a
coal miner, forced to become one of Appalachia's marginal
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton begins his tour of some of the United
States' most entrenched poverty regions on Monday, the
entrepreneurial impulse in the eastern hollows of Kentucky will be
on his agenda as he makes his first stop in London, Ky., 20 miles
to the west down the Daniel Boone Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   There he will focus on the bona fide success of Kentucky
Highlands, a 31-year-old anti-poverty program whose unusual
specialty is the gathering of venture capital via government loans
and charitable foundations to create businesses and jobs in
poverty-steeped areas.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 companies and 6,000 jobs have been fostered in nine
counties by Kentucky Highlands since Appalachia was first
dramatically designated in 1965 as a 13-state swath of intense
poverty deserving special regional aid and remedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a mystique about Appalachian people: They just don't
want to leave this land,'' Ray Moncrief, executive vice president
of Kentucky Highlands, said of the poor's tenacity in the tattered
coal fields.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton _ the first president to visit here since Lyndon B.
Johnson _ arrives, the statistical progress measured in the past 34
years by the Appalachian Regional Commission is significant: The
poverty rate, once 31 percent, has been cut to 15 percent, just two
points higher than the national average. The difference used to be
nine points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that the Great Society economic development programs
didn't work, I think, is just wrong,'' Jesse White Jr., co-chairman
of the Appalachian Regional Commission, said of the war on poverty
that began in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   President Ronald Reagan crimped the commission's programs, but
the regional approach survived and was formally reauthorized by
Congress last year after 16 years of uncertain budgeting. White
describes Appalachia's situation as ``halfway home and a long way
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In the more troubled hamlets, emerald hills resonate as before
with the hardscrabble life of residents like Ms. McDonald and her
scrawled sign proclaiming ``Donna's New and Used Clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Appalachia's most resistant areas _ much of West Virginia,
southern Ohio and eastern Kentucky _ still have unemployment and
poverty rates at least 50 percent higher than the rest of the
nation. A checkerboard pattern of diehard neediness in 108 of the
region's 406 counties leaves some residents reacting with a polite
shrug to the Clinton visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess anybody can go anywhere they want,'' said Boyd Asher,
a whatnot dealer sharing roadside space with Ms. McDonald. ``But it
seems like his big boom skipped this place,'' added Asher, yearning
for the steady paycheck of his old coal-mining job that was lost
when the industry moved on.
</P>
<P>
   ``That left us down in the dumps,'' said Asher, who drives the
school bus part-time and hustles used household goods on roads from
London to Harlan. ``Now the welfare cutbacks in food stamps and all
is hurting us bad. The only money around here is during the two
weeks after the welfare checks come.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At his side, Matt Collins, a retired coal miner and dealer in
assorted dishes and novelties, conceded total puzzlement about the
economy raging in so many other places. ``I just can't never figure
it out. Why can't they never get a factory in here?'' he said of
Clay County, where the unemployment rate is 80 percent worse than
the national average. Clinton, he said, trimmed back traditional
welfare on the promise of greater job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The president intends to highlight his new venture capital
program for impoverished areas. Dubbed New Markets Initiative, it
was announced in January as an attempt to use deferred-interest
loans and other incentives to draw the private sector more deeply
into the Small Business Administration's effort to spawn new
business and jobs in distressed areas.
</P>
<P>
   Local residents amiably speculate on why this proposal has come
more in the twilight than in the heyday of the Clinton
administration. But others stand ready to gratefully exploit the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never too late,'' said J.C. Egnew, an engineer who quit
the space program 27 years ago to settle here and become a
businessman, sensing a trainable and loyal pool of factory workers
clinging to the land.
</P>
<P>
   With venture capital help from Kentucky Highlands, Egnew has
created five factory businesses and more than 1,000 jobs, producing
hunting equipment, military tents and automobile air bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is the most powerful man on earth and whatever
he decides is important carries a lot of weight,'' said Egnew, a
community leader in Stearns who recently sponsored a new
computerized community college center to track the economy globally
so the next generation of Highlanders might be better prepared for
change.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why one coal-mine hollow inches toward recovery while
another does not, Egnew responded that the dominant factor beyond
all the aid programs seemed to be whether a community was willing
to dedicate itself to education as the engine of rescue. Otherwise,
he said, expectations remain low, political leaders rarely emerge,
and innovative ventures are never conceived.
</P>
<P>
   Such a community, he said, ``leans on those crutches'' that date
from the worst of Appalachian times in the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Kidd, a 36-year-old worker in Egnew's Outdoor Venture
business, is a coal miner's daughter who seized a job opportunity
as the rarest of Appalachia's resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm home-grown in this country, and I kind of progressed with
the times,'' she said, describing how she landed a start-up job as
a sewing-machine operator and worked her way up to supervisor and
now plant production manager overseeing all three work shifts. Ever
more galvanized, she also obtained a business degree in night
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great for the president to get a good picture of
our region,'' said Ms. Kidd, mindful of the luck of the draw in
life. ``If Mr. Egnew hadn't believed in the people here, what would
I be today?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kidd confessed to sadness lately with the high school
graduations depositing a fresh crop of teen-agers to hang around
with scant promise of a career. ``Mr. Clinton's visit couldn't hurt
anything around here,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
