<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     07-04 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WINNING WITH CLASS, EXITING WITH CLASS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Don't argue with the evidence, especially
when it's stacked against you. Andre Agassi tried hard to stir up
his passions, his competitive juices, but eventually realized he
would have to concede the day, surrender a court that is owned by
another.
</P>
<P>
   Center Court here at Wimbledon belongs to Pete Sampras, as it
once did to Steffi Graf, who went out in a more permanent sense
Sunday with nary a whimper or wave. Before Sampras won his men's
modern-record sixth Wimbledon and record-tying 12th Grand Slam
title, Graf lost the women's final to American Lindsay Davenport,
accepted her consolation salver, chatted amiably with the Duchess
of Kent and strode stoically off to announce that she was not
coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm a little sad about everything, which is normal
for the moment, but in a way I still feel like a winner getting out
of this tournament,'' she said after failing to win her eighth
Wimbledon title, while Davenport earned her first, by 6-4, 7-5.
Then on came Sampras to set off a fireworks display of power
serving in a 6-3, 6-4, 7-5 takeout of Agassi and complete an
American double by a pair of Southern Californians, on the Fourth
of July.
</P>
<P>
   Graf had trouble reading Davenport's crisp forehand, misplayed
too many backhands, but in the end, as usual, held tight her
emotional rein. When Martina Navratilova bid Center Court farewell
back in 1994, a tear slid down her cheek as she reached over to
pluck a blade of souvenir grass. Few expected less from Martina,
but Graf is who she is, in a perpetual state of unflappable grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was her day, and I wanted to keep it that way,'' she
said, deferring to Davenport while explaining her straightforward
exit and refusing to say if she'll play the U.S. Open next month.
</P>
<P>
   Graf is entitled to change her mind, the way Boris Becker, her
German compatriot, did, after informing Sampras at the net that he
was through following their match here two years ago. Becker missed
the stage and returned this year for a farewell redux. Graf is more
likely to hold to her decision, believing that her oft-injured body
has given her one last window of opportunity this summer _ which
the champion inside her seized by winning the French Open and
coming close here.
</P>
<P>
   Some accept these reality bites more easily than others, like
John McEnroe, who received the bad news from Graf on Saturday that
a strained left thigh compelled her to withdraw from their mixed
doubles semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, we could win this,'' McEnroe pleaded, when he should
have said he understood. That, at 40, he'd had his day.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy, realistic perspective is a wonderful thing. When
Agassi, for instance, was asked how it felt to be the world's new
No. 1 player in the arcane computer ranking, he cracked: ``How
'bout that? I didn't feel much like No. 1 out there today.''
</P>
<P>
   He came out determined, saying he needed a fast start against
the player he called ``a great front-runner.'' So it was that he
found himself at 3-3 in the first set, with triple break point on
Sampras' serve. Time for a fireworks display for the folks back
home, breakfast bombs bursting in air.
</P>
<P>
   First serve winner to the backhand. First serve to the backhand.
First serve and forehand volley. First service winner. First
service winner. Ace. A total of two Agassi strokes in play on five
Sampras points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unreturnables,'' Agassi called the Sampras artillery, which
not surprisingly preceded the breaking of Agassi in the very next
game and a run of 23 of 25 points that soon had the Las Vegan down
a set and a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing in the zone,'' the 27-year-old Sampras said.
``As well as I can play, plain and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Agassi was suspected of mentally disappearing at
times like these, but after reinventing himself from No. 141 to No.
1, the 29-year-old version wasn't going away without one last
crack. It came four games into the second set, Sampras serving at
2-1, 15-15. He hit a forehand approach, which Agassi measured for a
wicked backhand pass cross court.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras dived, flicked the racquet for a backhand volley winner
and rolled creakily over on his stomach. While he picked himself
up, appendage by appendage, right elbow bloodied, Agassi glared
from the baseline, hands on hips. He now understood that this day
was about Sampras, virtually ignored all tournament, except when it
counted most.
</P>
<P>
   While American women's tennis is deeper than ever _ with
Davenport, the Williams sisters and the emergence here of Alexandra
Stevenson _ some thought the 24th career match between Sampras and
Agassi could jump-start the slumping men's game, back in the
States. Nike's Phil Knight _ sponsor of both men and Davenport, too
_ viewed the day as a marketing coup. Brad Gilbert, Agassi's coach,
perceived it as both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great day for American tennis,'' Gilbert told Knight, in
passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great day for Nike,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nike is American tennis,'' Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the crass corporate line, but Sampras' 12 Slams, tying
Roy Emerson's record, speak for themselves. This is a deserving,
dignified champion, defined by his superior athleticism and
fundamental purity. Is he not charismatic enough? Depends what
you're selling.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming here, I spent 10 days extolling the virtues of Tim
Duncan, another young athlete who speaks with performance, with
calm and cool, who comes off well centered, on court and off. It's
not the only way to be, but it's not a bad way to go. From hello to
goodbye, it has made Steffi Graf, for more than half her 30 years,
a Center Court star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
