<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY PONDERS HIS OPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ General manager Bill Bavasi and pitcher Chuck
Finley spoke over the weekend about Finley's future with the
Anaheim Angels. Finley, whose contract expires at the end of this
season, previously had talked about the possibility of being traded
to a contender if and when the Angels fall out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the possibility of Finley getting a contract
extension, though he said terms have not been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's right for me to do anything contractually,
not when the team is scuffling,'' Finley said. ``It wouldn't be
right, it would be very selfish of me. It wouldn't be right for me
to go in there with the team 10{ games out and say, `Give me this
or that,' when the team needs help.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Finley said, the priority in his career right now is
winning, wherever it might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win,'' he said. ``I want to get it going the right
way or go somewhere where it's going to happen that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money part of the contract is the last thing on my mind,
because I want to win. I'd like to (win in Anaheim), but the
possibility of that happening is grayer and grayer every day. The
way other teams are playing, it's going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who is making $5.8 million this season, said he hopes to
play two or more three seasons, but the length of a possible
extension with the Angels hasn't come up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing they've spoken to me about is they don't want
to get locked in to a long-term contract with players that have
played a long time,'' Finley said. ``My response was, `I've never
been hurt, so why are you telling me that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   __ Phone it in: Pitcher Mike Fyhrie is expected to be called up
from Triple-A Edmonton today and start Tuesday's game against the
Mariners in Tim Belcher's spot (broken right pinky finger).
</P>
<P>
   Fyhrie is 8-5 with a 3.40 ERA for Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odd call: It might have seemed strange to see manager Terry
Collins send Jeff Huson to pinch-hit for Todd Greene in a crucial
situation, as was the case Saturday night. But Greene hasn't been
the hitter the Angels have expected him to be. Even though Huson
struck out with the potential tying runs on base in an eventual 9-7
loss, the numbers on Greene don't lie.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is hitting .200 with runners in scoring position this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, he hasn't been swinging very good,'' Collins
said. ``It was a chance to tie the game up and I wanted to put a
left-handed hitter in there.
</P>
<P>
   __ Center of attention: Darin Erstad got the start in center
field Sunday, his first since 1997. Garret Anderson went to the DH
spot to get a breather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was '97 against the Twins at home, either May or June,''
Erstad said of his last start in center. ``Terry came up to me and
just asked me if it was OK to put me out there and I said, `OK.'
It's pretty much the same to me. I get to play. I know it sounds
generic, but I don't care where I play.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Right woes: Mo Vaughn has struggled this season hitting
against right-handed pitchers. Going into Sunday's game, he was
hitting .224 against righties, though he did show signs of
improvement during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He analyzes himself as a hitter better than anybody I've been
around,'' Collins said. ``He can pick things out.''
</P>
<P>
   Against lefties, Vaughn is hitting .397.
</P>
<P>
   __ Next up: The Angels return home for a three-game series
against the Mariners beginning today at 7:35 p.m. RH Shigetoshi
Hasegawa (1-2, 3.69 ERA) will start for Anaheim against Seattle's
LH Jeff Fassero (3-8, 7.21).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
