<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-EVANS-ART-625&AMP;AD     07-04 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EVANS-ART-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S RIGHT-HAND MAN IS A FRIEND WITH A MIDAS TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Back in Midland, in the harrowing, exhilarating
oil days of rising gushers and falling prices, they all had
nicknames: Dennis Grubb was ``Wemus,'' George W. Bush was
``Boosto'' or ``the Bombastic Bushkin,'' Joe O'Neill was ``Spider''
and Donald L. Evans was usually ``Evvie'' or ``Donnie.''
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, just to annoy the future politician in the
rambunctious Bush, the friends used to call Evans by another name:
``Governor.'' Back then, in the '70s and '80s, it was Evans'
earnest, organized demeanor that seemed more suitable for an
executive office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could just as easily have been Donnie,'' said Grubb, then
an oil man and now an entertainment promoter, referring to the
sense of political destiny now gathering around Bush, the governor
of Texas. ``He could have been any kind of politician or elected
official he wanted, just like George. And now I think he'll make a
great chief of staff.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a little early, of course, to start casting a Bush
Cabinet, even if Evans' perfectly graying temples make him a
TV-movie dream of a distinguished White House official.
</P>
<P>
   But as the chief fund-raiser of Bush's presidential campaign,
Evans announced something last week that impressed the political
world like few other achievements: The campaign had raised $36
million in just four months, more than any other candidate had ever
collected in the entire primary season.
</P>
<P>
   With money now scrutinized as carefully as opinion polls, this
announcement only heightened the sense of inevitability carefully
cultivated by Bush's advisers, and gave the impression that Evans
had wrought some kind of financial miracle. More than once he has
heard it said that Bush had found his Jim Baker, the close friend
and aide of Bush's father, the former president. This kind of talk
brings an exasperated smile to Evans' face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not that,'' he said. ``I'm just the money guy. If
anything, it's more appropriate that somebody call me the Bob
Mosbacher of the campaign'' _ a reference to another wealthy oil
man and adept fund-raiser who became President Bush's commerce
secretary in 1989. (Evans doesn't rule out a possible move to
Washington in the future.)
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, of course, Evans, who will be 53 later this
month, is a rather fortunate money guy. He has collected checks
from 75,000 of the United States' most prosperous citizens at an
economic peak, and on behalf of a charmer with a well-known name
who is considered a Republican savior. It is in his nature to
minimize his achievement, but in this case there is some truth to
his modesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the easiest fund raising I've ever done in my life,''
Evans said in an interview at campaign headquarters in a plush
office building down the street from the state Capitol, far more
comfortable than the usual utilitarian jumble. ``Usually political
campaigns are a tough sell, and you always worry that someone's
going to ask you for something in return. This time, you call
someone and they say: `Oh, I'm so glad you called me. I was
wondering how to make a contribution.'''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also clear that Bush chose his national finance
chairman carefully, entrusting his family's extensive network of
money raisers to his best friend, a man with a similar background
and sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, chairman of the University of Texas Board of Regents and
chief executive of Tom Brown Inc., a Midland oil and gas company,
knows almost everyone Bush knows in Texas, where a third of the
treasury was raised.
</P>
<P>
   And being the candidate's best friend made it easier to set up a
network of ``Pioneers,'' who are each raising $100,000, and to call
upon governors who have endorsed Bush to push their state
check-writing operations into overdrive.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His experience seeking backers for oil ventures had already led
Evans to become the leading fund-raiser for Bush's campaigns for
governor, but their most formative moments together go back to
Midland in the 1970s, when both arrived in West Texas at the same
time to partake in what Evans calls the ``entrepreneurial heaven''
of the oil business.
</P>
<P>
   Evans had a mechanical engineering degree from the University of
Texas and no real background in the field. But his father had
worked for Shell Oil in Houston, where Evans grew up. His wife,
Susie, grew up in Midland with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He signed up with Tom Brown, a classic independent wildcatter,
and spent two months as a roughneck on the company's rigs before
moving back to the office and eventually assuming the company's
leadership from Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Evans invested in a few wells with Bush's firm, and the two
became inseparable, riding out the depths of the oil business and
regularly shooting baskets and playing golf.
</P>
<P>
   Their families were also close, and Evans said the Bushes were
an invaluable source of support after the Evanses' second daughter,
who is mentally retarded, was born. Evans, a devout Methodist,
calls that event one of the greatest things that ever happened to
him. (He and his wife later adopted their third child, a boy.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more than business,'' he said. ``We shared a lot of the
same values and beliefs. Both of us were out there at the same age,
building our families, pursuing the American dream, both of us
believing our highest calling in life is to serve other people,
getting involved in United Way, our church, immersing ourselves in
the community. Of course, I always knew who the candidate was going
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the cadences of his speech reflect his immersion in his
friend's world. Instead of ``around the country,'' he says with
repeated passion ``around this great country of ours.'' Driven by
his fierce friendship, he sees his current calling as a form of
public service, with each flurry of $1,000 checks reflecting not
political calculation but hope for America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind every check, there's a willing heart,'' Evans said.
``To me, it's not a check; it's a person, someone who cares about
this great country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
