<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARGAS MIGHT BE LAST CHANCE FOR MARQUEZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raul Marquez once was one of those can't-miss amateur fighters.
Promoters fell over one another in an attempt to sign him after he
reached the quarterfinals of the 1992 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's hard to take the left-hander from Houston too
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear not long into his pro career that he's resilient
but limited. His boxing skills are solid but nothing special. And
he doesn't have a big punch. He's also easy to hit, which doesn't
do much for a fighter's career.
</P>
<P>
   His vulnerability was particularly obvious in two forgettable
performances _ a disputed points victory over Keith Mullings and an
eighth-round knockout loss to Yory Boy Campas, his only defeat in
which he lost the IBF junior middleweight title.
</P>
<P>
   Now Marquez has a chance to prove he's not just a coulda-been by
facing current IBF junior middleweight champion Fernando Vargas of
Oxnard on July 17 at Lake Tahoe. Vargas, for one, doesn't like
Marquez's chances.
</P>
<P>
   The champion (16-0, with 16 knockouts) was asked to compare
Campas, whom he knocked out to take the IBF title, to Marquez
(30-1, 20 KOs).
</P>
<P>
   ``Campas can withstand a lot of punishment and he hits hard,''
Vargas said. ``Raul Marquez can withstand a lot of punishment, but
he !ital!can't hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference between Marquez and Campas.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad to say. Usually southpaws are intelligent fighters,
hard to hit. Raul isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that fair? Is Marquez just another opponent for a fast-rising
champion? Or were the Mullings and Campas fights anomalies? Marquez
insists the latter is the case.
</P>
<P>
   He admits the Mullings fight, in which Marquez suffered a
terrible cut over his left eye, was close. However, he believes he
deserved the decision over the fill-in opponent who evolved into
one of the division's better fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez also believes he shouldn't have taken the Campas bout
only 2{ months later because his face was unusually tender. The
close fight was stopped in the eighth round with Marquez, his eye
closed shut, barely able to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   He fought Campas at least in part because of criticism following
the Mullings fight and took an eight-month break to heal afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taking heat for the Mullings fight,'' he said. ``A lot
of the press thought I lost. I thought it was close, but I think I
pulled it out in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press knows, knowledgeable boxing people know, I lost (to
Campas) because I wasn't ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas also has referred to what he believes is Marquez's
propensity to get cut.
</P>
<P>
   The champion heard somewhere that Marquez has had 300 stitches
to close various cuts on his face _ which Vargas said is
``amazing'' and Marquez claimed is untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez hasn't been cut in his two fights since losing to Campas
and said his skin is completely healed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I have 300 stitches and keep boxing?'' Marquez said.
``He's being kind of childish, really. He's a kid; he talks a lot.
And when you get a guy like that, a guy who talks a lot, it means
he's worried. He knows he's in the toughest fight of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've studied his fights. I've seen the mistakes he does. I
feel I'm very confident, going to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   More likely, this will be his last hurrah.
</P>
<P>
   __ Vargas' future: Shelly Finkel, Vargas' co-manager, said he
and the handlers of WBA champion David Reid are nearing a deal for
a unification bout between May and September of next year.
</P>
<P>
   If things go as planned, that fight would be the finale of a
four-fight deal with HBO. Vargas-Marquez is the first of the four.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big fight, a big occasion,'' Vargas said. ``I'm
trying to unify this division. If God gives me the power, that's
what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas and Reid were teammates on the 1996 Olympic team. Reid,
who defends his title against journeyman Kevin Kelly on July 16 in
Atlantic City, N.J., was the only American to win a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   __ Post fight: Johnny Tapia continues to believe he beat Paulie
Ayala in the fight-of-the-year candidate June 26 in Las Vegas.
However, he seems to be coping well with the fact he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala outpointed Tapia to win the WBA bantamweight championship
in Las Vegas. It was the first loss of Tapia's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every champion, Robinson, Ali, Tyson, everybody's gotta
lose,'' Tapia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost. That's what the judges thought I did. There's nothing
you can do, nothing you can say. It's on the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it makes me more focused, it makes me push harder to
another world title.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Tapia wants immediate redemption and to become
champion again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in good shape right now,'' he said. ``Nothing
happened to me in the fight. If they can put it on tomorrow, I can
do it. I want a rematch to get the belt back and prove I won the
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala said his future is up to his handlers. Of course, that's
not entirely true; he has the final say on all his fights. If he
!ital!really wanted to fight Tapia again, he probably could.
</P>
<P>
   He also said, ``Now's the time to get compensated.'' That could
mean a few relatively easy paydays before he takes on an opponent
as tough as Tapia again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is the business aspect of this now,'' Ayala
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia said life will go on if he might never fight Ayala again,
but he had bitterness in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a rematch don't come, it don't make no difference to me,''
he said. ``I have three, four fighters, world champions, I can
fight. I'll go for them.''
</P>
<P>
   __ More Tapia: Tapia had after the Ayala fight he was through
with promoter Bob Arum, with whom his contract has expired.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's not so sure. Tapia has talked business with several
promoters, including Arum.
</P>
<P>
   __ Moving up: Oscar De La Hoya said his title-unification fight
with Felix Trinidad on Sept. 18 will be his last at the 147-pound
welterweight division.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been difficult for me to make the weight in this
division, and if I beat Trinidad and he wants a rematch, it'll have
to be in the super-welter category,'' he said. ``I'm not a natural
welter. I'm not going to fight anymore as a welter.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Vargas' two cents: Vargas, no fan of De La Hoya, predicts
Trinidad will beat the Golden Boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on his last two fights, Oscar looks beatable,'' he said.
``Trinidad has looked solid, strong. It looks like he has the eye
of the tiger you're supposed to have, that a hungry champion has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar hasn't shown that. I'm going with Trinidad.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Rabbit punches: Reid will be featured on ``George Michael
Sports Machine'' on Sunday. The sports news program is scheduled
for 11:45 p.m. on Channel 4. . . . Arturo Gatti will return to the
ring against Puerto Rican Reyes Munoz on Aug. 14 in Mashantuckett,
Conn., on HBO's ``Boxing After Dark.'' In the main event, Stevie
Johnston will defend his WBC lightweight title against Angel
Manfredy. . . . Undefeated Zab Judah will face David Sample in a
10-round junior welterweight bout Friday in Cape Cod, Mass., on
ESPN2. Sample was chosen as Judah's opponent because his style is
similar to that of Sharmba Mitchell, the WBA champion Judah is
trying to entice into the ring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
