u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-CAMPAIGN-FOURTH-NY     07-04 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-CAMPAIGN-FOURTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULY 4 PARADE IN NEW HAMPSHIRE BECOMES PARADE OF CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRIMACK, N.H. _ It was so smotheringly hot here Sunday that
even the ever-immaculate Elizabeth Dole perspired through the back
of her blouse. But the heat did not stop Anna Britton, on the
sidelines of the Independence Day parade, from reaching out her
arms when she saw Gov. George W. Bush approaching on fast-moving
cowboy boots, flashing his Clint Eastwood crow's feet.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his own sopping shirt, Bush obligingly hugged her,
eliciting an exultant cry from Ms. Britton, a Massachusetts tire
company owner, of, ``I have Bush sweat!''
</P>
<P>
   That celebrity-style encounter was just one of the ways that
this southern New Hampshire town's July 4 parade acted largely as a
parade of candidates _ turning poll and finance numbers into flesh,
and allowing presidential hopefuls whose numbers look weak to try
to counteract them with contact among residents who vote in the
nation's first primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, first among the candidates in the parade, was as much a
front-runner there as he is in the polls and financial tallies,
jogging from one side of the crowd to another so energetically that
by parade's end, droplets of sweat dripped to the ground from under
his chin. His deep blue signs far outnumbered any others in the
crowd, and his reception seemed the loudest.
</P>
<P>
   Front-runner status also entails greater scrutiny, however.
Earlier in the day, in nearby Amherst, N.H., Bush had faced
questions from reporters about an article that appeared on the
front page of Sunday's Los Angeles Times saying that he had
``received favorable treatment and uncommon attention'' when he
served as a pilot in the Texas Air National Guard. It said there
was ``no evidence of illegality or regulations broken'' in Bush's
military career, but ``doors were opened and good fortune flowed to
him'' at a time when his father was a congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, now the governor of Texas, was quoted by The Associated
Press as saying: ``I asked to become a pilot. I met the
qualifications, and I ended up becoming an F-102 pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Merrimack parade, Bush was too busy pumping the public's
hands to fend off delicate questions. But his activity level was
nearly rivaled by Mrs. Dole, the former president of the American
Red Cross. She crisscrossed the parade path wearing a wireless
``lavaliere'' microphone, her voice projected by mobile speakers
that trundled along in a car behind her.
</P>
<P>
   She never said much more than ``Happy holiday to you!'' and
``Hello, thank you for coming,'' but she said it many, many times,
and the turnout of Dole volunteers in yellow T-shirts appeared to
run a close second in numbers to the Bush hordes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Mrs. Dole and Bush had exchanged what seemed
a significantly warm greeting, but both said afterward that they
were just good friends with high opinions of each other, and
assiduously avoided playing into speculation that Mrs. Dole might
serve well as Bush's ticket mate.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Sunday afternoon if her campaign thinking would be
affected by Bush's strong poll showings and recent announcement
that his campaign had amassed a record $36.3 million in four
months, she exclaimed, ``No way!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Money matters,'' she said, ``but it's ideas, it's vision. The
landscape is strewn with politicians who had tons of money and
outspent their opponents, and never got to the finish line.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Mrs. Dole said, she believes her campaign is
attracting many voters, particularly young people, who are not
being captured in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Farther back in the parade line and further down in the
popularity polls, similarly undaunted sentiments came from other
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the millionaire publisher, was campaigning
elsewhere, but Paul Young, a senior advisor, said that Forbes
planned to raise as much money as every candidate except Bush. And
then, he said, Forbes ``will match him dollar for dollar in
spending in order to overcome the advantages that Bush has as a
special-interest, Washington-insider politician.''
</P>
<P>
   If money were everything, said Gary Bauer, former president of
the conservative Family Research Council in Washington, ``We'd be
finishing up the second Ross Perot term.'' Standing chummily with
the conservative commentator Patrick Buchanan, Bauer said, ``I know
Pat and I both are anxious to get the governor on a stage and ask
him why he's in favor of Most Favored Nation status for China,''
and other questions.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who received 37 percent in the New Hampshire
Republican primary in 1992 and won it in 1996, recalled that in
1991, President Bush ``was at 91 percent in the polls and president
of the United States. Talk about formidable odds _ that's when you
come up here and have Air Force One land behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore missed the parade, but his New Hampshire
campaign manager, Bill Shaheen, said he was on ``baby watch,''
waiting for the overdue birth of his first grandchild. Bush's
strong lead did not concern the Gore campaign, said Shaheen, who is
the husband of New Hampshire's governor, Jeanne Shaheen. At this
point, he said, Gore workers are focused on winning the primary, on
reaching Democrats and potential Democratic converts.
</P>
<P>
   The other Democratic contender, former Sen. Bill Bradley, had no
visible presence at the Merrimack parade.
</P>
<P>
   Among parade-watchers queried, there were still a great many
undecideds, though many showed a decided willingness to accept the
yellow Dole mini-frisbees, the Bush stickers with sheriff's stars
printed on them and the candy scattered by the Forbes car.
</P>
<P>
   At heart, many seemed in the same state as 98-year-old Yvonne
Carter, who rode in the parade as Merrimack's oldest citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still debating it,'' she said of her choice for president.
Asked what she was looking for in a candidate, she replied, ``A
good, honest man.'' And, she was asked, hadn't she spotted one yet?
``No, I haven't,'' she replied firmly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
