u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-PAKISTAN-710&AMP;ADD     07-04 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-PAKISTAN-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION OFFICIALS EXPECT PAKISTANI FORCES TO WITHDRAW FROM
DISPUTED AREA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After three hours of hastily arranged talks here
between President Clinton and the Pakistani prime minister, Nawaz
Sharif, administration officials said Sunday that they expect that
Pakistani-backed forces would withdraw from their mountain redoubt
on the Indian side of the cease-fire line in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials, who participated in the sessions with the two
leaders, seemed uncertain how or even if Sharif would be able to
guarantee a withdrawal of the forces, who the administration
believes are controlled by the Pakistani military and include some
of its soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   A joint statement by Clinton and Sharif after the unusual
Independence Day talks said ``concrete steps'' would be taken to
restore the cease-fire line in the disputed Himalayan territory.
But it left unclear how far the meeting had gone toward calming an
increasingly volatile standoff between the world's two newest
nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding is that there will be a withdrawal of the
forces now,'' a senior administration official said after the
meeting. But he added, referring to the Pakistani leader, that ``we
cannot say how he will pursue'' the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty appeared to arise from Sharif's tricky political
situation at home, where Pakistan's population and military are
likely to resist backing down. Further, it remains unclear whether
Sharif has full control over the mountain fighters or even his own
military command, which has run the government either overtly or
from the shadows for much of its history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also spoke Sunday by telephone with the Indian prime
minister, Atal Behair Vajpayee, during a break in the talks to
inform him of what was going on, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The incursion of the Pakistani forces in May has severely
exacerbated the long-running tensions over Kashmir, raising the
stakes with the possibility of a regional war for the first time
since the two countries tested nuclear weapons last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the urgency of the situation we expect to see action in
the very near future,'' an administration official said after the
talks. ``We'll have to see whether they follow through in the
coming days.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said the Pakistanis understood that the threat of
escalation of the conflict meant that the current situation ``has
to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the official said, the talks had produced a
sequencing of events: withdrawal of forces, cessation of the
hostilities begun in May and then a return to the Lahore
Declaration of last February. Under the Lahore Declaration, the
Indian and Pakistani leaders agreed to peacefully work out their
countries differences.
</P>
<P>
   But before returning to the Lahore talks, which are designed to
deal with a wide gamut of issues, Clinton urged Sharif to resolve
the current incursion first, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fighters crossed the so-called line of control nearly
two months ago, India has warned that it could not allow the
situation to continue. The line of control has divided the province
since a 1972 agreement between India and Pakistan, known as the
Simla Accord.
</P>
<P>
   In their statement, Sharif and Clinton said they recognized that
the current fighting was ``dangerous and contains the seeds of a
wider conflict.'' The statement added that ``the president urged an
immediate cessation of the hostilities'' once the cease-fire line
had been restored.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why Sharif had asked for a rush appointment with Clinton
appeared to baffle administration officials. Vajpayee had declined
a similar offer of a meeting in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a continuing dialogue that Clinton has been running
with Sharif and Vajpayee, Sharif called the White House on Saturday
morning and told Clinton he had some ideas that he wanted to talk
about urgently in person with the president, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is scheduled to be traveling across the country for
the next few days, invited him to come at once.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the gravity of the distrust between India and
Pakistan and the unpredictability of the domestic politics in both
countries, and the fact that they are now nuclear armed, Sharif's
apparent plea for help was too important for Clinton to ignore,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Before the meeting Sunday afternoon, administration officials
said they expected Sharif to press Clinton hard to play the role of
an international mediator. But this is a role that the
administration, despite its keen interest in stabilizing the
flashpoint, believes it cannot take on, officials said. To do so,
they said, would be to side with Pakistan, as India has long said
that the conflict should be settled between the two countries
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's desire to come to Washington was probably driven in
large part to get political cover from Clinton for the hard job of
persuading his military to withdraw, several officials suggested.
</P>
<P>
   On his return home, Sharif will presumably have to face the
chief of army staff, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, a more activist
military leader who was appointed to the job after the removal of
the former chief of staff last October.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani military has denied that it controls the forces
that crossed into the craggy peaks of the area. The military has
claimed that the fighters are Muslim freedom fighters. India
maintains that the men are Pakistani army regulars.
</P>
<P>
   In public, the Clinton administration says that Pakistan is
supporting the forces but is vague about who the forces are. Less
publicly, administration officials assert that the forces _
described as about 700 men dug into mountains _ are most likely a
mixture of guerrillas and Pakistani soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani government's insistence that it does not control
the fighters will make it politically difficult for Sharif to live
up to the pledge that he appeared to have made to the
administration Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Further, returning home with a deal that looks as though he has
bent to American pressure is politically risky for the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir has been the main issue at stake between overwhelmingly
Muslim Pakistan and Hindu India since the two countries were
created from the British Empire in 1947. Pakistan asserts that
Kashmir, with a large Muslim majority, should have the right to
vote on whether to join India or Pakistan. Secular India claims
Kashmir as one of its states.
</P>
<P>
   The current fighting is taking place on peaks more than 15,000
feet high. On Saturday, India claimed that it had captured the
strategic Tiger Hill from the Pakistanis, a position from which the
Pakistanis had been able to hit at an important Indian military
supply road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
