<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9165 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-ANALYSI     07-04 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-ANALYSIS-BOS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT DECISION PRODUCES AT WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 Repeating for Green Bay
 &HT;    By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   LONDON _ Should I divorce my wife?
</P>
<P>
   This is a reasonable question that men across the world are
asking themselves after watching or reading about newly unattached
Andre Agassi playing a game called tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Not to give Brooke Shields a bad rap. They remain great and good
friends, says Agassi, and probably have joint custody of the People
magazine subscription. Nevertheless, since their April uncoupling,
Agassi has supercharged up the pike like an express train. Call him
the Las Vegas Cannonball. Agassi's post-parting record _ his split
parade _ is 20-2, including Hong Kong and French Open titles and a
13-match winning streak that goes on the line Sunday at the Big W
against his acquaintance and rival of 18 years, Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   New bachelor Agassi showed he'll have no problems with domestic
duties after whipping up a hot and spicy recipe in a Wimbledon
barbecue pit called Court 1. Rafter, the net-marauding Aussie who
has won the last two US Opens, was tough, all right. But Agassi,
marauding through a 7-5, 7-6 (7-5), 6-2 win, was tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick could nudge and coax only two break points all Saturday
afternoon against Agassi's serve, which has grown muscle and eyes
over the recent weeks. ``Everything he does is terrific,'' Rafter
says, ``but the way his serve has improved really impressed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi hasn't lost serve in a week, 56 consecutive holds since
somebody named Albert Martin broke through by accident. Those
scarce breakers that Rafter glimpsed happened to be set points at
4-5, 15-40, that could have changed everything. But Agassi gave
those vitals the brushoff as though they were aluminum siding
salesmen hoping to remodel one of his palaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my first real opening,'' says Rafter, ``but I didn't
realize then it would be my last. Andre never let me in. I couldn't
find any inroads.''
</P>
<P>
   So Patrick was on the outroad to Boston for the Australia-US
Davis Cup showdown at Longwood, inwardly rejoicing that Agassi
won't be there, too.
</P>
<P>
   One shot told you how Agassi was reveling. Set point in the
tiebreaker, Rafter serving at 5-6. Agassi caromed a double-barreled
backhand return past Rafter so quickly that the Aussie had taken
only a step or two on his route to the net. He flicked the ball
like a half-volley, so early that you wondered if he had allowed it
to bounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I saw that ball _ the balls all afternoon _ really
well,'' enthuses Agassi. The set ended, and so did Rafter, although
they played the third required by rules.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to Sunday afternoon, and the duel at 26-or-so
paces on a patch of lawn that is starting to look as barren as
Agassi's head. As ragged as King Pete's chances to keep his crown
if both men continue at their present pace.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, just about gonzo in Paris, lagging behind the 1998 champ
Carlos Moya by a set and 4-1 in the fourth round, suddenly found
the combination that lifted him beyond previous glories and put him
on another planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard work, focus, passion came together,'' says the restored
one, his brown button eyes gleaming thankfully. ``I found there's
much more left in me _ for several years. Who would have believed
it a month ago? I had recovered from the terrible fall to 142 in
the rankings. I was starting to play big tennis again, but I wasn't
winning big matches _ until Paris. Until Moya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Pete again. It's great. This is all the way from
Northridge (Calif.) to Centre Court,'' he laughs at the memory of
two little boys belting balls at each other on a concrete slab in
1981, a 12-and-under tournament. ``I was 11; Pete was 10, about a
foot shorter than me. He's grown a little since. He had a
two-handed backhand then, and he beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras nods, ``If that's the way Andre says it was, fine. I
don't remember, but we've been playing each other ever since. He's
the best returner in the business, maybe the best ever. Andre is
one guy who takes my serve away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi recalls, ``Our first meeting as pros (1989) I beat him
one-and-one in Rome (it was 6-2, 6-1), and he really sucked.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras's memory coincides: ``I did suck. I was just struggling
in Europe to break even and didn't know what I was doing on clay.''
</P>
<P>
   That launched a feud that was supposed to be the greatest since
the Montagues and the Capulets. But after Sampras beat Agassi in
four for the US Open title of 1995, you began to wonder if Pete
weren't the apothecary, mixing a potion fatal to Andre's career.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras feels, ``That seemed to take the steam out of him and
the rivalry. Andre started to go off his game. It was too bad
because we've brought out the best in each other. But I never gave
up on him. I knew he'd be back. Andre is too good. No, we're not
close, but we're not unfriendly. We respect each other.''
</P>
<P>
   They made beautiful tennis together, as well as amusing TV
commercials. ``A lot of fun, the tennis and the commercials,''
Sampras says. And now they're back together again, like old lovers
who've decided to make up and give it another try.
</P>
<P>
   Linked once more, they go at each other in racket-to-racket
combat for the 24th time (13-10, Sampras), the sixth in a major
(3-2, Sampras). But never before in a Wimbledon final. Never for
the most cherished prize of them all on this stage of tennis
stages. And never as Yankee Doodle Dandies on the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't Northridge, but the occasion still calls for fireworks.
They are just the guys to provide sky rockets, cherry bombs, and
Roman candles every time they swing. Look out, Pete. The usurper
also brings dynamite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
