<HEADLINE>
LITTLE GUYS PAY PRICE AT BOX OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It was the upset of this year and a dramatic fight in
any year.
</P>
<P>
   But  &UR; Paulie Ayala's stunning victory over  &UR; Johnny Tapia 10 days
ago won't be remembered by many people. Not many watched.
</P>
<P>
   The Ayala-Tapia drama stands in sharp contrast to the garbage
that boxing has produced lately. Thus far, 1999 has been defined by
the
 &UR; Evander Holyfield- &UR; Lennox Lewis mess. The draw, despite Lewis'
superiority, generated predictions that fights and fighters in the
smallest weight classes would suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala's unanimous decision over the once-unbeaten Tapia for the
World Boxing Association's bantamweight title is evidence of damage
done.
</P>
<P>
   Blood was spilled.
</P>
<P>
   At the box office.
</P>
<P>
   A $400,000 loss is expected on the pay-per-view television
production. Customers weren't buying at the rate promoters had
hoped. After Lewis-Holyfield, why would they? Judging for that one
has planted suspicions that the fix was in. Rob the buyers once,
but not twice.
</P>
<P>
   At the site of the fight itself, there was a scramble to fill
seats. Las Vegas' Mandalay Bay scaled back its Events Center in
anticipation of 6,000, a moderate crowd. But as the opening bell
approached, it was clear that even that was optimistic. In the end,
the hotel/casino sold $50 tickets to its employees for $4. Even at
that price, the crowd fell about 1,000 short of capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala-Tapia had none of the glitter and celebrity that has
assured a sellout for the  &UR; Oscar De La Hoya- &UR; Felix Trinidad clash
on Sept. 18. De La Hoya has become a pop idol,  &UR; Ricky Martin in
boxing gloves. He attracts 5,000 groupies to a weigh-in.
</P>
<P>
   The true test of the game's health was in a bout between
lesser-known bantamweights. Had there been a lively interest in
boxing, there would have been a bigger crowd, both at ringside and
in the television audience. &QL; 
Briefly. . .  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The final crowd count for  &UR; Michael Carbajal's victory Friday
night over  &UR; Oscar Calzada at Tucson Community Center was 3,242,
short of the original estimate of 5,000. The larger number was a
result of the noise. Tucson fans warmly welcomed Carbajal with loud
cheers, unlike the boos the Phoenix fighter often hears when
introduced in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch: Previously unbeaten junior-middleweight  &UR; Manny
 &UR; Sobral had more than his record marred in a loss to  &UR; Tony Badea in
Edmonton. He was mauled. Fifty-three stitches closed cuts on his
face. His right leg was broken. ``After I hurt my leg, I felt I was
having hallucinations,'' said Sobral, who snapped his leg when he
hit the canvas in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Junior-lightweight  &UR; Diego Corrales, a former Phoenix fighter for
west-side trainer  &UR; Willy Borchert, is in line for a mandatory shot
at the International Boxing Federation title held by
 &UR; Robert Garcia, whose possible unification bout with World Boxing
Council champ  &UR; Floyd Mayweather is snagged at the bargaining table.
Purse bidding for Corrales-Gracia is scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Butterbean vs. Has Been? Butterbean, otherwise known as  &UR; Eric
Esch, wants to fight  &UR; Mike Tyson, who is trying to shed pounds
before beginning some serious work at the Valley's former Madison
Square Garden gym for a possible bout on Oct. 2. ``Mike can only
fight four rounds, anyway,'' Butterbean said after stopping  &UR; Peter
McNeeley in 179 seconds, or just 90 seconds longer than it took
Tyson. ``I've gotten better and he's gotten worse.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's a shot fighter: New Jersey would not license
Philadelphia welterweight  &UR; Charles Young for a bout last week in
Atlantic City. A CAT scan revealed that Young has a 9-millimeter
slug embedded in his skull. &QL; 
Information for other media sources included. Norm Frauenheim can
be reached at (602) 444-8259 or norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
