<HEADLINE>
CALLING LONG-DISTANCE: D-BACKS READY TO DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Diamondbacks' accounting office is set for a
dramatic jump in the club's long-distance phone bills this month.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola Jr. has been tirelessly working
the phones, piecing together as many trade possibilities as
possible so the club's brain trust can sift through them and decide
in what direction to go.
</P>
<P>
   There appear to be five legitimate deals the Diamondbacks can
pull off. All involve acquiring major league relief help. All also
translate into the Diamondbacks having to part with one or two of
their prized minor league prospects and at least one player from
the big league roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not just asking for the moon, they want a couple of
planets also,'' Garagiola said. ``We'd be rolling the dice if we
stand pat and rolling them if we make a deal. If we do something,
it will probably be sooner rather than later. We're not looking at
the (July 31) trading deadline; we're serious about it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Any talk of dealing second-year first baseman  &UR; Travis Lee has
been eliminated, Garagiola said. The biggest obstacle is coming to
grips with dealing one of the three phenom pitchers  &UR; (Nick
Bierbrodt, John
 &UR; Patterson or  &UR; Brad Penny) as well as another minor leaguer and
someone from the big league roster for immediate bullpen help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is more about where we're left after a deal,''
Garagiola said. ``Where we are right after, a year from and even
two years from now. It's not difficult to evaluate in terms of who
we would be getting. It's harder to evaluate the other side.'' &QL; 
Dellucci shines &QL; 
It was just his ninth starting assignment in 82 games, but
outfielder &UR; David Dellucci made the most of it again. He was 2 for 4
with a career-high four RBIs Sunday afternoon, including hitting
his first home run since June 23, 1998, a span of 301 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci is batting .459 (17 for 37) with 15 runs and seven RBIs
when he starts and .250 (9 for 36) otherwise. &QL; 
Etc. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reliever  &UR; Darren Holmes, on the disabled list because of a sore
lower back, is set to receive a second anti-inflammatory injection
today. Holmes, arguably the club's most consistent reliever,
probably will not return to the active roster until July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter is contemplating the idea of carrying 12
pitchers for the first few series after the All-Star break. The
first two series are in American League ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Two Diamondbacks have been staying in their St. Louis area
homes. Outfielder  &UR; Bernard Gilkey, who was born and reared in St.
Louis, and pitcher  &UR; Andy Benes, who still has a residence in the
area from his days with the Cardinals, were allowed to stay with
their families. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
