<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM LOOKS FORWARD TO REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Before turning their attention to the Women's
World Cup championship match against China, the U.S. players are
hoping to enjoy a break from the long-distance travel and the
rigors of playing every third or fourth day.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans played in New Jersey, Chicago, Boston and
Washington, often in warm temperatures and high humidity. They have
also practiced every day they weren't traveling, and made the long
haul across the country. Now, they will remain in California,
awaiting Saturday's final at the Rose Bowl in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tournament is very physically taxing, but also
emotionally taxing,'' U.S. captain  &UR; Carla Overbeck said after
Sunday's 2-0 win over Brazil. ``We feel a real sense of
accomplishment at having come this far, but we're looking forward
to a little rest and time to recuperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the players are nursing minor injuries, along with
exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all pretty tired,'' forward  &UR; Mia Hamm said. ``But we
have five or six days to regenerate, and that's important. We
haven't reached our goal yet. Our goal is to win it all.'' Jumping
for Joy &QL; 
The Fawcetts were overflowing at a San Jose hotel Sunday morning,
but there was no cause for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 of U.S. team defender  &UR; Joy Fawcett's friends and
family members made the trip from Southern California to see the
Huntington Beach native play in the semifinal match.
</P>
<P>
   Her fans at the hotel were all dressed in replica U.S. team
jerseys, with her number, 14, and ``Fawcett'' on the back. They
also wore caps with ``Fawcett's Fanatics'' written above the bill. &QL; 
Pre-game festivities &QL; 
The scene outside Stanford Stadium was decidedly different from
what it was for the 1994 men's World Cup, when Brazilian fans
virtually took over the city. They were singing in the streets and
partying in the parking lots, while outnumbering the oppositions'
fans, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the crowd was overwhelmingly pro-American. Red, white
and blue was everywhere on the Fourth of July, and thousands
partook in the American tradition of tailgating in the parking
lots. &QL; 
Corner kicks &QL; 
The Brazilians lost the semifinal match to the United States, but
team members did not go home empty-handed. Before their
quarterfinal match against Nigeria, the Brazilians spent a day
shopping in the Georgetown area of Washington. According to a Cup
official, some players spent more than $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a home-field advantage. Seven of the 20 U.S. team
players are from California, including  &UR; Julie Foudy, who attended
Stanford.  &UR; Brandi Chastain, who grew up in nearby San Jose, was
honored before Sunday's match for making her 100th international
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The United States entered the semifinal with no yellow cards,
the only team in the tournament not to receive a warning from the
referees. They remained card-free until the 90th minute of Sunday's
match, when  &UR; Michelle Akers was cautioned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
