<SLUG> BC-R-MEXICO-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTENTIOUS MEXICAN ELECTION SEEN AS WARM-UP FOR PRESIDENTIAL
VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add art advisory.)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Charges of vote-buying, polling place
electioneering and other questionable practices, mainly by the
governing party, marred the balloting for governor in the state of
Mexico Sunday, in an election that amounts to a dress rehearsal for
a watershed presidential vote next year.
</P>
<P>
   The race is a tight heat between Arturo Montiel Rojas, 55, the
candidate of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or
PRI, and Jose Luis Duran Reveles, 38, the candidate from the
right-of-center National Action Party. A third candidate, from the
left-of-center Party of the Democratic Revolution, was lagging far
behind in recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   The election is being watched all over Mexico because the
breakdown of the parties' membership in the state of Mexico, the
most populous with 7.1 million registered voters, mirrors the
political configuration of the country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are showing the way to the 2000 election,'' Maria Yolanda
Mejia Dominguez, a retired primary school teacher, said with pride
as she cast her vote Sunday in the state of Mexico's capital,
Toluca. The presidential race will be the most open and competitive
in Mexico's modern history.
</P>
<P>
   In another governor's race Sunday, in the western coastal state
of Nayarit, an unusually broad coalition of four opposition
parties, including the Democratic Revolution and National Action
parties, came together to face the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   The two elections will tell the opposition parties much about
whether one of them can win the presidency alone, or whether they
have to forge an alliance next year in order to beat the governing
party, which has won every presidential election in seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   Results from an exit poll by the Televisa network indicated that
the opposition coalition in Nayarit won with 54 percent of the
vote, to 44 percent for the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   In the state of Mexico, reports of questionable, if not illegal,
election day conduct by the governing party poured in to radio
stations and opposition party monitoring stations all day.
</P>
<P>
   In the huge township of Cuautitlan Izcalli, callers to a popular
radio station reported that governing party members had arrived at
one polling place with a suitcase full of cash and handed out about
$10 to some voters as they emerged from the polls. When opposition
poll watchers protested, they were told that the party members were
not giving out money but were taking up a collection for the local
Catholic charity.
</P>
<P>
   In a neighborhood of Ecatepec, a sprawling urban township with
more than 900,000 voters, governing party followers who were
assembled near a polling place worked a telephone list printed by
the local government, which is controlled by the party, of
residents on a street it had paved in the past few days. The party
members reminded the residents of the new asphalt and told them to
go vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multiply this by an order of 400, and you have what's going on
in Ecatepec today,'' said Jose Luis Gutierrez Cureno, a federal
congressman from the Party of the Democratic Revolution who was
monitoring the election in the township.
</P>
<P>
   In another Ecatepec precinct, the governing party organized a
rodeo in an empty lot next to a polling place, also offering voters
a free beer before they cast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   In Naucalpan, where Duran, the National Action candidate, had
been the mayor, workers from the local telephone company, Telmex,
arrived Saturday evening with orders to change all the telephone
lines for the the party's elections headquarters, where it had its
vote-counting computers.
</P>
<P>
   After protests from party leaders, the telephone workers got the
lines running, but they all had new telephone numbers, ones that
were not known to party workers spread out across the state.
</P>
<P>
   In Chimalhuacan and Zumpango, two other large state of Mexico
townships, governing party workers handed out vouchers to some
voters as they left the polls, so they could collect bags of
cement, roofing materials and food. The National Action Party
complained that the governing party paid about $20 to some people
National Action had lined up as poll watchers so they would switch
parties.
</P>
<P>
   The governing party also complained of irregularities. In
Toluca, the state capital, a National Action worker, Jesus
Alcantara, was detained by governing party poll watchers, who said
he was carrying a package, known in Mexican elections jargon as a
``taco,'' of ballots marked for his party.
</P>
<P>
   The clumsily shaped state of Mexico, draped around three sides
of the federal district of Mexico City, reflects the population and
economic makeup of the country. Teeming suburbs cluster at the
capital city's edge, built around an industrial belt. Yet much of
the state's income still comes from one-acre farms in inhospitable
sierras in the western part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   In recent elections, the governing party has won about 38 per
cent of the vote, having lost about half of its voters since its
peak strength in the 1987 election for governor. National Action
has won at least 34 per cent of the vote, but several polls
indicated that it has battled the governing party to a tie in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Party of the Democratic Revolution, whose candidate is
Higinio Martinez Miranda, 43, suffered an embarrassing decline
during the campaign. It was largely because of negative fallout
from a vote in March for party president, which was annulled
because of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Mexico election, in which the three main candidates
laid out $23 million among them, is also a bellwether for the
lavish spending expected in the presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Nayarit, with 547,000 registered voters, has long been dominated
by the governing party. But the four opposition parties in the
coalition set aside their quarrels to back a candidate who had
recently defected from the governing party because it did not
nominate him for governor. The candidate, Antonio Echevarria
Dominguez, is a Coca-Cola bottling magnate who owns the bullring in
the state capital and was a veteran governing party ward healer.
</P>
<P>
   He is running against Jose Lucas Vallarta Robles, 67, also an
old-time governing party boss, but who is seen as having less vigor
than his opponent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-99 2218EDT &QL; 
