<SLUG> BC-SOC-USSOCCER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN REACH FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Briana Scurry knew the day would come when
she had to rescue this American team. She had seen too many
breakdowns and lapses since this Women's World Cup started to think
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   And with the U.S. at it again Sunday, continually allowing
Brazil to sneak behind the back line and create dangerous
opportunities, there was Scurry, having the game of her life,
turning away shot after shot _ one theatrical save after another in
front of a wild Indepedance Day crowd of 73,123 at Stanford
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, an 80th minute Michelle Akers penalty kick dashed
any last Brazilian hopes _ allowing the U.S. to breathe a sigh of
relief following a tougher than expected 2-0 semifinal victory _
earning the U.S. a date with China Saturday at the Rose Bowl for
the championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese routed Norway, 5-0, in the other semifinal at
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, U.S. coach Tony DiCicco talked about his team's
defense and particularly the play of Scurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really had to play a lot of defense today, said DiCicco.
``We really worked on trying to eliminate space for Sissi
(Brazilian midfielder) but when they were able to get in on us,
Briana Scurry was awesome tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that she could become the best goalkeeper
in the world and I think she's proving she is the best keeper in
this World Cup. She came up with some great saves and surely that
was a calming and securing affect for this team.
</P>
<P>
   All through the tournament, the U.S. has been able to dominate
possession and outshoot its opponent. That didn't happen Sunday as
Brazil out-fired the U.S., 13-10, using its speed and pinpoint
accurate passes to spread the U.S. defense.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's Pretinha fired two deadly shots at Scurry and almost
chipped another over her shoulder in the second half, but each time
Scurry threw her body at the wind, deflecting shots away from the
goal.
</P>
<P>
   With the U.S. up 2-0 late, Pretinha had another easy chance in
the 83rd minute, but again, Scurry slapped her shot wide from
10-yards out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were breakdown's in the defense today, Bri just came
up huge and saved us, said Mia Hamm. ``That one save she made at
the end, just spectacular. I just kept telling her thank God you're
on our team.
</P>
<P>
   Even Scurry admitted she couldn't remember a better game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotta be the best game I've ever played, she said. ``I've
had many good games, but I think today was my best effort in five
years with this team.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the game ended, the entire U.S. team piled on Scurry,
each one afterward praising her efforts, particularly defender
Carla Overbeck.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been in the game a long time, she's a warrior, said
Overbeck. ``She is extremely athletic, she's very dependable, and
just knowing that, we as defenders are going to make mistakes
sometimes. But knowing that Bri's behind us makes all the
difference in the world because she's the best keeper out there.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. was lucky _ very lucky to walk off after 45 minutes
with a 1-0 lead _ a contrast to previous games where they have
given up early goals because of defensive lapses.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was Brazil who made the early mistake. U.S.
midfielder Julie Foudy sent an innocent cross from the left side.
Brazilian keeper Maravilha stepped in front, but instead of pulling
it down, she tried to tip the ball back to herself. Before she
could gather it, 5-foot-11 striker Cindy Parlow was close enough to
get her head on it first, giving the U.S. a 1-0 lead in the fifth
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been coming out so slow, so I said what ever you've been
doing at the beginning of games do something different, said
DiCicco. ``We came out and got the goal early on and that set the
tone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, until Akers' late goal, there was a lot of concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure there was, any mistake in the back against a good team
like Brazil and it's tied up, said Overbeck. ``We were fortunate to
get that early goal because we've had our share of bad luck early
in games. With the crowd noise it's difficult to hear and that
might have affected them today.
</P>
<P>
   Next up is China, a team that has beaten the U.S. twice in the
past year. Before he starts thinking of the Chinese, though,
DiCicco talked about how difficult it was for the U.S. to avoid
disaster with all of the high expectations placed on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one reason why we played a bit nervous during the
tournament, said DiCicco. ``Getting hear was no easy chore. I
thought our group was more difficult than people thought. Obviously
the quarterfinal and semifinal were against teams capable of
winning the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we're through all that. We're going to sit back, get
some needed rest and prepare for the final.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-99 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990704.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9201 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-REDS-HNS &LR;      07-04 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-REDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CINCINNATI _ Forget the movies. The National League Central race is
shaping up to be the summer's blockbuster hit.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the Astros, there was no shortage of nominees for best
performance in a supporting role in Sunday's 5-3 victory over the
Cincinnati Reds before a Fourth of July crowd of 22,023 at Cinergy
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds withstood temperatures that reached 150 degrees
on the artificial turf to become the Astros' third double-digit
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Powell escaped two jams in relief _ the latter with the
tying runs on base in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Billy Wagner pitched two innings for only the fifth time
this season to record his 20th save in 21 chances.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett made an adjustment at the plate and responded with
a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great game to win, a great game to survive,'' Wagner
said after the Astros moved within percentage points of the
first-place Reds in the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   A day after suffering a 10-0 defeat, their most lopsided in
three years, the Astros rode a solid performance by the bullpen and
home runs from Everett and Derek Bell to win for the second time in
three days against the Reds. The teams will complete the four-game
series this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be back and forth,'' Astros interim manager Matt
Galante said. ``We talked in spring training how we thought this
was going to be a tough division. We've always said this was not a
cakewalk for us. We knew it was going to be a tough year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros built a four-run lead and never trailed on one of the
hottest afternoons in Cincinnati in the last two years. Officially,
the temperature was 92 degrees at game time, but the artificial
playing surface felt like an oven. A digital thermometer placed on
one of the on-deck circles 15 minutes before the first pitch read
150 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds (10-6), who has fared miserably against the Reds
throughout his career, allowed three runs and did not walk a batter
in 5 innings, joining Jose Lima (11-4) and Mike Hampton (10-3) as
double-digit winners among Astros starters. He helped his cause
immensely by inducing two crucial double-play grounders and also
had an RBI groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, now 2-8 in 18 career appearances against the Reds,
surrendered a two-run homer to Aaron Boone that hit the left-field
foul screen in the fifth and exited with one out in the sixth after
allowing consecutive hits to Greg Vaughn and Barry Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time your starter gets into the sixth inning in heat like
this, it's nice to pick him up and get Shane the win,'' Powell
said. ``I've said all along you get more gratification getting out
of that kind of situation and getting your starter a win more than
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Powell did. He entered the game with one out
in the sixth and the Astros clinging to a 4-2 lead with runners at
second and third. Eddie Taubensee hit a sacrifice fly to cut the
margin to a run, but Powell ended the inning with a called third
strike on Mike Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ever-pesky Reds, who swept a four-game series at the
Astrodome the previous weekend, again had two runners on with two
out in the seventh inning. This time, Powell waged a seven-pitch
battle with Sean Casey, the NL's second-leading hitter, before
coaxing him into a groundout to third. Moments before, Casey hit a
screaming foul down the left-field line that came within inches of
tying the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's some of the most fun I've had in baseball,'' said
Powell, who has a 0.80 ERA over his last 11 appearances, covering
11 innings. ``I guess if he would have hit it over the wall, it
wouldn't have ended up fun. Everything I was throwing, he was
fouling off. When he hit the ball down the left-field line and it
went foul, I thought, `Maybe the breaks are changing in our
favor.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took a 2-0 third-inning lead when Everett, a switch
hitter who normally bats righthanded against an opposing
lefthander, chose to hit from the left side against Steve Avery
(5-7). The move paid off as Everett hit his 11th home run, pulling
a 2-1 curveball to right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt more comfortable batting lefthanded against him,'' said
Everett, who has three hits in 14 career at-bats against Avery.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros added to their lead in the fourth. Ricky Gutierrez
tripled to lead off the inning and slid around catcher Taubensee on
Reynolds' groundout. In the fifth, Bell crushed a ball to
straightaway center field for his 10th home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we talked about _ guys stepping up,'' Galante
said.
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros' pitching staff thinned because of injuries,
Galante stretched his relievers Sunday, with Wagner pitching the
final two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner ended the game with a strikeout of Pokey Reese,
registering 98, 98, 99, 99 and 100 mph on the radar gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matty asked me, `Can you do it?''' Wagner said. ``I told him,
`Don't ask me if I can do it; just put me out there.' That's the
way our whole team is. Don't ask us how we feel. Just put us out
there, and we'll give you everything we've got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
