<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA ANGRY AFTER NATO BANS TROOPS FROM KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A NATO delegation rushed to Moscow Sunday as Russian
officials reacted angrily to the Western alliance's refusal to
allow Moscow to send more of its peacekeeping troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As new strains appeared in the alliance's already tense
relationship with Moscow, Russian and Western military officials
began talks Sunday night aimed at resolving differences over
Russia's role in the Kosovo peacekeeping force, Russian and US
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO's request, Hungary, Romania, and Bulgaria refused to
grant permission for two Russian military transport planes carrying
equipment and 100 paratroopers to enter their airspace on Saturday
and continued the ban Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials Sunday described the action as a
``provocation on the part of the United States,'' the news agency
Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
   US officials say NATO wants the details of Russia's role to be
resolved before 3,600 Russian troops can join several hundred of
their countrymen who arrived unexpectedly on June 12 and occupied
the airport in Kosovo's capital Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main issues are already agreed, but there are many
technical details,'' US Ambassador James Collins, attending an
Independence Day barbecue for Americans living in Moscow, told
Russia's NTV television.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate incident that highlighted the chilly relations
between the two nations, US officials said an American diplomat had
been expelled from Moscow on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   US officials say Moscow has sought revisions to a deal on the
peacekeeping force signed by NATO and Russia in Helsinki last month
by demanding that Russian forces report only to their own
commanders and not to NATO. Russia has always maintained that its
forces would not be under formal NATO command. Interfax quoted the
Russian military officials as saying all the details had been
worked out in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's relations with the United States and NATO are at a
post-Cold War low. Moscow angrily protested when NATO, without
United Nations approval, launched 11 weeks of air strikes against
Yugoslavia _ which Russia sees not only as an ally, but also as
territory well within Moscow's sphere of influence.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the bombing, Moscow has been increasingly suspicious
of NATO's expansion to include former Soviet-bloc countries such as
Hungary. Sunday, Interfax quoted an unnamed Russian diplomat as
saying Moscow felt ``surprise and regret'' at Hungary's involvement
in efforts to block Russian peacekeeping troops for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has twice given NATO cause to feel shock and surprise in
recent weeks, first by rushing into Pristina ahead of NATO troops
in June and last week forcing alliance fighters to scramble as
Russian strategic bombers flew close to Norway and Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he did not know how long the negotiations in Moscow
would go on, but the Russians clearly want to move their troops as
soon as possible. Ten flights of troops and equipment were supposed
to begin Saturday and a Russian military official said the planes
would begin flying Monday.
</P>
<P>
   US officials say the Russians will not be allowed into Kosovo
until the differences are worked out. Moscow has also begun sending
troops by rail to the Black Sea, where four naval transport
carriers are due to take them to Yugoslavia this week.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Kosovo crisis, Russia has had to balance its
anger over what it perceives as the NATO's arrogance against the
need to maintain good economic relations with the West. Russia's
apparent helplessness is a source of humiliation for policymakers
and citizens alike, especially when former allies are seen to be
aiding NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin held talks with
President Leonid Kuchma of Ukraine, which at one juncture during
the crisis had also refused to allow Russian military planes to fly
over its territory at NATO's request.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin also sent a goodwill message to President Clinton to
mark US Independence Day. He said the Kosovo crisis had shown the
need for Moscow and Washington to work more closely to resolve
international disputes.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments relating to Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   --Zoran Djindjic, leader of Serbia's opposition Democratic
Party, returned to Belgrade Sunday and promised to fight for the
democratization of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   He was greeted by a cheering crowd of up to 300 people at
Belgrade airport, newly reopened after 11 weeks of NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Police made no attempt to arrest him even though a military
prosecutor has ordered an investigation against him for avoiding an
army call-up during NATO's air war on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   --In the small Kosovar village of Rodesh, truckloads of Gypsies
abandoned their homes for fear of revenge attacks by ethnic
Albanians and fled to Montenegro under the protection of Spanish
soldiers over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Many wept and expressed remorse for the actions of some of their
fellow villagers, accused of collaborating with Serb forces in
committing atrocities against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo before and
during NATO's 11-week bombing campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   --Yugoslav army reservists who blocked roads in central Serbia
for a day and a half ended their protest at the weekend after the
authorities agreed to pay them for serving during NATO bombing,
Beta news agency reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
