<SLUG> BC-NY-HEAT-805&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 RITE OF SUMMER PASSES, BUT HEAT WAVE SETTLES IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The midafternoon sun burned like a magnifying glass
in the sky. Heat waves scalded the unprotected face, pavements
turned igneous and reality withered into Saharan mirages. But on a
sweltering Fourth of July, people across the Northeast turned out
gamely for parades, picnics and fireworks and flocked to beaches,
parks and other retreats to escape an old-time scorcher.
</P>
<P>
   Held down by overcast skies that grumbled and wept in the
morning and early afternoon, temperatures rose only into the mid to
high 90s across most of the Northeast and along the mid-Atlantic
seaboard, but fell short of Independence Day records and of
forecasts that had warned of something even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi. It's hot! Goodbye,'' quipped George McKillop, a
meteorologist with the National Weather Service on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   How hot was it? The weather service recorded 95 degrees at
Kennedy International Airport and 96 in Central Park; 98 in Newark,
N.J., Philadelphia and Washington; 92 in Hartford, Conn., and 91 in
Albany. The heat index, a temperature and humidity formula, made it
feel like 105 to 110 degrees over much of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McKillop and other forecasters said that Sunday was only
the first and least dire of what is expected to be a three-day heat
wave topping out around 100 degrees on both Monday and Tuesday.
Those marks would eclipse 98-degree records for the dates _ for
July 5 in 1955, and for July 6 in 1986. The heat index would rise
to a furnacelike 110 to 115, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about as bad as it gets,'' Todd Miner, a meteorologist
with Pennsylvania State University, said of the week's forecasts
for the New York region. ``It will be muggy and quite hot until the
end of the week. There could be some relief on Wednesday, but from
now through next Saturday I would give it a 50-50 chance of being
the hottest week of the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, the heat and the holiday weekend, extending officially
through Monday, were reason enough to stay inside air-conditioned
homes, venturing out only to air-conditioned cars or
air-conditioned movie theaters during the day, and after sunset out
into the galactic night for great cascades of fireworks above the
East River and in communities across the region.
</P>
<P>
   But the lure of thundering breakers and rapturous sea breezes
brought large crowds out to the beaches of Long Island, New Jersey
and Connecticut, and many could not resist backyard barbecues,
picnics in the parks, baseball games and, in towns large and small,
old-fashioned Fourth of July parades.
</P>
<P>
   The largest parade in New York City unfolded in a neighborhood
called Travis, on Staten Island, where Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
Borough President Guy Molinari and other public officials joined
400 marchers and several thousand spectators in a singing,
flag-waving display of American pride.
</P>
<P>
   It was just across the harbor from Manhattan, but it seemed like
a small town in Kansas or Illinois. The bands played John Philip
Sousa, crowds sang ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' and recited the
Pledge of Allegiance; men and women lined the route, some watching
from their porches, and Norman Rockwell kids sat at the curb,
waving the Stars and Stripes and licking ice cream cones.
</P>
<P>
   The 89th Annual Travis Fourth of July Parade _ billed as the
``oldest continuous'' such parade in the country _ featured high
school, community and police marching bands, fire engines, mothers
and children dressed as Statues of Liberty in greenish robes and
foam crowns, and an Uncle Sam on stilts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy Fourth of July, happy Independence Day,'' the mayor,
looking cool in sunglasses and polo shirt, said from a stage.
``This is a wonderful day to remember the history of our country,
the beginning of it, our freedom, our independence.'' There were
spontaneous shouts of support for the mayor's anticipated Senate
race next year and cries of derision for Hillary Rodham Clinton,
his likely opponent.
</P>
<P>
   At Coney Island, another Fourth of July ritual was taking place
_ Nathan's Famous hot-dog eating contest. As a crowd wavering
between nausea and fascination watched for 12 minutes, Steve
Keiner, 50, of Egg Harbor Township, N.J., downed 20\ hot dogs to
defeat the reigning Hirofumi Nakajima, a 134-pound former
noodle-eating champ from Japan, who managed only 19 franks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tears of joy in Coney Island,'' George Shea, a
public relations man who gave a running commentary, told The
Associated Press when it was all over and the trophy, a
mustard-yellow weight lifter's belt, was safe on Keiner's 317-pound
girth. ``The belt is back in America!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the Zen approach,'' Keiner explained. ``I went down a
path that the hot dog was one with me, and I was one with the
universe.'' As the cheers went up and the flash bulbs popped, he
added, ``Can I get some french fries now?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thousands lined the sun-drenched beaches of Long Island's South
Shore and the New Jersey Shore on Sunday. And in Cape May, N.J.,
the holiday celebrators included some wedding parties who found
transportation in the air-conditioned vehicles of Great American
Trolley Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Thomas, a trolley driver, said the bridal parties hardly
worked up a sweat in the heat. ``The brides are excited about
getting married, and nervous. They never complain. They're not
thinking about the heat. I pick them up at home. The trolley is
air-conditioned. The church is air-conditioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists also took refuge in the air-conditioned comfort of
Hawaiian Jewelry and Gifts, a shop in the Historic Towne of
Smithville in Galloway Township, N.J., operated by Jon Mason, who
moved from Hawaii two years ago. ``We had a different kind of heat
in Hawaii,'' he said. ``It could be 85 degrees and breezy. We never
had this humidity.''
</P>
<P>
   In Battery Park, a long line of tourists stood in the heat for
the ferry to the Statue of Liberty. Some whiled away the minutes by
studying other people in the park: a homeless man lunching on hot
dogs and Poland Spring water, and a very polite park cleaner who
was willing to answer a few questions.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a busy day for him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he hot in his uniform?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he looking forward to going home?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   Another park employee spoke almost wistfully about going home,
having ``a few cold ones,'' and watching the fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   At Yankee Stadium, the heat got to be too much for the home
plate umpire, Greg Kosc, who left the game between the Yankees and
the Baltimore Orioles in the seventh inning, sweating profusely.
</P>
<P>
   Grover R. Cleveland, who said he was the great-great nephew of
the 22nd and 24th president of the United States, was also working
Sunday. A telephone cable splicer for Bell Atlantic, he was with a
crew standing around a manhole at 109th Street and Broadway,
working not very hard at replacing a copper cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love working on the Fourth of July because I make a lot of
money,'' Cleveland said. He said he was not affected much by the
heat. ``When you work outside,'' he said, ``you have to deal with
the elements, the heat and the cold. Business doesn't stop. I just
drink a lot of water.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
