</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-MARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOYALISTS STAGE PEACEFUL PROTEST INSTEAD OF MARCH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ In a change in tactics, a
Protestant fraternal organization staged a token, peaceful protest
Sunday against a British government ban prohibiting the group from
marching through a Catholic neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In dramatic contrast to last year, when tens of thousands of
Orangemen and their supporters massed in a field at Drumcree Church
to loudly and violently protest the blocking of their annual parade
down the Garvaghy Road, only about 3,000 people turned out Sunday.
By Sunday night, all but a few hundred had gone home.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Orange Order acknowledged that they had gone out
of their way to keep the crowds down and violent loyalists away,
part of a strategy to persuade the British government to lift the
ban. British Prime Minister Tony Blair has hinted that Orangemen
will be rewarded if this year's protest passes off peacefully,
perhaps with a lifting of the ban so the parade can proceed down
the Garvaghy Road later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen commemorate 17th century Protestant victories over
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few isolated incidents of violence. On
Saturday night, a loyalist used a flagpole to hit a Boston woman
who had come here as one of the hundreds of international
observers. Shannon Eaton was treated for a head wound and a broken
wrist. Eaton said one of the men who attacked her was wearing an
orange sash, a symbol of the fraternal order.
</P>
<P>
   While Orangemen remained defiant, their protest Sunday was far
more restrained than last year's, which touched off violence across
Northern Ireland and ended abruptly a week later when three
Catholic boys were burned to death after loyalists firebombed their
home. Last year, violence flared nightly as loyalists fired at
police and British soldiers blocking their path. One police officer
was killed and dozens injured.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fifth consecutive year that there has been a
confrontation over the march from Drumcree Church, and the second
consecutive year the march has been banned from the Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic nationalists on the Garvaghy Road say the parade is
triumphalist and insulting. Protestant unionists, however, say the
parade has followed the same route for nearly 200 years and that
banning it proves that their civil rights are being trampled to
appease nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Flanagan, chief of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, praised
the restraint shown by both sides. But he said the intense security
will remain for at least several days.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the toning down of the protest, the police and British
Army maintained a heavy presence, barring the Orangemen's path with
a 15-foot high metal barrier topped with razor wire. Sunday
afternoon, a teenager braved a moat and delicately picked his way
through barbed wire to plant a loyalist flag before returning to
the Drumcree side of no man's land to cheers from protestors.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's protest, and the response of police, were carefully
choreographed. After a service at Drumcree Church, six leading
Orangemen, including Harold Gracey, the local Orange Order leader,
marched to the metal barrier barring their way and spoke to a
senior police officer who crossed over to the marchers' side to
hear their complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing bowler hats, white gloves, orange sashes over their best
suits, and carrying umbrellas, the six Orangemen lodged a formal
protest against the ban, demanded an explanation for it, then
turned around and walked back to the church. The police officer
went back through a side flap to the metal barrier, which was then
welded shut.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gracey acknowledged ``we decided to change tack'' in
scaling back the protest. But Gracey, who has spent much of the
past year in a small trailer at the church, remained defiant,
saying he would remain at Drumcree ``until we are allowed to
march.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm entitled to walk any road without asking anyone's
permission,'' he said. ``The problem is not at Drumcree. The
problem is on the Garvaghy Road.''
</P>
<P>
   While denying that the Orange Order could be held responsible
for those who caused violence last year, Gracey said he would leave
if the protest turned violent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Garvaghy Road, the residents' group leader, Breandan
MacCionnaith, welcomed the scaled-down protest, but said it was
time for the Orangemen to meet with residents and work out a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Gracey, however, said he would never talk to MacCionnaith, who
served a prison sentence for the IRA bombing of the local British
army veterans hall.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the field that was covered with tents last year was
empty. Even protesters who said they intended to come here daily
until the ban is lifted said they would commute rather than camp
out.
</P>
<P>
   Bill McCann, part of a loyalist soccer team from Belfast that
came to show its support for the local Orangemen, said ``things
will be different this year. We'll show who's really intransigent.
It's the people on the Garvaghy Road who won't let a 15-minute
march go down the road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein assembly member Dara O'Hagan, who represents the
Garvaghy Road area, said people fear that the ban will be lifted
and the parade forced down the road, as happened in 1997. ``People
are taking a wait-and-see attitude,'' O'Hagan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-99 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
