<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     07-04 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SAME SETTING, DIFFERENT RESULT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Their legs were tired, somewhere between the
consistency of tapioca pudding and muscle, the logical result of a
steamy Thursday night in Maryland and a bright Sunday afternoon in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Jet planes and time zones will do that to you. The United States
beat Brazil, 2-0, in the semifinals of the Women's World Cup on
Sunday, as players from both sides fought off sluggishness and
cramps.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell your mind to tell your legs to run,'' said Carla
Overbeck, who wears the yellow captain's band on her left arm.
</P>
<P>
   The players would not have it any other way. This was your
typical Fourth of July World Cup game at Stanford Stadium, the
second in history, following the men's 1-0 loss to Brazil exactly
five years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The American women know the long schlep is the price for a
once-in-a-lifetime World Cup, a giddy spree across this huge
continent, playing to throbbing stadiums. This is the big time, and
it may never come around again like this in their careers, and they
are enjoying every roar, every ache.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Overbeck said. ``We're bringing our game to the
whole country, not just one coast.''
</P>
<P>
   The game itself was disjointed, lacking any sense of pace or
urgency. Yes, even the Women's World Cup is allowed to settle into
a gallantly professional plateau of weary bodies and careful
tactics. Yes, even the newest American sensation, just discovered
in the past few days, can have a normal game of fits and starts.
</P>
<P>
   There were no back flips, no horizontal headers, that might show
up on the evening sports news, now that the lads back at the
stations have suddenly become conditioned to show a few snippets of
these entertaining new faces.
</P>
<P>
   The two American goals came from a relatively easy header after
a two-handed bobble by the Brazilian keeper, and a penalty kick
following a somewhat questionable call by the referee. Well, weak
goalkeeping is an affliction of the Brazilian men's team, too.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it was a typical soccer game, a typical World
Cup game, with the home team holding off the visitors, somewhat
short of producing the Greatest Game Ever Played That Led the Way
to a Women's League. The stakes are high here. They have been
raised by a barrage of publicity and exposure, charismatic
performers making the most of their shot.
</P>
<P>
   This World Cup was originally supposed be a one-coast wonder,
stretching from Landover, Md., to Foxboro, Mass., with a foray one
time zone west to Chicago. However, the American organizers dared
the world soccer body, known as FIFA, to think big.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking big produced a crowd of 73,123 fans on Sunday, under a
cloudless sky. With Brazilian flags and Brazilian T-shirts and
Brazilian drums all jiggling in the crowd, the Brazilian women
never showed the national genius for offense.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of rhythm may merely mean that women's soccer is quite
sophisticated enough to produce game plans. Coach Tony DiCicco
assigned long-maned Michelle Akers to hector close-cropped Sissi of
Brazil, and Akers negated her all day. And after watching Sissi win
the quarterfinal with a missile of a free kick, the Americans
denied her the opportunity on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coach prepared us,'' Overbeck said. ``We just knew any
time she kicked near the penalty box, she would put it in the
net.''
</P>
<P>
   All these subtle things were happening out on the field, and the
northern California fans understood. The sport-utility-vehicle
crowd cannot muster anywhere near the passion of soccer crowds
around the world, but these people knew when to applaud, if not
scream their hearts out.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks did what they had to do. As Briana Scurry, who played
her best game ever in goal for the Americans, put it: ``I knew we'd
have to knuckle down. It's hard to adjust to that flight. A massage
therapist can only do so much.''
</P>
<P>
   They will be needing some more massages after willing their
bodies to perform on Sunday. Akers took another few hard knocks,
and Mia Hamm once again was hammered, the price of fame.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm did make one gorgeous run, taking a short pass from
Kristine Lilly and feinting to the right and lunging to the left,
before losing the ball to a defender. The fans appreciated the
artistry.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the matter of the sprawling two-handed flop
performed by Hamm after some moderate jostling from Brazil's
captain, Elane. The dive was enough to draw a penalty kick, and the
Brazilian coach, Wilson Oliveira Rica, was sure that that bit of
gymnastics affected the game more than any coast-to-coast flight or
time change ever could.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the cute commercials and the fashion shoots. There
was quibbling about officials. There were welts on Akers' face. The
Women's World Cup is allowed to have them, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
