<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS CAN TAKE THE HEAT, LIGHT UP CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Diamondbacks batters were virtually running to the
batter's box, each one wanting to take his shot off whatever
sacrificial lamb St. Louis Manager Tony La Russa sent to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   It was only appropriate this game took place at Busch Stadium,
especially since the absurd 17 runs and 19 hits Arizona batters
collected seemed like they belonged in a beer league boxscore,
rather than a major league summary.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' offense busted out in a huge way for the
second time in three days, putting a severe 17-5 thumping on the
struggling Cardinals, who are perilously close to dropping into the
National League Central cellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough day out there,'' said starter Andy Benes, who
somehow fought his way through the 95 degree temperature that
seemed much worse than any Arizona heatwave when you threw in the
85 percent humidity. ``It was hot, but everybody basically deals
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some dealt with the stambath conditions better than others.
Specifically, Diamondbacks players seemed to fare far better than
their Cardinals counterparts on a tortuous St. Louis summer day.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the dragged 3-hour, 32-minute game came to its
painful end, Diamondbacks players were so zapped of their strength
the best they could manage for post-game handshakes were quiet
congtratulations to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of weather takes so much out of you,'' said third
baseman Matt Williams, who was removed from the lineup before the
bottom of the eighth inning. ``This kind of heat gets to you much
more than what we have in Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no better example of a player being hit hard by the
sticky conditions than St. Louis starter Juan Acevedo, who was
clutching his knees as early as the second inning on a pop fly to
the infield.
</P>
<P>
   That Acevedo was forced to dart to second base on a hit-and-run
situation on seven consecutive pitches in the bottom of the fourth,
only seemed to push him to the edge that much quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Several Diamondbacks players were nearly in tears from laughter
after watching Acevedo try to rev his legs up while teammate J.D.
Drew continued to foul off pitch after pitch in the sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was clinging to a 4-3 lead and needed just three
outs to become the pitcher of record for St. Louis, Acevedo lasted
just one batter into the top of the fifth, unwillingly being
removed by La Russa after allowing a leadoff single to Luis
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unbelievable day out there,'' said Gonzalez, whose
three-hit day matched David Dellucci for the club best on an
afternoon when the Diamondbacks set the franchise record for runs
in a game. ``When we saw their pitcher running sprints like that,
we knew it was going to take its toll on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci, starting for just the ninth time in 82 games, got
things rolling early when he blasted his first home runs in 13
months in the top of the first. It was the first of three home
runs, the club's first multi-homer game since June 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be eating 10 hours just to get my weight back,''
said Dellucci, who believes he lost at least nine pounds Sunday
afternoon. ``I don't get to (start) very often and I'm pleased to
come through when I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my teammates to have confidence in me when I go out
there. I'm not selfish. I look around and see guys having career
years. I'm not stupid. As long as they're doing well, they're going
to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Manager Buck Showalter: ``There will come a day when we
will find out (how Dellucci will do as a starter). The challenge
for me is to give him starts, keep him in the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes _ who has put together solid back-to-back outings now,
allowing four earned runs in his last 13 innings _ was aggressive
for nearly all of his 114 pitches. He was ahead of hitters most of
the afternoon and had them swinging at his pitches more often than
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as gutsy an effort as can see by Benes,'' Showalter
said. ``He had great body language. He wasn't bending over huffing
and puffing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
