<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVARES BEATS A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ All around him, there is chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Belcher and Ken Hill are on the disabled list, Chuck Finley
is pitching as poorly as he ever has and Steve Sparks' knuckleball
is about as reliable as a TV weatherman's forecast.
</P>
<P>
   But Omar Olivares, No.5 on the depth chart, has been the Angels'
best starting pitcher this season. Olivares gave up two runs and
five hits in a complete game Sunday, leading the Angels to a 5-2
victory over the Oakland A's before 19,721 at the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   It was Olivares' second complete game of the season, the only
two on the Angels staff this year. Olivares, who entered the game
with the sixth-best ERA in the American League, lowered his ERA to
3.27.
</P>
<P>
   It was the eighth time in 16 starts Olivares (7-6) has pitched
at least seven innings in a game. And he's the only Angels pitcher
in the last 12 games to pitch at least six innings _ and he's done
that twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pitched great for us all year,'' said Angels manager
Terry Collins. ``Without question he's been our most consistent
guy. He came into spring training and earned a spot. He didn't want
any doubts, so he came in ready to go and he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares gave up an RBI single to Eric Chavez in the fifth and a
sacrifice fly to Jason Giambi in the ninth. That was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I didn't feel that strong, but mentally I was
focused and I hit both sides of the plate,'' Olivares said.
``That's what you have to do to be successful _ location _ and I
had that today.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for a two-run homer in the ninth by Troy Glaus, Troy
Percival would have pitched the ninth. But with the lead 5-1,
instead of 3-1, Olivares got the chance to finish it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always try to throw the whole game,'' he said. ``Every time
I pitch, I'm thinking nine innings. I knew it was huge because the
bullpen has pitched a lot the last 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had 12 hits Sunday _ 39 in the three-game series _
including three by Mo Vaughn. Vaughn's RBI single in the seventh
inning broke a 1-1 tie and gave the Angels the lead for good.
Garret Anderson also had three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn went 7 for 16 with four RBI in the series, which he said
was big because he was hitless in the Texas series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept working at it,'' Vaughn said. ``I'm starting to take
good swings and hit the ball all over the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim had at least one hit in each of the first five innings _
eight in all _ but only one run to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn and Anderson singled with two out in the first, but Glaus
struck out.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got an RBI double by Randy Velarde in the third
inning but left the bases loaded when Reggie Williams struck out.
In the fourth and fifth innings, the Angels had possible
run-scoring innings thwarted by hitting into double plays.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Olivares was cruising. He didn't allow a hit through
four innings, and the only two baserunners he allowed _ two walks _
were erased on double-play grounders.
</P>
<P>
   The A's got their first hit of the day when Giambi led off the
fifth with a single to right; he took third when John Jaha followed
with a single.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares looked like he might escape, striking out Matt Stairs
and getting Ramon Hernandez on a popup to shallow right field. But
Eric Chavez got the run home with a groundball single to center,
tying the game at 1.
</P>
<P>
   The A's took starter Mike Oquist out of the game after Gary
DiSarcina's leadoff double in the seventh. Doug Jones came in and
struck out Darin Erstad but walked Velarde, bringing up Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn got his third hit of the day, a single to right, to drive
in DiSarcina for a 2-1 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had a chance for more as Velarde took third on
Vaughn's single. But Anderson popped out to third and Glaus _ after
Chad Harville replaced Jones _ struck out.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels added their third run in the eighth inning after
loading the bases on three walks. DiSarcina got the run home when
he grounded out, but the Angels again missed an opportunity to
increase the lead _ after an intentional walk to Erstad _ when
Velarde grounded into a double play.
</P>
</TEXT>
