<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-H     07-04 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
WIMBLEDON, England _ Lindsay Davenport once feared she lacked the
game, or perhaps the brain, to conquer Centre Court. She always has
been the least mobile, least athletic of the contending women, and
her confidence sagged accordingly.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wimbledon's slippery lawns forgive nothing _ but slow feet and
clumsiness tend to be punished most severely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I had the game to win here,'' the third-seeded
Davenport said Sunday after a 6-4, 7-5 victory over seven-time
champion Steffi Graf, who afterward announced her Wimbledon
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, fittingly on this Fourth of July, becomes the first
American woman since Martina Navratilova in 1984 to win Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open title Davenport claimed last year told her the
self-doubting was no longer necessary. It told her she had arrived
at the summit and that she belonged there, no questions or
apologies required. Six fortnights of grass-court futility
notwithstanding, Davenport finally was prepared to make her peace
with tennis' most sacred grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport went out Sunday and played like the No. 1-ranked
player she is, making shockingly short work of the second-seeded
German who had become an enduring symbol of Wimbledon excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, on a 7-0 roll in finals here before Sunday's, couldn't
convert either of her break points against Davenport's serve. The
23-year-old Californian achieved just two herself, but she made
them pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Those winners, a mis-hit forehand in the first game and a
forehand cross-court drive in the penultimate game, proved the
difference in a match that apparently has brought a close to Graf's
long, immensely fruitful tenure at what the English call ``The
Championships.'' Only Navratilova's nine titles exceed her
prodigious total.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be here again as a player,'' Graf, 30, said.
</P>
<P>
   She had bid Roland Garros adieu a month ago, having surprised
herself with a sixth French championship, her first major title
since reconstructive knee surgery and a wrist operation had
threatened to curtail her career. But Graf's Wimbledon farewell
would not prove to be such a celebratory occasion, as her somber
tone and red-rimmed eyes confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Given that she wouldn't guarantee her participation in the U.S.
Open this year or future Australian Opens, Graf's bid to equal
Margaret Court's record of 24 Grand Slams appears over as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' Davenport said. ``She came through so much, and
she's the greatest player, probably, that's ever played. If she's
not going to play the French or Wimbledon again, it's looking
pretty obvious that she'll retire sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think it's really, really cool that she's been able to
go out on her own. I think that's how we'd all like to end our
careers, still playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf's legacy, considering the depth of the contemporary women's
game, seems to justify calling her the best ever. She has won 22
Slams, including five U.S. and four Australian Opens, and she swept
the four majors in 1988, besides winning the Olympic gold medal,
giving her the so-called ``Golden Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   Four other times she won three legs of the Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of Court's titles came at the Australian Open during a
period when many top foreign players skipped the event. Also, 13 of
them predated the advent of Open tennis.
</P>
<P>
   But Graf was in no mood to reflect on the scope of her
accomplishments, or what her future might hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we talk about today?'' Graf said, expressing displeasure
with questions about her plans. ``I'm not going to go into anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the match, the only Wimbledon final she had dropped
since Navratilova defeated her as an 18-year-old novice in 1987,
she was unhappy with her backhand and, to a lesser degree, her
serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing because I didn't play up to the level that
I can,'' Graf said. ``Unfortunately, my backhand didn't work very
well. My forehand, I guess, played OK, but on my backhand side I
made too many unforced errors, and she served more consistently
than I did. The (break) chances I had, I didn't convert so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's confidence level going in was such that she elected
to receive after winning the racket toss. The payoff came
immediately, leaving Graf to fight from behind. Even a half-hour
rain delay with Graf leading 5-4 on serve in the second set didn't
disrupt Davenport's momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason,'' she said, ``that helped me calm down. I
just told myself, `My gosh, I'm doing so well. I'm so close. I can
do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport never had advanced beyond the quarters, and she was a
15-1 long shot according to London's bookmakers at the outset of
the tournament. To earn the right to hold the plate aloft in
triumph, Davenport delivered what Navratilova called ``a perfect
match.''
</P>
<P>
   And practically a perfect tournament.
</P>
<P>
   She rolled through the fortnight without yielding a set and
spent, on average, less than an hour on the court per round. Even
Graf kept her out there for only 117 minutes. When the last ball
was struck _ a Graf forehand return into the net _ Davenport burst
into tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God, I did,'' she said. ``I was in such shock. I was
like, `I can't believe I did it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Or, for that matter, against whom she did it. Davenport had
upset then-No. 1 Martina Hingis to win at Flushing Meadow. Now
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to win these tournaments by beating the best,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Davenport added the doubles title with Corina Morariu and
then headed happily off to the Wimbledon Ball, wearing a new dress
picked out for her only Sunday afternoon. Next year, she's likely
to come better prepared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
