<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: INDEPENDENTS' DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMAGANSETT, N.Y. _ Ready for a little political mischief on a
holiday weekend? Let us consider what could upset the seemingly
preordained Bush and Gore nominations.
</P>
<P>
   An unremarked time bomb called the Reform Party is on the ballot
in all 50 states. Based on its vote total in 1996, its presidential
candidate will receive $12.6 million in federal funds in 2000. If
Ross Perot runs again, his vote will again dwindle; if the party
chooses an ex-senator like David Boren or Sam Nunn, it would draw
equally from both major parties and have little impact.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the Reform Party, in convention assembled next year,
chose to embrace the nominee of the Republican or Democratic Party?
It would never endorse the Establishment candidates, Bush or Gore _
but what about a genuine maverick with appeal to independents, like
Republican John McCain or Democrat Bill Bradley?
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the next 12 months, the 25-point lead that Bush
now holds over Gore will surely shrink. The major parties will look
at the pull of that crucial third line, plus its federal money and
stretch-drive call on prime-time ad slots, and wonder _ wouldn't it
be great to have that independent segment count for our man?
</P>
<P>
   In New York state campaigns, it is routine for the major parties
to dicker heavily for Independence, Liberal and Conservative Party
lines on the ballot. In the Rudy-Hillary senatorial race, national
Republicans will beg Conservatives not to split New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's vote, and national Democrats will try to snatch
his Liberal line away for Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   Fusion is a New York tradition; the Conservative Party made the
difference for Ronald Reagan in 1980 and the reform party delivered
a quarter-million votes for Charles Schumer last year.
</P>
<P>
   Is such ``double access'' available to presidential candidates
elsewhere? Yes in crucial Pennsylvania and Connecticut; no in a
dozen other states; and in the remainder, it would take about $6
million (much reimbursable as primary expenses) to conduct petition
drives and lawsuits to achieve double access. The Reform Party has
proved itself adept at winning such arguments.
</P>
<P>
   What would be in it for Ross Perot? (1) A maverick-major party
name at the top would build his Reform Party in 50 states,
strengthening its lower-level independent candidacies; (2) Reform's
aim to end the corporate pork barrel and shake up the corrupting,
out-of-control politics of money is the essence of McCain's message
now and will be Bradley's later; (3) becoming a real player would
change the debate-denied Perot from a Stassen-esque joke into a
claimant to the role of Warwick, the kingmaker.
</P>
<P>
   What would it take to transform this amusing academic notion
into an unforeseen political development?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fear of losing. &LR;  If George W., in some gaffe during an
interview or primary toe-stubbing or weakness in debate, loses his
aura of inevitability; or if Al Gore is too slow to close the poll
gap and cannot dispel that ``can't win'' miasma _ loyalties would
vanish. Diehards are now die-easies; nobody wants to go down with
the Gore or Bush ship. Vast campaign treasuries won't stop a run on
the bank of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   A Kierkegaardian dread is sure to afflict whichever party's
front-runner fails to show late foot in early primaries. This could
give the reformist long shots of both parties _ McCain and Bradley
_ a new viability.
</P>
<P>
   Next February, the candidate within each major party running
second for the nomination may say to party leaders: Polls show that
our likely nominee will lead us down the road to defeat. Here's how
we can win: I can deliver the third line on ballots that can tip
the balance almost everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Pshaw, say boxed-in thinkers; unless Ross runs himself, the
Reform line won't have big money. But if Perot goes on that third
line for vice president, and Reform endorses the slate to the
Electoral College chosen by the major party candidate, then
billionaire Ross could contribute as much as he wanted to the
campaign _ and nobody need fear he would become vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something creative has to happen to American politics,'' says
Russell Verney in Dallas, chairman of the Reform Party. This is my
off-the-wall contribution, accompanied by a wish for a happy
Independents' weekend to all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
