<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-TIGER-LADY-NYT &LR;      07-04 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TIGER-LADY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIGER LADY' DEFLECTS CHARGES THAT ONE OF HERS RAN WILD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ Since the DNA fits, you would think the
tiger lady would admit, but that is not the case with Joan
Byron-Marasek, who has become known as the Tiger Lady of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   On June 28, there was the news that fur samples from the
431-pound Bengal tiger found wandering around Jackson Township and
subsequently shot to death in January matched the DNA of fur found
on the grounds of Ms. Byron-Marasek's Tigers Only Preservation
Society, a privately owned preserve.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Ms. Byron-Marase and her lawyer, Valter Must, stood
on the woodsy outer fringe of her 11-acre property _ where, OK,
they admit, a section of the mesh iron fence that circles the
property was down _ insisting, as she has all along, that the late
tiger was not hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not our tiger,'' said Ms. Byron-Marasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tuft of hair was found on a thorn tree,'' said Must, in fine
courtroom style. The New Jersey Division of Fish, Game and
Wildlife, he said, ``is arguing that because a tiger was shot a
mile from here, and they found this tuft of hair over here, that
ipso facto the tiger came from inside the container.''
</P>
<P>
   Not an unreasonable assumption.
</P>
<P>
   Where do Ms. Byron-Marasek and her lawyer believe a tiger could
have come from?
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been tigers dumped in this area,'' Ms.
Byron-Marasek said darkly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two possibilities,'' Must said. ``One: A tiger visited here.
Two: There was no tiger here, but somehow the fur got here. They
put it here to frame her.''
</P>
<P>
   There is something of a siege mentality these days at Tigers
Only, which Ms. Byron-Marasek appears to have run as a one-woman
save-the-tiger project for 23 years, with occasional help from her
husband. On Jan. 27, a 7-foot-long Bengal tiger went for a stroll
in the suburban woods of Jackson Township, setting off a chase by
foot, patrol car, and finally, as night fell, by FBI helicopters
equipped with infrared light.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in here with their guns drawn, with shotguns,'' Ms.
Byron-Marasek said. ``Fifty people in my little tiny house;
helicopters over the animals, terrifying the animals. I was just in
shock afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials counted 17 adult tigers in Ms.
Byron-Marasek's preserve, though her animal theatrical permit
listed 23. Later, records from Ms. Byron-Marasek's own
veterinarian, whose name Fish and Game has not released, indicated
that Ms. Byron-Marasek had 18 tigers in January, just before the
tiger was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Ms. Byron-Marasek's position helped by a report by Dr.
Patrick Thomas, curator of mammals at the Bronx Zoo in New York. He
called the fencing at the preserve ``inadequate'' and the sanitary
conditions ``deplorable.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, state officials turned down Ms. Byron-Marasek's
application to renew her permit and gave her 30 days to remove the
the tigers from her property. She is appealing that decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
