A9220 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LAD     07-04 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILD WILD WEST' BANGS UP BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Will Smith's ``Wild Wild West'' shot to the top at
the nation's multiplexes with an estimated $28 million at 3,342
theaters as major movies continued to set off fireworks during the
Friday-Sunday Fourth of July holiday period, studio sources said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' action comedy took in $8.5 million more than the
nearest contender, the second weekend of ``Big Daddy'' with a
still-impressive $19.5 million at 3,121 theaters. ``Wild Wild
West'' has now grossed $41.2 million in its first five days, but
that total is less than half the stratospheric $84.1 million posted
by Smith's mega-hit ``Men In Black'' during its first five days
over the July 4th weekend in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the industry were expecting `Wild Wild West' to do a
little better,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel
Source forecasting service. ``There was a lot of competition
because most of the major films are geared to people under 22.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said ``West'' will not suffer significantly from the
spate of negative reviews it received, noting that poor notices
have little impact on its core audience of younger moviegoers. He
predicted ``West'' could eventually top $150 million domestically,
which should push it into profitability despite its reported $115
million price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for ``Wild Wild West'' had been sky high because
``Men In Black'' topped $250 million and Smith's ``Independence
Day,'' which launched on the same weekend in 1996, went past $305
million. But Warner distribution chief Dan Fellman said comparisons
to Smith's other blockbusters are not entirely valid.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Wild Wild West' is a very different film from the other two,
but anytime you open like this, you have to be very pleased,'' he
said. ``Young people are responding very well, and it played well
in all markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall business totaled an impressive $126 million for
Friday-Sunday, up 12 percent from the same period last year and
down 6 percent from last weekend's turbocharged box office. Summer
season receipts have been running a stunning 27 percent ahead of
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business has been so powerful with big openings and
pictures showing strong legs,'' said industry tracker Arthur
Rockwell, who noted that ``Wild Wild West'' had a tough task due to
the pull of holdover films. ``I think `Wild Wild West' had a decent
opening due to Will Smith's star power, but it doesn't have
franchise or sequel written all over it.''
</P>
<P>
   With moviegoers off work Monday, ``West'' could take in another
$9 million and top $50 million in its first six days while Sony's
``Big Daddy'' will likely be closing in on $90 million after 11
days. Despite losing more than half its opening weekend audience,
``Big Daddy'' is on track to reach the $150 million mark by the end
of its domestic run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan'' continued to post respectable numbers in third place
with $13.1 million at 3,103 theaters as attendance fell 45 percent
from its second weekend, giving Disney's 37th animated feature $105
million overall. ``Tarzan'' is the sixth 1999 movie and 188th of
all time to top the $100 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's controversial ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and
Uncut,'' R-rated due to its foul-mouthed animated stars, performed
solidly in fourth with $11.3 million at 2,128 sites to push its
five-day total to $19.6 million. The studio will likely see massive
profits from the big-screen version of the Comedy Central series,
since the film cost a bargain-basement $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   A trio of holdovers were battling for fifth, led by Paramount's
third weekend of ``The General's Daughter'' with $10 million at
2,858 theaters, followed by 20th Century Fox's seventh weekend of
``Star Wars Episode 1: The Phantom Menace'' with $9 million at
2,631 sites and New Line's fourth weekend of ``Austin Powers: The
Spy Who Shagged Me'' with $8.9 million at 3,091 locations.
``Phantom Menace,'' which lowered its theater count by nearly 500,
is the fourth highest domestic grosser ever with $369 million while
``Shagged'' is No. 47 with $168.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's opening of ``Summer of Sam,'' Spike Lee's recounting of
the impact of the 1977 serial killer case, performed moderately in
eighth with $5.5 million at 1,536 theaters. ``That's not too
shabby, given the subject matter,'' Bucksbaum said, adding that
positive reviews helped attract the target audience of over-25
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were Universal's sixth weekend of
``Notting Hill'' with $3.7 million at 1,940 theaters and Miramax's
third weekend of ``An Ideal Husband'' with $2.6 million at 602
sites. ``Notting Hill'' is less than $4 million shy of joining the
$100 million club, signaling strong prospects for star Julia
Roberts' next film, ``Runaway Bride,'' which Paramount opens July
30.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's opening of coming-of-age comedy ``American Pie''
should post solid business next weekend and may challenge ``Wild
Wild West'' for the top spot. Sony will also open ``Arlington
Road,'' with Jeff Bridges investigating terrorists, after delaying
its original mid-May release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
