   (NYT14) JACKSON TOWNSHIP, N.J. -- July 4, 1999 -- NJ-TIGER-LADY,
7-4 -- Joan Byron-Marasek, who has become known as the Tiger Lady
of New Jersey, with one of her cubs. Ms. Byron-Marasek owns the
Tigers Only Preservation Society, an 11-acre private preserve. In
May, state officials turned down Ms. Byron-Marasek's application to
renew her permit and gave her 30 days to remove the the tigers from
her property. She is appealing that decision. (Laura Pedrick/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WESTBOROUGH, Mass. -- July 4, 1999 -- Y2K-GARTNER, 7-4
-- Louis Marcoccio leads the Gartner Group Inc.'s Year 2000
research. Gartner's year 2000 star rose rapidly after a 1996
congressional hearing when it suggested that American companies
might spend as much as $600 billion finding and dealing with
end-of-century computer flaws, making it the first prominent
information-technology firm to put a hard, eye-opening number on
the problem in a public forum. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- July 4, 1999 -- MARYGORDON-WRITERS, 7-4 --
Mary Gordon, whose novels include ``Men and Angels'' and
``Spending.'' ``Writing by hand is laborious, and that is why
typewriters were invented. But I believe that the labor has virtue,
because of its very physicality,'' says Ms. Gordon. ``For one thing
it involves flesh, blood and the thingness of pen and paper, those
anchors that remind us that, however thoroughly we lose ourselves
in the vortex of our invention, we inhabit a corporeal world.''
(Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) COMMERCE CITY, Colo. -- July 4, 1999 --
TRUCKSTOP-MAKEOVER-4, 7-4 -- At the new truck stop in Commerce
City, Colo., built by Travel Centers of America to attract
travelers as well as truckers, Gylinda Gonzales, a waitress, talks
with Neil Hope and his 6-year-old son, Jesse James Harp. For the
first time in its 80-or-so-year history, the American truck stop
has been ``re-imaged,'' as designers like to say, with nostalgic
roadside touches and the ultimate highway seducer -- neon. (Essdras
M. Suarez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 4, 1999 -- CITIZENSHIP-TEST-2, 7-4 --
Felicia Voltaire, 80, from Haiti, being sworn in by Winston Barros,
an officer of the Immigration and Naturalization Service. Critics
contend that the Immigration and Naturalization Service relies on a
process that is not uniform in content, administration or grading.
The immigration service, driven in part by the unwieldy backlog of
applications that has overwhelmed the naturalization process, has
now started looking at ways to make the citizenship test more
uniform. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 4, 1999 -- CITIZENSHIP-TEST-1, 7-4 --
Russian-speaking immigrants taking a course at Bronx House, a
Jewish community center, to prepare for the federal citizenship
test. Critics say the Immigration and Naturalization Service relies
on a process that is not uniform in content, administration or
grading. The immigration service, driven in part by the unwieldy
backlog of applications that has overwhelmed the naturalization
process, has now started looking at ways to make the citizenship
test more uniform. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PINE RIDGE RESERVATION, S.D. -- July 4, 1999 --
ADOPT-A-GRANDPARENT, 7-4 -- Oglala Sioux tribal elders Rebecca
Yellow Hair, right, and Emma Waters, who is sponsored by the
Adopt-a-Grandparent Program, sing a traditional song at a Fourth of
July weekend powwow. The Adopt-a-Grandparent Program, which was
started in 1987 by a freelance photojournalist, Gail Russell, helps
Native American elders who live on reservations and are at least 60
years old or disabled. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) AUSTIN, Texas -- July 4, 1999 -- BUSH-EVANS, 7-4 --
Donald L. Evans, 53, chief fund-raiser for Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas. Evans, during an economic boom, has collected checks from
75,000 of the United States' most prosperous citizens, on behalf of
a charmer with a well-known name who is considered the Republican
savior. ``This is the easiest fund raising I've ever done in my
life,'' says Evans. (Bryce Harper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BELGRADE, Yugoslavia -- July 4, 1999 --
YUGOSLAVIA-BIRTHRATE, 7-4 -- Vesna Markovic, a 27-year-old
economist who works at an electric utility, in front of her
apartment building with her son Dusan, 8. Mrs. Markovic has
resisted her parents' pleas that she have more children. In postwar
Belgrade, she is finding it a daily struggle to provide for even
one child. ``We have all become poorer and it is not good to raise
children like this,'' says Mrs. Markovic. (Ivan Milutinovic/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) COMMERCE CITY, Colo. -- July 4, 1999 --
TRUCKSTOP-MAKEOVER-3, 7-4 -- Complete with a business center and a
drop-off laundry, a new Travel Centers of America truck stop in
Commerce City, just northeast of Denver. An Ohio-based company,
Travel Centers of America, the largest full-service truck stop
company in the country, now affords motorists and truckers the
opportunity to visit a massage therapist, see a chiropractor, get a
manicure or even surf the web. (Essdras M. Suarez/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) COMMERCE CITY, Colo. -- July 4, 1999 --
TRUCKSTOP-MAKEOVER-2, 7-4 -- Complete with a 40-seat movie theater,
a new Travel Centers of America truck stop in Commerce City, just
northeast of Denver. An Ohio-based company, Travel Centers of
America, the largest full-service truck stop company in the
country, now affords motorists and truckers the opportunity to
visit a massage therapist, see a chiropractor, get a manicure or
even surf the web. (Essdras M. Suarez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) COMMERCE CITY, Colo. -- July 4, 1999 --
TRUCKSTOP-MAKEOVER-1, 7-4 -- The new truck stop in Commerce City,
built by Travel Centers of America. In a design trend as yet
unheralded by Architectural Digest, the American truck stop has
been ``re-imaged,'' endowed with architectural fireworks: ribbed
aluminum (a nod to the American diner), a huge striped awning (the
traditional sign of welcome) and the ultimate highway seducer --
neon. (Essdras M. Suarez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
