<DOCNO> NYT19990704.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-HNS     07-04 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
WIMBLEDON, England _ He knew what people were saying. The stuff
about his mediocre results of late, his questionable fitness, his
good fortune in the quarterfinals, when Mark Philippoussis, who was
pummeling him, up and quit with an injury.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indeed, it had become hip and trendy to predict top seed Pete
Sampras' demise on the grass court he had come to call his own,
particularly with that old fire back in Andre Agassi's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday proved a bad day for the doom prophets. The world
didn't come to an end _ take that, Nostradamus _ and neither did
Sampras' now-record reign at Wimbledon. Take that, Andre.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' Fourth of July rockets practically set Agassi's baggy
britches ablaze in a final that was as un-American as it was
all-American. There was nothing patriotic, much less benevolent,
about the under-two-hour 6-3, 6-4, 7-5 Pistol-whipping Pete gave
his popular countryman. The only flag the fourth-seeded Agassi
waved when he left the greensward was white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to give Pete full credit for the way he played,''
Agassi said. ``He played some impeccable tennis at the most
important times.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was even good enough to amaze himself, no trivial feat
when you have been top-ranked in the world six years running,
prevailed at Wimbledon six times in seven summers and pulled into a
tie with Roy Emerson in the race for the most Grand Slam titles.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has 12, too, and because he's 27, it's probably going to
require the end of the world to prevent him from leaving Emerson _
and everyone else _ eating his dust. His six Wimbledon titles are
the most by anyone in the 20th century, and his match record here
since a semifinal loss to Goran Ivanisevic in 1992 is 46-1. Richard
Krajicek beat him in the quarters en route to the title in '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete's achievements speak for themselves,'' Agassi said.
``Pete's accomplished more than anybody else, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   A stubborn sort, though, the French Open champ who is one of
only five men to own a career Grand Slam added: ``I still expect
myself to beat him. I'm obviously looking forward to the U.S. Open.
We've had three Grand Slams and three different winners. Who's No.
1? The U.S. Open will tell that.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering how swimmingly Agassi had come through in Paris,
completing the aforementioned sweep of the Slams at Roland Garros,
and how brutally he had dismissed the two-time defending U.S. Open
champ, Patrick Rafter, a day earlier in the semis, Agassi found
legions of believers in his corner when he strode onto Centre
Court.
</P>
<P>
   If Lindsay Davenport could knock off Steffi Graf for the women's
title, Agassi could do likewise to Sampras. The pro-Agassi crowd
smelled another upset, especially when, at 3-3 in the first set,
Agassi got Sampras in a love-40 headlock. Tennis' consummate
counterpuncher had come out swinging. Sampras' response?
</P>
<P>
   Whack! Whack! Whack! Whack! Whaaack!
</P>
<P>
   Three break points saved, service held. Then, to prove he was
serious, Sampras broke Agassi in the next game, held for the first
set and began the second with another break. At love. After which
he really started smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the middle of the second set,'' Sampras said, ``I was on
fire. That was as well as I can play, plain and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From 3-3, 0-40,'' Agassi said, shaking his head, ``six minutes
later I was down 6-3, 1-0 and a break. That's how Pete plays.
You've got to weather his storm. When you do, that's when he's
vulnerable. I had my opportunities, but his storm was too strong
today. I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras conceded it was his most impressive effort in a long
while, for which he gave Agassi, the new No. 1-ranked player in the
world despite the outcome, much of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre brings out the best in me,'' he said. ``He elevates me
to a phenomenal level because I have so much respect for his game.
If I'm not at my best, it's a long day against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi is thought to have the best return of serve in the game,
but he had just one other break point in the match. Agassi got to
30-all six times, but as he said, ``If Pete didn't hit an ace on
the first serve, he'd hit his second one 109 (mph) or 111 and
sometimes 119 or 122.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taking chances out there, and people think he's walking
on water until he starts missing a few of those. But today he
walked on water.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras averaged 110 mph on his second serves yet had only five
double faults. He aced Agassi 17 times. It was a remarkable
performance at a most opportune juncture, particularly because his
tennis hadn't been overly inspired lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``My serve sort of carried me to the title, as it has before,''
he said. ``I haven't played great, but once I step on that Centre
Court this atmosphere, playing Andre, it brought out the best in
me. I was going to enjoy myself out there. Who knows how many times
I'll play Andre in a big final?''
</P>
<P>
   Until the Wimbledon tuneup at Queen's Club, Sampras had not won
a tournament all year, skipping the Australian and bombing out
early, as usual, at Roland Garros. Also, many believe he wouldn't
have survived the Philippoussis onslaught, if the hulking
Australian hadn't gone down with a knee injury shortly after
winning their first set.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win any Slam, you have to have some good fortune,'' Sampras
said. ``Maybe that was the turning point for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to reflect on the enormity of the moment and its historic
ramifications, Sampras politely declined. He said he hadn't
digested much yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still spinning,'' he said. ``It's going to hit me over the
next couple days. It's hard to explain how I'm feeling right now.''
</P>
<P>
   A word he could have used was ``unbeatable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
