<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS ARE NOT COMPLYING WITH OLD TENET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On their treadmill to maybe missing the National
League wild-card berth again, the Mets keep falling to the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday night's finale with the Atlanta Braves, the Mets
had not only already lost the three-game weekend series at Shea
Stadium, they had also been blanked in the two previous games, 16-0
and 3-0. No runs, not enough hits and another error: losing more
ground to the Braves in the N.L. East.
</P>
<P>
   That was typical of the Mets late last season, and has been
again this season, whenever there's an occasion to rise to.
</P>
<P>
   One of baseball's oldest tenets for a good team is to win each
regular-season series, no matter who the opponent is, good or bad.
That has been Joe Torre's philosophy in measuring the Yankees for
two World Series rings in his three seasons as manager, just as it
was Earl Weaver's philosophy years ago when the Orioles dominated
the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that from the master,'' Don Baylor, who played for
Weaver and is now the Braves' hitting coach, was saying Sunday
night. ``If you play four, win three. If you play three, win two.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a special value to, say, winning the first two
games of a three-game series, as the Braves did over the weekend.
With two in the bag, a manager can choose to rest a regular in the
third. Another factor: Some pressure is off the team that won the
first two, more pressure is on the team that lost the first two.
</P>
<P>
   In their struggle to justify themselves as wild-card contenders,
the Mets have yet to learn the trick of winning the series that
make a difference in the standing, the trick of rising to the
occasion. And until they learn it, they will never be a contender
for a wild-card spot, much less a challenger for the division
title.
</P>
<P>
   With a chance for a wild-card berth last September, the Mets
lost their final five games _ two in Montreal, three in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, just one victory would have lifted the Mets into
a three-way playoff with the Cubs and Giants (the Cubs won a
playoff with the Giants). Two triumphs in the Mets' last five games
would have meant the first wild-card playoff berth in the Mets'
history. But they lost all five games.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Mets have had three occasions to rise to, but
they slipped and fell each time.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, the Mets lost two to the Yankees before
salvaging the finale at Yankee Stadium, the first of 10 victories
in a span of 12 games before going to Atlanta for another occasion.
Yes, they won the opener of that series for 11 out of 13, narrowing
the Braves' division lead to two games, but they then lost the last
two games.
</P>
<P>
   After winning three of four in Florida, the Mets returned to
Shea for another occasion with the Braves, but fell flat.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mets' four-game series with the Expos, which begins
Monday night at Shea, another occasion awaits them _ the Yankees'
three-game visit to Shea, starting Friday. Winning at least two
from the Yankees would seem to be imperative if the Mets are to
develop any confidence in themselves for the next occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Winning all the games they're supposed to win against lesser
teams is fine, but if they are to rise in the wild-card race, they
must consistently rise to the occasion against the division leaders
and the other wild-card contenders.
</P>
<P>
   And against the Yankees next weekend, the Mets must rise to the
occasion with Armando Benitez as their closer now that John Franco,
the left-hander with 19 saves, is on the disabled list with an
inflamed tendon on his middle finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's no different,'' Benitez said before Sunday
night's game. ``Everybody knows what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Dominican right-hander has done, primarily as a setup
man for Franco, is appear in more games, 41 to 34, than Franco;
strike out 67 in 42 innings and earn three saves with a 1.50 ERA.
But his record is 0-2. ``For me, only the inning is different,''
said Benitez, the Orioles' closer last season. ``The ninth instead
of the eighth.''
</P>
<P>
   In their quest for the playoffs beyond the Yankee series, the
Mets must rise to at least 10 more occasions with division leaders
and wild-card contenders _ two series each with the Braves, Astros,
Pirates and Giants; one each with the Phillies and the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Mets hope to emerge as the wild-card winner, they
must win most of those series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
