<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-U.S.-BRAZIL-NYT &LR;      07-04 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-BRAZIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND SCURRY BEAT BRAZIL AT ITS OWN GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ They had played two games in four days,
connected by a coast-to-coast flight. And when Sunday's Women's
World Cup semifinal ended, the exhausted American players were left
sprawling in the locker room, backs aching, happy for the 2-0
victory over Brazil, even happier for five days to recover for the
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   If this was a largely uninspired match, it was understandable.
Both teams had played quarterfinal matches on Thursday in suburban
Washington and on Sunday they were battling jet lag as much as each
other.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Americans did not fully have their legs, they did
have the endurance of midfielder Michelle Akers and the composed
goalkeeping of Briana Scurry to forge a convincing victory before a
star-spangled Fourth of July crowd of 73,123 at Stanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The United States now advances to the World Cup final next
Saturday at the Rose Bowl against China, which defeated Norway by
5-0 in Sunday's other semifinal match in Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   China is fast and technically skilled and has defeated the
Americans twice in three matches this year. But the United States
can be encouraged by the resourcefulness of having won three
consecutive games without a goal from the world's career leading
scorer in international play, Mia Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   While Hamm appeared hesitant in one-on-one challenges on Sunday,
perhaps bothered by a nagging hamstring injury or a lapse of
confidence, she continued to run hard, to track back on defense and
to fire dangerous crosses into the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   And, with the Americans holding a tenuous 1-0 lead, she
cunningly produced a foul in the 80th minute, falling to the
ground, both hands extended like Superman about to save Metropolis,
after what appeared to be a less than vicious push by the Brazilian
defender Elane.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no necessity for the refereeing to be that bad,''
said Wilson Oliveira Rica, the Brazilian coach. ``The United States
is a great team. They didn't need that kind of help. If that was
Brazil inside the 18-yard box, it would not be called.''
</P>
<P>
   Volunteering for the penalty kick was Akers, the original star
of this team, the most valuable player of the 1991 World Cup, who
continues to show amazing stamina despite battling chronic fatigue
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Akers played the entire 90 minutes Sunday, clearing a dangerous
cross in the first half, tying up the Brazilian star Sissi in
midfield, staying on the field after a nasty collision left her
with a goose egg on the back of her head and shaking off a raking
cleat from Sissi that caught her in the face. Akers took a couple
of eight counts, but remained in the game both times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived with my chronic illness so long, I've learned to
stuff it,'' Akers said of her pain.
</P>
<P>
   In the 80th minute, captain Carla Overbeck played a goal kick to
midfield and Akers expertly headed it backward to a sprinting Hamm
on the left flank. When Hamm was taken down and the penalty kick
was awarded, Akers stood over the ball from 12 yards, like a
field-goal kicker waiting for the snap, took two confident steps
and punched the ball inside the right post for a 2-0 American lead
that finally provided security on an uncertain afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `Yeah, baby, give me that,''' said Akers, who also
scored a crucial penalty kick during the 1996 Summer Olympics.
``Those are the moments you live for. It's a scenario I've been
practicing every day for the last couple of months. The only thing
on my mind was `Where do I put it?'''
</P>
<P>
   The American defense had been instructed by coach Tony DiCicco
not to commit fouls near the penalty area, thus depriving Sissi,
the World Cup's leading scorer with seven goals, of her specialty _
the free kick. ``She was my girl,'' Akers said. ``I wasn't going to
let her score.''
</P>
<P>
   When Brazil did breach the penalty area, Scurry fended it off
with gymnastic goalkeeping, pitching her third shutout in five
World Cup matches and 52nd career shutout in 95 international
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``She proved she's the best keeper in the World Cup,'' DiCicco
said.
</P>
<P>
   Scurry punched away a point-blank shot in the 30th minute,
pushed a floater over the crossbar in the 46th minute and laid
herself out like a shortstop 10 minutes later, making a diving save
of a low blast by Nene. Afterward, her teammates sprinted toward
her and jumped into her arms in appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be the best game I ever played,'' Scurry said.
``Any game when I can do my part and get my team into the final of
the World Cup is my best game.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco had considered benching forward Cindy Parlow in favor of
the more vibrant Shannon MacMillan, but he resisted, and on Sunday
his decision paid off.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans scored an early goal, instead of giving one up, as
they had in previous games. In the fifth minute, Julie Foudy lifted
a cross from the left flank that was fumbled by Maravilha, the
Brazilian goalkeeper. It is a vulnerability the Americans had
spotted in previous matches. Parlow charged the goal, and before
the ball could hit the ground, she flicked it with her head into
the net for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it gave our whole team confidence,'' Parlow said. ``We
had been behind in the early part of two games. Getting ahead early
gave us confidence and let us relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Relaxing is exactly what the fatigued American players plan to
do in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play better,'' Hamm said. ``This is not the type of
game we wanted to play, but it got the job done. In the final, we
have to play our best. That's as simple as I can make it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
