<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   It was late at night after a disappointing Yankees loss, and an
emotionally charged crowd poured onto a downtown No. 4 train. A
woman who had been on the train before the fans filled it, upset at
the sudden influx of people, exclaimed, ``It's like a herd of
animals in here!''
</P>
<P>
   Within a matter of seconds, the entire car of about 100 riders
burst into a cacophony of moos, neighs, oinks, baas,
cock-a-doodle-doos and any other farm-animal sound imaginable. This
went on for about 30 seconds. The fans' stress had been released,
and the woman had learned a lesson: Don't mess with Yankees fans.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBERT BRUCKHEIMER
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   My friend Kevin and I were strolling down Madison Avenue on a
lovely warm Sunday evening. The city was exceptionally peaceful,
and he and I were quietly shopping and enjoying the last precious
hours of the weekend. We were facing downtown, with our backs to
the setting sun. Suddenly we heard ``Excuse me,'' and turning
around, we saw a handsome, well-dressed middle-aged man. ``Yes,''
we replied, probably sounding a little confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you happen to notice the beautiful sky behind you?'' he
asked. ``It's amazing, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   We looked up Madison and saw the illuminated orange-red-purple
sky. It was simply lovely. The three of us stood for a moment, just
admiring the view, and then he broke the silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky was so beautiful, I just wanted to share it with
somebody,'' he said. ``Enjoy the rest of your evening.''
</P>
<P>
   We thanked him, looked at each other, smiled and continued our
strolling. The lovely man said it all. New Yorkers are wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   _ KRISTINE GITELSONE
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Shapiro and Alan Kornfield, two former New Yorkers, were
standing in front of a subway station and asked an emerging elderly
woman about the Metrocard, which had been introduced after their
time. She answered their questions graciously; they thanked her and
then told her they were from Florida. ``That's your problem,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Montague Street in Brooklyn Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Observer: Leslie A. Friedlieb.
</P>
<P>
   Players: A man and a woman, probably in their 30s, who
apparently have not seen each other in some time. They spot each
other in the crowd and, with broad grins on their faces, exchange
hugs.
</P>
<P>
   He: ``How are you?''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``My, how long has it been?''
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Too long.''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``What's new?''
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Same old thing.''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``Me too.''
</P>
<P>
   They part and go their separate ways without exchanging another
word.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   An article in a recent issue of The New York Times about a
hairdresser who was accused of discriminating because he refused to
cut the hair of older women brought back memories of an experience
with that same hairdresser.
</P>
<P>
   I had an appointment to meet my husband, and my hair definitely
needed work. A young colleague told me of ``a great hairdresser''
who was a bargain as well. I made an appointment. I was greeted at
the door with the question ``Didn't you know that I don't cut the
hair of anyone over 25?''
</P>
<P>
   I was ready to walk, but it was a really bad hair day, so I
said, ``Well, you can make me look 25 years younger.'' He cut my
hair.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I told my 27-year-old daughter what I had done, and I
knew she would say: ``Mom, how could you? You should have reported
him.'' She did say that, and then paused. ``But was it a good
cut?'' she asked. ``Maybe I'll go to him first.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MARSHA SCHORR
</P>
<P>
   Marvin J. Levy, who now lives on the West Coast, remembers that
when he lived in New York about 25 years ago, he entered a building
on Park Avenue, the site of a Jaguar showroom. At the bank of
elevators in the lobby, he saw his first indication of the trend
toward upwardly mobile euphemisms: The man overseeing the ups and
downs proudly wore a uniform emblazoned with the title Floor
Director.
</P>
<P>
   A BRIEF ROMANCE
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bennett left his heart in San Francisco, the city by the
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   I left mine in New York City, on a trip that took my breath
away.
</P>
<P>
   From the right-field bleachers we watched the heroic Bronx
Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   In Central Park I gazed in her beautiful eyes, they were quite
the charmers.
</P>
<P>
   Chinatown is where we had a wonderful meal.
</P>
<P>
   Were my experiences a dream or were they real?
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway we saw Ragtime, it was really quite a show.
</P>
<P>
   Was it true love in the air, I may never know.
</P>
<P>
   You see, she claims the distance between us is too vast.
</P>
<P>
   Silly me, and I thought our love would last.
</P>
<P>
   _ DANIEL KATZ, Colorado Springs
</P>
<P>
   David Stiles' 6-year-old nephew, Nick Trusty, was walking to
school with his mother when they saw a dead bird on the sidewalk.
They stopped to look but his mother reminded Nick that they had to
get going to get to school in time. He wanted to stay only a
minute, Nick said. ``I want to pay my respects to the bird.''
</P>
<P>
   He slowly put his hand to his chest, looked up to the sky and
solemnly recited: ``I pledge my allegiance to this flag and to the
United States ...''
</P>
<P>
   ODE TO AN ABSENT SON
</P>
<P>
   My son is a magician
</P>
<P>
   As I will make quite clear.
</P>
<P>
   If I provide the air fare
</P>
<P>
   He can make himself appear.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANONYMOUS
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Consider the street banana. Grown in a tropical paradise amid
chattering birds and baby monkeys at play, it has traveled
thousands of miles over land and sea. On trucks, boats and trains
it has ridden, handled by scores of people; yet its skin is
unblemished, its fruit still sweet. You give the man a quarter. He
gives you a banana. No change. No receipt. No bag. A transaction
direct from the agora. A journey through space and time.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANN BURACK-WEISS
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Gross still remembers a sign he saw posted on public
property in North Hempstead. It warned, ``No Trespassing Until
Further Notice.'' Gross said it disappeared a few years ago, and he
still wonders whether it was because of embarrassment or the
lifting of an embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Levin was in her doctor's waiting room when she overheard
two elderly women.
</P>
<P>
   One said, ``Did you see the article about the thousands of
viruses spread through computers?''
</P>
<P>
   The other said: ``I saw it. I can't believe people use them.
They are so dangerous. How do you think they get all those
viruses?''
</P>
<P>
   The first woman replied, ``I don't know, but I bet it has
something to do with people not washing their hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-99 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
