<DOCNO> NYT19990704.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT &LR;      07-04 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME'S CLOSE LOOK AT CORPORATE TAX BENEFITS  
 TNN JUMPS INTO THE RING  
 RETURN TO SAVANNAH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least no one can say there was no warning. Last November, in
the first part of an award-winning series on corporate tax benefits
by Donald Barlett and James Steele, Time Magazine published a
related article about various tax benefits that were granted to its
parent corporation, Time Warner Inc. The article, detailing tax
breaks worth about $2.4 million, ran under the headline ``We Play
the Game Too.''
</P>
<P>
   And play it and play it. New York City's government last week
gave Time Warner its second windfall of the year. This one was
worth $28 million and specifically benefits the company's
publishing division, which is expanding and renovating its offices
on the Avenue of the Americas between West 50th and 51st Streets.
Earlier this year, City Hall granted an $11 million tax break to
HBO, another Time Warner division, when it said it would renew its
lease at West 42nd Street and Avenue of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Steele does not seem to be raising eyebrows at the deal. Asked
about the practice-what-you-preach aspects of the situation, he
said, ``The point we made in the series was that, as long as
governments are making these available, corporations will seek
them. Until an overall policy exists, in which one state can't raid
another's jobs or one city can't raid another, this is going to go
on.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the most important thing a media corporation has
to do is ``at least write about these things.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's managing editor, Walter Isaacson, said, ``I think
corporate welfare is silly in all its guises.'' He added: ``We
write about the corporation. We don't speak for the corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Costiglio, who does speak for Time Inc., said of the tax
breaks, ``The executives who run the company try always to act in
the best interest of the company _ this would be a case of that.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of other media companies have received tax benefits in
the city in recent years, including New York Times Co., News Corp.,
Bertelsmann AG, Viacom Inc. and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   More Mock Mayhem
</P>
<P>
   How much more popular can professional wrestling get? A
mainstream (if audience-starved) broadcast network, UPN, has
already decided to embrace the mock mayhem on Thursday nights in
the fall, scheduling two hours of ``WWF Smackdown.'' Now elbowing
its way into the fray is TNN, the Nashville Network, which last
week announced a three-year deal with an outfit called Extreme
Championship Wrestling for an hourlong show on Friday nights.
</P>
<P>
   TNN may be the network of ``Grand Ol' Opry,'' rodeo and fishing
shows, but it also has NASCAR automobile races and ``Rollerjam,'' a
late-'90s version of Roller Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have dual audiences, basically female Monday to Thursday,
and basically male on weekends,'' said David Hall, president of TNN
and CMT, Country Music Television, both owned by CBS Cable. ``With
`Rollerjam' on Friday nights, we found we could attract a young
male audience, and they'd hang around for `Motor Madness,' which is
tractors and trucks and stuff like that,'' at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   That young male audience _ so particularly desired by
advertisers _ is driving the wrestling phenomenon. But it is not
for men only. The World Wrestling Federation's two Monday-night
hours on the USA Network earned 26 of the top 30 rankings on the
Nielsen list of most-watched shows among all basic cable networks
for the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On its lowest-rated night, the WWF show attracted 4.1 million
households; on its highest, 6.4 million households tuned in. And
the competition, TNT's ``WCW Monday Nitro Live,'' draws between 2.7
million and 3.5 million households each Monday, as well.
</P>
<P>
   USA Network also has a Sunday-night show. Now UPN is adding its
Thursday show, and TNN a Friday show.
</P>
<P>
   If the WWF and WCW are the major leagues of wrestling, ECW is a
sort of Triple-A league, staging live wrestling events in small
arenas and televising a handful each year on a pay-per-view basis.
It has a reputation for being a training ground for WWF and WCW
performers _ and for encouraging even wilder physical violence.
</P>
<P>
   The TNN show starts on Aug. 27 and will run at 8 p.m. Fridays,
preceding ``Rollerjam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the not-very-pleasant stuff going on outside the ring
will not be part of our show,'' Hall said, ``because this ECW is
such an athletic approach to wrestling, your story lines don't have
to get into whose dating who.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   City's Mystique Seduces a Publisher Again
</P>
<P>
   The Southern charm of Savannah, Ga. _ a crucial character in the
best seller ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' _ has
seduced a New York publisher once again. St. Martin's Press is
paying a six-figure advance for a previously published first novel
set in the balmy coastal city by a native son who tirelessly
promoted his work with Rotary Club appearances and articles in
``Podiatry Today.''
</P>
<P>
   William Harris Jr., a podiatrist for almost 25 years and the son
of a former sheriff of Chatham County, Ga., is the first to
acknowledge that the early success for ``Delirium of the Brave''
comes on the pages of a perennial best seller known simply in
Savannah as The Book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that there's any denying that `Midnight in the
Garden of Good and Evil' has put such a spotlight on Savannah and
that because of that any book of this caliber would stir up some
interest,'' said Harris, 52, in a telephone interview from his
medical office in Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delirium,'' which was originally published by a small Savannah
publisher, Frederic Beil, is a Southern saga that follows four
generations of an Irish-Catholic family and a black family through
their clashes with the Chatham County power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Like John Berendt's ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,''
the plot pivots on a murder of a homosexual _ in this case a serial
killer who distributes body parts in brown paper bags.
</P>
<P>
   But while Midnight was a nonfiction work that stretched the
facts in fictional ways, ``Delirium'' is billed as fiction with
firm roots in factual events, including the crimes of a paper bag
murderer who was captured in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Since the book was published last fall, the title has sold more
than 5,000 copies locally, which eventually attracted the interest
of an agent and large publishers who bid for the book in an auction
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' new literary agent, Nancy Stauffer, said the writer
himself could be a Flannery O'Connor character. At the age of 19,
Harris stepped on a downed power line, and his legs had to be
amputated.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal with St. Martin's, which is owned by
Holtzbrinck GmbH, Harris is planning on writing a sequel to
``Delirium.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the foreseeable future his shingle will stay up in
Savannah while the fiction takes shape at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't quitting my day job real soon,'' joked Harris. ``But
who knows.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
</TEXT>
