<HEADLINE>
CHINESE WOMEN ROUT NORWAY, 5-0; WILL PLAY U.S. FOR TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ The Chinese sent a clear message to the
Americans Sunday night with a 5-0 rout of Norway that sends them
into the championship game of the Women's World Cup against the
United States. The Chinese were vastly superior in all aspects of
the game in eliminating Norway, the defending World Cup champion,
and ending its 10-game winning streak in the tournament, going back
to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   China has defeated the Americans twice this year, in Portugal in
March and in New Jersey in April. Coach Per-Mathias Hogmo of Norway
was so impressed by the Chinese after Sunday night's game that he
called them the best team in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ma Yuanan of China refused to make his team the favorite
against the Americans in Saturday's championship game, even after
Sunday night's remarkable performance. He was very careful in his
choice of words and said he hoped his team would play against the
Americans at the level it did on April 25, referring to China's 2-1
victory in a friendly at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will take one step at a time,'' Ma said, when asked about
his strategy for the game against the Americans in the Rose Bowl.
``But this is the best China has played in recent games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese came to the tournament with a high motivation to
reach the championship game after they were eliminated by Sweden in
the quarterfinals in the first Women's World Cup, in 1991 in China,
and then lost in the semifinals to Germany in 1995 in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest motivating factor for us is the solidarity and the
united effort of the team,'' Liu Ailing, who scored two goals, said
through an interpreter after the game when she acted as the team
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Wen also had two goals, with Fan Yunjie getting the other
goal. Sun's two goals gave her seven for the tournament and tied
her for the most goals with Brazil's Sissi. Sun has a chance to
capture the golden boot as the tournament's leading scorer in the
clash against the Americans in the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   China's play was flawless, especially on attack. The Chinese
front runners of Sun and Jin Yan were a constant threat. With help
from Liu, playing slightly behind the two strikers, the Chinese
showed plenty of variety in their play, often changing the point of
attack to exploit weaknesses in Norway's defense.
</P>
<P>
   The first goal, three minutes after the opening kickoff, came on
a left-footed shot by Sun from near the penalty spot after Jin's
shot was knocked down by Bente Nordby, the goalkeeper. The goal was
the culmination of a play that developed on the left side of the
attack with a precision pass into the middle by Liu.
</P>
<P>
   China's second goal came in the 14th minute on a blistering shot
by Liu to the upper right corner from the arc on top of the penalty
area after a play that started with a corner kick from the right
side.
</P>
<P>
   Sun and Liu Ying had marvelous opportunities to extend China's
lead, but their shots sailed over the bar from good position inside
the penalty area. It was the goalkeeping of Nordby that kept the
Norwegians within 2-0 at the half. There was little Nordby could do
on Liu Ailing's goal, in the 51st minute, when Liu collected a
loose ball after a corner kick from the left and rocketed a
left-footed shot from 13 yards.
</P>
<P>
   China's three goals in 51 minutes equaled the total Norway had
allowed in four games before Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   China's rendezvous with the Americans was secured in the 65th
minute, when Fan sprinted all the way from her defensive position
to get behind Norway's defense to put China ahead by 4-0 from close
range. Sun scored her second of the night, on a penalty kick in the
72nd minute.
</P>
<P>
   Hogmo tried everything, even replacing a couple of key players
whom the Chinese had neutralized, but nothing worked. The
Norwegians had two decent opportunities after China's third goal,
but Gao Hong, the Chinese goalkeeper, showed tremendous quickness
in recording the shutout.
</P>
</TEXT>
