<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS LOSES HIS ZIP, AND YANKEES GET ZAPPED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Scientists have documented global warming in this
century, but nobody needed to tell the Texan Roger Clemens that it
was panhandle-hot at Yankee Stadium on Sunday. Clemens returned to
the Yankees' dugout after pitching another inning in the thick heat
and said drolly, ``I think they just dumped a pail of water on the
rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' sauna analogy was appropriate. The humidity was
stifling and the temperature was 89 degrees when the game started,
and when the sun came out in the early innings, players and umpires
baked.
</P>
<P>
   But even after a devastating week of blown victories, and in the
throes of a losing streak that has likely choked off their playoff
aspirations, the Orioles did not wilt. B.J. Surhoff launched a
grand slam off Ramiro Mendoza to cap a six-run rally in the seventh
inning as the Orioles beat the Yankees, 7-3, before 37,046.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff is a candidate for the American League All-Star team
that will be filled out with reserves picked, in part, by Yankee
manager Joe Torre. Maybe Surhoff's All-Star chances would have been
better, Torre joked later, if he had ``hit into a double play.''
Baltimore's victory was its first after 10 consecutive losses.
</P>
<P>
   Making his 14th start for the Yankees, Clemens returned to the
air-conditioned clubhouse after each half-inning, changed his shirt
and drank water and other liquids to keep himself hydrated.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Orioles' hitters battled him and extended the
counts in the early innings, Clemens was doomed to an early
departure; it was just too hot to expect anyone to last long with
that workload, Torre mused later.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens threw 83 pitches in the first four innings, more than 20
pitches per inning. When Clemens breezed through the middle of the
Baltimore lineup in the sixth while needing only seven pitches, the
Yankees' coaching staff hoped Clemens might be able to pitch into
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees leading, 3-1, Jeff Conine doubled to open the
Orioles' seventh, and Clemens hustled to back up third for a
possible play there. Whew. Cal Ripken hit Clemens' next pitch into
short center field for another hit, and Clemens moved to back up
home plate as Conine scored. Whew.
</P>
<P>
   Those two short sprints, coupled with his mounting pitch count,
sucked the breath out of Clemens, and catcher Jorge Posada and the
pitching coach, Mel Stottlemyre, went to the mound and lingered,
giving Clemens a chance to recover.
</P>
<P>
   But there was not enough time. After the rookie Jerry Hairston
flied to deep left, Torre replaced Clemens with Mendoza. ``The
pitch count,'' Torre said, ``was as much of an issue as the heat
was for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The first batter Mendoza faced was Mike Figga, the reserve
catcher who was placed on waivers by the Yankees last month without
having taken an at-bat for them this year. Mendoza's first
sinkerball to Figga did not sink, and Figga banged it over the head
of center fielder Bernie Williams; Ripken stopped at third.
</P>
<P>
   After Brady Anderson was walked intentionally, Mike Bordick
singled to right, scoring Ripken with the tying run. Mendoza threw
a fastball for ball one to Surhoff, then came back with a changeup,
and Surhoff reached out, his weight on his front foot, and flicked
his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Torre thought Surhoff's fly ball to right would be caught for a
sacrifice fly. Mendoza was sure of this, too, as was Derek Jeter.
But the ball kept going, and Paul O'Neill, the Yankees' right
fielder, reached for the wall and looked up _ grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   As Surhoff rounded the bases, the third base umpire, Larry
Barnett, moved to check on the condition of the home-plate umpire,
Greg Kosc, and Barnett called for the Yankees' trainer, Gene
Monahan. Kosc had been sweating a lot all day _ the front of his
shirt and pants were soaked _ and early in the game he had begun
curling cold towels around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   When Monahan reached Kosc, he waved smelling salts under the
umpire's nose; Kosc's head bobbed, his eyes bulged, his face was
pale, and soon Kosc's arms dangled over the shoulders of Barnett
and Monahan, like a human yoke, and he was led off the field.
</P>
<P>
   He was hospitalized for heat exhaustion and dehydration and was
replaced behind home plate by the second-base umpire, Ed Hickox.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Yankees had been griping openly with Kosc on his
ball-and-strike calls in the previous two innings, particularly
Posada, who seethed after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Posada said that after he was called out on strikes by Kosc in
the sixth, he turned to the umpire and told him he was being
inconsistent with his strike zone. ``He hasn't called it all day,
and all of a sudden, he's going to expand it because it's hot,''
said Posada, before expanding the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line, the guys are not in shape,'' Posada
continued, referring to umpires. ``It was hot _ I can understand
it's hot. You've got to be able to go through the game. They're not
prepared, they're not in shape; it's a shame. He gets hot, the zone
gets bigger. One doesn't go with the other one.''
</P>
<P>
   The American League president, Gene Budig, who watched the game
on television at his New Jersey home, said of Kosc: ``Greg passed
the required physical examination. He is a weight lifter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
