<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-SPEEDLIMIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FASTER, BUT IS IT DEADLIER? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you are lucky enough on this holiday to find
yourself in traffic moving more than 55 mph, you might contemplate
a surprising fact: You are not dead.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be a surprise to you, but it is to some people in
Washington who consider themselves experts on highway safety. In
1995, when Congress voted to repeal the national 55-mph speed
limit, they predicted carnage on the roads.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Claybrook, the president of Public Citizen, an advocacy
group, called the bill ``a death sentence to thousands of
Americans.'' As President Clinton prepared to sign the bill, the
consumer advocate Ralph Nader prophesied, ``History will never
forgive him and his allies in Congress for this assault on the
sanctity of human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Stone, president of the Advocates for Highway and Auto
Safety, went on the NBC program ``Today'' to predict ``6,400 added
highway fatalities a year and millions of more injuries.'' That
figure of 6,400 more deaths each year, which Ms. Stone's group took
from a worst-case estimate of a Department of Transportation study,
was repeatedly cited by journalists and dozens of advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, the massacre has been avoided. Driving has
actually become safer despite the higher speed limits adopted in
most states. In 1995, the final year of the national speed limit,
41,817 people died on American roads; last year there were 337
fewer deaths, even though Americans drove more miles. The fatality
rate per mile has declined 11 percent since 1995, and is now at an
all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   The national speed limit, imposed in 1974 to conserve energy,
never saved much oil but survived thanks to claims that it saved
lives. After being modified in 1987 to allow 65-mph speeds on some
rural freeways, it was eliminated by the 1995 law allowing the
states to set their own limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety and consumer groups warned us in 1995 that there'd
be blood on the highway and soaring premiums for car insurance,''
said Stephen Moore, the director of fiscal studies at the Cato
Institute, a libertarian policy group. ``But since then the
fatality rate has dropped steadily, and insurance premiums have
actually fallen, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The prophets now say they were misunderstood. ``We were
predicting a worst-case scenario,'' Ms. Stone said, ``if all the
states changed their laws on all the potential roads, including the
dangerous secondary roads. Fortunately, most states didn't do
that.'' That's true _ but then there was never any reason to assume
that the entire country would become stupidly reckless.
</P>
<P>
   Local politicians (and local drivers) generally know a little
about local road conditions. Even without guidance from the experts
in Washington, legislators in northeastern states figured out that
the 70- and 75-mph limits set in places like Wyoming might not work
in congested urban areas. In New York, New Jersey and Connecticut,
the top speed limit is 65, and it applies on only a few highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prediction of 6,400 deaths was never very realistic,''
said Julie Rochman, the spokeswoman for the Insurance Institute for
Highway Safety, which recently analyzed accident rates on the roads
where the speed limit was raised. It concluded that the higher
limits led to a higher fatality rate resulting in about 500
additional deaths per year.
</P>
<P>
   Even that estimate may be too high, according to Moore's new
study for the Cato Institute. He found that the overall highway
fatality rate has been declining nearly as fast in states with
raised speed limits as in states with unchanged limits. How, if
there are extra deaths on the higher-speed roads, could the overall
death toll still be falling in those states?
</P>
<P>
   One possible explanation is that extra deaths are more than
offset by the lives saved by other safety measures like seat belts,
air bags, better-engineered cars and laws against drunken driving.
But Moore prefers another explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can go 70 or 75 miles an hour on an Interstate,'' he
said, ``you're more likely to take it than a secondary road that's
a shorter route. So even if a few more people die on the
Interstates because of higher speeds, there are fewer deaths
overall because drivers are being diverted from two-lane roads to
much safer six-lane roads.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if you assume the worst, that the higher speed limits
are killing a few hundred Americans annually, those losses have to
be balanced against the time that drivers are saving: 400 million
hours annually, by Moore's calculations, which works out to about
600 lifetimes spent outside a car. That might not seem like a bad
bargain, especially to anyone sitting in traffic today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-99 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
