<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990704.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9306 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     07-04 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ It might be a final spasm, the last gasp from
a dying patient.
</P>
<P>
   American tennis isn't healed, by any means, certainly when you
see how bereft of future male champions our junior ranks appear.
But for one golden throwback summer, at least, tennis is strolling
proudly through the garden again, taking the sun.
</P>
<P>
   For now, golf is the straggler, tagging along well to the rear.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Maria Olazabal's winning another Masters and Payne
Stewart's winning another U.S. Open _ I don't care how dramatically
he did it _ do not compare to Andre Agassi coming from two sets
down in the French Open final, then having Agassi go
Swoosh-on-Swoosh against Pete Sampras in a Yankee Doodle dandy of a
Fourth of July Wimbledon crescendo.
</P>
<P>
   True, the match proved a tad anticlimactic, a one-horse race.
Sampras, inarguably the King of Centre Court, had too much serve
for Agassi's vaunted return. Hence, he won his sixth Wimbledon in
seven years with a brutally efficient straight-sets victory that
made a mockery of Agassi's computer glitch of a No. 1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel very much like No. 1 right now,'' Andre said
sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   The Independence Day fireworks he had promised amounted, on his
part, to no more than a sparkler or two, but watching Sampras'
unabashed 6-3, 6-4, 7-5 excellence rewarded would be enough of a
thrill by its lonesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have played any better,'' Sampras said, saying a
lot. ``That's probably the best I've played in many years. I mean,
plain and simple, I was hitting the ball clean from the backcourt
and serving big at all the right times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre brings out the best in me. No question, he elevates my
game to a phenomenal level.''
</P>
<P>
   A word that also describes his career achievements. Pistol
Pete's 12th Grand Slam title tied Roy Emerson's all-time record.
Sampras' Wimbledon total stands unmatched during the modern era,
which is the only era worth noting.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with Lindsay Davenport's women's championship, ending
Steffi Graf's for-the-ages Wimbledon career, it made for as
smashing (pardon the pun) a day in tennis as the United States has
experienced in at least 15 years, or since John McEnroe and Martina
Navratilova last pulled off the same all-American sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Factor in the guaranteed rowdy, rip-roaring U.S.-Australia Davis
Cup tie at historic Longwood in a couple of weeks, an affair that
commemorates the 100th anniversary of the competition and pairs the
two nations with the proudest Cup traditions, and you have a tennis
interlude for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   A zenith, even. The age of McEnroe, Connors and Borg never
produced a more concentrated dose of high-drama, high-octane tennis
than we've seen since Agassi began his entrancing, unexpected run
through Roland Garros. In Paris, he completed the first career Slam
since Emerson in the mid-1960s joined the exclusive company of Fred
Perry, Don Budge and Rod Laver.
</P>
<P>
   With Andre, now there are five of them.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this explosion of history-making will have kids _ never
mind their paunchy, aging baby-boomer parents _ streaming from
their houses, rackets in hand, to create another tennis power surge
remains to be seen. But the sport has at least regained a toehold
in the American consciousness after interest levels had ebbed to
distressing lows, certainly in regard to the dreary,
European-dominated _ Sampras excepted _ men's game.
</P>
<P>
   Yevgeny Kafelnikov, Carlos Moya and Marcelo Rios, three
pretenders who have intruded of late on Pete's mountaintop turf,
are virtually unknown to Bubba on Main Street. Even Boris Becker
and Stefan Edberg before them, although huge talents, captured at
best cult followings as tennis drifted into minor-sport territory,
closer to cricket and curling than to basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Yet I'm told people in bars Saturday night were arguing the
relative merits of the Sampras serve vs. the Agassi return, and
debating the two Yanks' merits as athletes and entertainers.
Everybody loves a showdown, a high-noon shootout between two
superstar gunslingers, something golf is ill-designed to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   And rarely does.
</P>
<P>
   Golf will need Tiger Woods and David Duval to be even turning
the corner in the final twosome at the British Open at Carnoustie
or the PGA at Medinah to equal what Wimbledon gave us Sunday with
the whopper one-two punch of Sampras-Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Graf-Davenport, not to slight the women, made for a formidable
undercard, too. Everywhere we turned, history was sprouting. Will
it help launch an all-out renaissance?
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know,'' Sampras said, ``is this was one great day for
American tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the greatest.
</P>
</TEXT>
